('downfield', 'Downfield', 'https://downfield.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/downfield#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'No', 56.490338, -3.031331, 0, 0, '', '', 'downfield', 7518, 'downfield', 1, 0, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000cdcea2772a4008c037fe4465c33e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Often overshadowed by the coastal giants of nearby St Andrews and Carnoustie, Downfield Golf Club in Dundee is a masterclass in parkland design. Originally established in 1895, the course underwent a significant evolution in 1932 under the vision of the legendary James Braid, before being refined by C.K. Cotton in 1964. The result is a lush, tree-lined sanctuary that feels worlds away from the windswept dunes of the coast. With more than 100 species of trees framing its fairways and water coming into play on seven holes, the course is as visually stunning as it is strategically demanding.\r\n\r\nThe club holds a unique place in professional golf history as the host of the inaugural Scottish Open in 1972, won by Neil Coles. However, its most famous historical footnote came in 1999, when a young Paul Lawrie battled through the Open Qualifying rounds at Downfield before going on to lift the Claret Jug at Carnoustie just days later. Lawrie remains an honorary member today and has described the layout as \"one of the finest inland courses in Britain.\"\r\n\r\nThe experience here is defined by precision over power. The par-3 12th, affectionately (or perhaps fearfully) named \"Davy Jones\'s Locker\" is a signature test requiring a carry over a meandering stream to a heavily guarded green. While the sceneryfrequently shared with local deer, red squirrels, and buzzardsis tranquil, the championship-length layout ensures a rigorous test that has earned the respect of greats like Peter Thomson and Sam Torrance.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/R4s7N0UjBPw?si=Lao_MRMH9CLJthPh'),
