('dullatura', 'Dullatur - Antonine', 'https://dullatur.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'clubv1', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.960964, -4.019928, 8843, 0, '', '', 'dullatur', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000048197101681410c011514cde00fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dullatur  Antonine, also near Cumbernauld, offers a contrasting parkland test to Carrickstone. Measuring approximately 6,100 yards with a par of 71, it features tree-lined fairways, gentle undulations, and strategic bunkering.\r\n\r\nNotable holes include the par-4 10th, which rewards precise driving, and the finishing par-5 18th, offering risk-reward decisions into a well-protected green. Antonine hosts a variety of local competitions and society days, fostering an active golfing community.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse overlooks the course and provides hospitality, making it ideal for visitors and members alike. Dullatur  Antonine blends classic Scottish parkland characteristics with accessibility and challenge for all levels.\r\n', ''),
('Dumbarnie', 'Dumbarnie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumbarnie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumbarnie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'No', 56.209127, -2.887510, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'Dumbarnie', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000d2fbc6d79e1907c0f5da6cacc41a4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Dumbarnie Golf Club, located near Fife, is a links-style course that combines scenic coastal views with strategic design. The layout measures around 6,200 yards with a par of 71, offering natural dunes, firm fairways, and small, challenging greens.\r\n\r\nHoles like the par-4 12th and par-5 15th reward creative shot-making and careful navigation of natural hazards. Dumbarnie has a strong amateur and society event schedule, emphasizing accessibility and enjoyable play.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides stunning views over the Firth of Forth and coastal surroundings. Dumbarnie exemplifies the charm of Scottish seaside golf: strategic, scenic, and authentic, with a relaxed atmosphere for players of all levels.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/RSUYXI4Cr4w?si=T4MlSZxvN7_v64RF'),
('dumbarton', 'Dumbarton', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumbarton#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.953997, -4.570354, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1029, 'dumbarton', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000369204e10a4812c0b6bddd921cfa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumbarton Golf Club, near Glasgow, is a mature parkland course dating back to 1895. Measuring roughly 6,000 yards with a par of 70, it offers tree-lined fairways, strategically placed bunkers, and subtle green undulations.\r\n\r\nThe par-4 9th and par-5 17th are notable holes, demanding accurate tee shots and thoughtful approaches. Dumbarton hosts a strong schedule of local competitions, society days, and amateur events, fostering a welcoming golfing community.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and panoramic views over key holes. Dumbarton exemplifies classic inland Scottish parkland golf: accessible, strategic, and steeped in local tradition.', ''),
('dumfriesandcounty', 'Dumfries and County', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandcounty#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandcounty#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.080560, -3.601510, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dumfriesandcounty', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000056bc9179e4cf0cc0d1ae42ca4f8a4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumfries and County Golf Club, in Dumfries, is a parkland course established in 1885, featuring 18 holes across rolling countryside. Playing around 6,100 yards with a par of 71, it combines strategic challenges with scenic beauty.\r\n\r\nThe course includes tree-lined fairways, water hazards, and subtle elevation changes, with holes like the par-4 10th and par-5 18th testing accuracy and decision-making. Dumfries and County hosts local competitions and society days, maintaining a vibrant amateur golf scene.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers a welcoming social environment. The course represents classic Scottish parkland tradition, balancing strategic golf with natural beauty in southwest Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('dumfriesandgalloway', 'Dumfries and Galloway', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandgalloway#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dumfriesandgalloway#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.065340, -3.626200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dumfriesandgalloway', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a60a462575020dc0718fa50f5d884b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dumfries and Galloway Golf Club, near Dumfries, is a historic parkland course dating to 1882. It plays roughly 6,200 yards with a par of 70, featuring mature trees, strategic bunkering, and subtly contoured greens.\r\n\r\nKey holes include the par-3 6th and par-4 16th, requiring precision and careful course management. The club hosts local competitions, society days, and amateur championships.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and a social hub for members and visitors. This course blends tradition, challenge, and scenic parkland surroundings, representing the best of inland Scottish golf.', ''),
('Dunaverty', 'Dunaverty', 'https://www.dunavertygolfclub.com/index.htm', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.312679, -5.644815, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000087e123624a9416c0b0928fdd05a84b40, 'links', 'No', 'Dunaverty Golf Club, located on the Kintyre Peninsula, is a charming 9-hole course set amid scenic coastal and Highland surroundings. While modest in size, measuring roughly 2,700 yards for 9 holes (or 5,400 yards if played twice for a full 18), it offers a strategic and enjoyable challenge for golfers of all abilities.\r\n\r\nThe course combines gently undulating fairways, natural hazards, and mature trees, creating variety despite its shorter layout. Holes such as the par-3 4th and par-5 7th stand out, requiring precise tee shots and careful approaches to navigate bunkers and sloping greens. The design emphasizes accuracy and thoughtful course management over sheer distance, making it ideal for both beginners and experienced golfers seeking a tactical test.\r\n\r\nDunaverty maintains a strong local club culture, hosting amateur competitions, society days, and friendly inter-club matches. The clubhouse provides a welcoming environment, with views across the course and surrounding countryside.\r\n\r\nWhat sets Dunaverty apart is its natural beauty and peaceful location: golfers often enjoy panoramic views of Kintyre hills and the nearby coastline. Though smaller than many Scottish courses, it delivers an authentic and rewarding inland parkland experience, reflecting the charm and community spirit of Scotland\'s smaller clubs.', ''),
('dunbar', 'Dunbar', 'https://www.dunbargolfclub.com/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.997828, -2.499275, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.dunbargolfclub.com', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000e6ae25e483fe03c03c84f1d3b8ff4b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Dunbar Golf Club, in East Lothian, is a celebrated links course designed by Tom Morris in the late 19th century. Stretching around 6,400 yards with a par of 70, it features undulating fairways, deep bunkers, and firm greens, all set against dramatic views of the North Sea.\r\n\r\nThe course is strategic in nature, requiring precise shot-making and careful consideration of coastal winds. Signature holes include the par-4 12th, which demands accuracy off the tee, and the par-5 17th, offering a risk-reward decision along the dunes. Dunbar has hosted regional amateur tournaments and is a popular stop for visiting links enthusiasts exploring the East Lothian coast.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers panoramic views over the course and the sea, with a welcoming atmosphere. Dunbar exemplifies classic Scottish links, blending history, challenge, and natural beauty in a memorable golfing experience.', ''),
('dunblanenew', 'Dunblane New', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunblanenew#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunblanenew#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.179627, -3.954564, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunblanenew', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f5824f73f2a20fc0433d7d04fe164c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dunblane New Golf Club, near Stirling, is a mature parkland course offering a balanced mix of challenge and accessibility. Measuring around 6,100 yards with a par of 70, it features tree-lined fairways, strategically placed bunkers, and subtly contoured greens.\r\n\r\nKey holes include the par-4 9th and par-5 18th, where precise drives and thoughtful approaches are rewarded. The course has a strong community focus, hosting local competitions, society days, and junior events.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse provides hospitality and scenic views over the surrounding countryside. Dunblane New embodies classic Scottish parkland design, emphasizing accuracy, strategic thinking, and enjoyable play for golfers of all abilities.', ''),
('dundasparks', 'Dundas Parks', 'https://dundasparks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://dundasparks.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.973763, -3.407916, 0, 0, '', '', 'dundasparks', 299, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000001fbc7669430bc005871744a4fc4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dundas Parks Golf Club, located near Falkirk, is a modern 18-hole parkland course set in well-maintained, gently rolling terrain. Measuring approximately 6,200 yards with a par of 71, it features tree-lined fairways, bunkers, and water hazards that provide both challenge and variety.\r\n\r\nThe par-4 10th and par-5 16th are standout holes, offering risk-reward opportunities and requiring thoughtful navigation. Dundas Parks hosts local competitions, society events, and junior golf programs, fostering a vibrant club culture.\r\n\r\nThe clubhouse offers welcoming hospitality and views over key holes. Dundas Parks exemplifies modern inland Scottish parkland golf: strategic, scenic, and accessible for players of all levels.', ''),
('dundonald', 'Dundonald', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dundonald#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dundonald#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.584086, -4.654881, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dundonald', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000004c16f71f999e12c096067e54c3ca4b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Dundonald Links is a modern masterpiece that feels as though it has been carved out of the Ayrshire coast for centuries. Though a course existed on this site as far back as 1911designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Ferniethe layout as it stands today is the work of acclaimed architect Kyle Phillips. Phillips, known for his work at Kingsbarns, was commissioned in 2003 to create a championship-standard links that could hold its own against the historic giants of the region. He succeeded spectacularly, blending rugged undulations with the classic coastal aesthetic.\r\n\r\nThe course has quickly become a heavyweight on the professional circuit. It has hosted the Scottish Open on multiple occasions, most notably in 2017 when Rafa Cabrera-Bello took the title, as well as the Trust Golf Women\'s Scottish Open. Unlike many flat links, Dundonald features significant elevation changes and is framed by pockets of pine trees, giving it a unique visual identity. The resort recently underwent a 25 million upgrade, adding luxury lodges and a world-class clubhouse, ensuring that the off-course experience matches the quality of the pristine, gorse-lined fairways.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/BhXBUG2pqtg?si=OoUhgKbQLoE72dKa'),
('dunechthousegolfclub', 'Dunecht House', 'https://www.dunechthousegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.dunechthousegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.161030, -2.413260, 0, 2212, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000aef545425b4e03c062d68ba19c944c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tucked away in the heart of Aberdeenshire, Dunecht House offers a truly exclusive and intimate golfing experience. This is a private nine-hole parkland gem located within the sprawling estate of Dunecht House, a magnificent 19th-century mansion. Founded in 1920, the club was originally intended for the enjoyment of the estate\'s owners and their guests, and it retains that \"secret garden\" atmosphere to this day. It is a course that rewards precision over power, winding through mature Scottish woodland that provides both shelter and a stern test of accuracy.\r\n\r\nWhile many courses in the region shout for attention, Dunecht House whispers. It is a favorite among locals who appreciate its tranquil setting and the breathtaking views of the Aberdeenshire countryside. The layout has stood the test of time with very few changes, preserving the original vision of a gentleman\'s sporting retreat. Membership remains limited, which means those lucky enough to play here often feel as though they have the entire estate to themselves. It is the quintessential example of traditional Scottish parkland golfunpretentious, naturally beautiful, and deeply rooted in its local history.', ''),
('dunfermline', 'Dunfermline', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.058637, -3.505713, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunfermline', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e04be141b30b0cc0f3aace6a81074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Dunfermline Golf Club, often referred to as Pitfirrane, is steeped in a level of history that few clubs can match. The club was founded in 1887, but it moved to its current home at Pitfirrane Estate in 1953. The centerpiece of the property is the spectacular Pitfirrane Castle, which serves as the clubhouse; parts of this Category A listed building date back to the 15th century. Walking into the 19th hole here feels more like entering a museum than a locker room, providing a sense of gravitas to every round.\r\n\r\nThe 18-hole parkland course was designed by the esteemed J.R. Stutt, a prolific Scottish architect who worked alongside James Braid. Stutt utilized the natural undulations of the Fife landscape to create a testing layout that features no fewer than five par-fives. The signature 18th hole, \"Halkett\'s Hame\" is a grueling 480-yard finish that requires nerves of steel to conclude a round. Notable for its impeccably manicured fairways and fast greens, the course has long been a venue for regional qualifying events and amateur championships, consistently proving that it remains a formidable test for golfers of all skill levels.', ''),
('dunfermlinepitfirrane', 'Dunfermline - Halkett', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/3', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunfermline#/course/3', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.058637, -3.505713, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunfermline', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e04be141b30b0cc0f3aace6a81074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While the main 18-hole course draws the crowds, the Halkett Course offers a more intimate and technical experience within the same historic estate. This 9-hole, par-3 executive course is a hidden gem for those looking to sharpen their short game or enjoy a brisk round in the \"Footsteps of Kings.\" Legend has it that King James VI and King Charles I both enjoyed golf on these grounds while staying at nearby Dunfermline Palace, lending the course a regal pedigree that belies its modest 1,074-yard length.\r\n\r\nThe Halkett Course is meticulously maintained to the same high standards as its larger sibling but presents its own set of challenges. Though it lacks sand bunkers, the course is heavily protected by a phalanx of mature, ancient trees that require pinpoint accuracy off the tee. Each hole demands a soft touch and careful club selection, making it a favorite for juniors, beginners, and low-handicappers alike. It serves as a tranquil sanctuary where the modern game meets centuries of Scottish heritage, all under the watchful eye of the imposing Pitfirrane Castle.', ''),
('dunkeldbirnam', 'Dunkeld and Birnam', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunkeldbirnam#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunkeldbirnam#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.570837, -3.569972, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunkeldbirnam', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f015dd7a4d8f0cc0622cd32f11494c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Highland Perthshire is home to some of the most scenic golf in the world, and Dunkeld and Birnam is arguably its crown jewel. The club\'s origins trace back to 1892, with the original nine holes laid out by the legendary Old Tom Morris. While the course moved to its current hillside location in 1922, the spirit of \"The Grand Old Man of Golf\" still permeates the atmosphere. The official opening of the new site was a grand affair, conducted by Her Grace, The Duchess of Atholl, cementing the club\'s prestigious local standing.\r\n\r\nIn 2000, the course was expanded to 18 holes, with the newer section running alongside the Loch of Lowes. This expansion added a parkland dimension to the original heathland character, creating a fascinating \"game of two halves.\" The elevation changes provide spectacular vistas of the Tay Valley and the historic town of Dunkeld. It is a course where you are just as likely to spot an osprey or a deer as you are to make a birdie. The layout is quirky and charismatic, demanding creative shot-making rather than brute force, making it a must-visit for those who value character in course design.', ''),
('dunnikier', 'Dunnikier', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunnikier#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/dunnikier#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.139963, -3.163416, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'dunnikier', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000024253d0cad4e09c035d3bd4eea114c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Dunnikier Park is a delightful parkland course situated on the northern outskirts of Kirkcaldy. Designed by the Paisley-based architect John Stutt and opened in 1963, the course was part of a post-war movement to provide high-quality golf to the local community. Stutt\'s design philosophy is evident here: he used the natural contours of the parkland to create a fair but demanding test. The course is famously well-wooded, with mature trees lining almost every fairway, requiring players to be strategic with their off-the-tee placement.\r\n\r\nOver the years, Dunnikier has built a reputation for its friendly, inclusive atmosphere. While it hasn\'t hosted the major professional opens of its coastal neighbors, it is a frequent host of Fife Golf Association events and has nurtured many talented local amateurs. The layout is particularly known for its challenging finish, where the final few holes can easily ruin a good scorecard. It offers a peaceful escape from the nearby town, providing a lush, green sanctuary that feels far removed from the bustle of modern life. It is the kind of course that rewards the \"thinking golfer\" who knows when to take a risk and when to play safe.', ''),
('Dunning', 'Dunning', 'https://www.dunninggolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.313464, -3.590110, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002a5778978bb80cc0973c9e961f284c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The village of Dunning is home to a quintessential nine-hole course that captures the heart of Scottish village golf. Established in 1906, the course is located in the shadow of the historic St. Serf\'s Church, where the 12th-century tower looms over the fairways. The layout was designed by the prolific Tom Dunn, an architect who was instrumental in the spread of golf across the UK in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Dunn\'s signature stylefunctional, natural, and accessibleis perfectly preserved in this scenic Perthshire valley.\r\n\r\nDunning is unique because it features two burns (the Dunning Burn and the Dewar Burn) that meander through the property, coming into play on several holes. Despite being a nine-hole layout, the club offers 18 separate tee positions, allowing for a varied second loop. It is a course that emphasizes the \"short game\" with small, tricky greens that require a deft touch. Famous for its warm hospitality, the club is a favorite for those touring the Gleneagles area who want a quick, charming round that highlights the beauty of the Ochil Hills without the championship price tag.', ''),
('duns', 'Duns', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/duns#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/duns#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 56.387868, -3.457551, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'duns', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004b04aa7f10a90bc01c959ba8a5314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set in the rolling hills of the Scottish Borders, Duns Golf Club is a hidden gem that offers a peaceful, panoramic golfing experience. The club was founded in 1894, but the course was redesigned and extended to its current 18-hole layout in the 1920s by the legendary James Braid. Braid\'s influence is unmistakable, particularly in the way the course utilizes the natural slopes of Hardens Hill to create challenging lies and strategic bunkering. The elevation provides views that on a clear day stretch across the Merse to the Cheviot Hills in England.\r\n\r\nDuns is often described as a \"course of two halves.\" The lower holes are relatively flat and parkland in nature, while the upper holes transition into a more rugged, moorland environment. This variety keeps the golfer engaged from start to finish. One of the club\'s most famous honorary members was the legendary Formula 1 champion Jim Clark, who hailed from the area. The club maintains a memorial to him, and the sense of local pride is palpable. It is a welcoming, traditional club that provides a rigorous but fair test of golf in one of Scotland\'s most underrated regions.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('Durness', 'Durness', 'https://www.durnessgolfclub.org/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.576366, -4.772935, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002cbccb457c1713c05f43705cc6494d40, 'links', 'No', 'Durness Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the most bucket-list-worthy nine-hole courses in the world. Located in the far northwest Highlands, it is the most north-westerly course on the British mainland. It was remarkably designed and built in 1988 by three local enthusiasts-Lachie Ross, Ian Morrison, and Francis Keith-who saw the potential in the stunning limestone machair land. The result is a course that looks like it was designed by nature itself, with dramatic cliff-top views of Balnakeil Bay and the North Atlantic Ocean.\r\n\r\nThe signature 9th hole (or 18th, if playing twice) is a heart-stopping par-three that requires a shot across a yawning Atlantic chasm to a green perched on the cliffs. It is frequently cited as one of the most extraordinary holes in golf. While it lacks the \"famous architect\" pedigree of other courses, its sheer beauty and isolation have made it a cult favorite among international golf travelers. The course is maintained by a small, dedicated team, and the \"honesty box\" for green fees adds to the feeling of being at the very edge of the world.', ''),
('eastermoffat', 'Easter Moffat', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastermoffat#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastermoffat#/course/1', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.871143, -3.916913, 0, 0, 'no opens', '', '', 0, '', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ce37a27bd6550fc0d591239d81ef4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Lanarkshire, Easter Moffat Golf Club is a grand parkland course with a history dating back to 1922. The club\'s focal point is its stunning clubhousea Grade B listed mansion built in 1838. The transition from the historic elegance of the house to the lush green fairways sets a sophisticated tone for the day. Originally a nine-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes following the Second World War, with the layout evolving over the decades into the polished, championship-style course it is today.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its wide fairways and large, undulating greens, which are often cited as some of the best-conditioned in the county. It sits on a high plateau, offering views across the Monklands and towards the Campsie Fells. While it provides a stern test for the low-handicapper, its fair layout makes it accessible for the casual player as well. Easter Moffat has long been a pillar of the Lanarkshire golf scene, frequently hosting county championships and producing several notable amateur players who have gone on to represent Scotland on the national stage.', ''),
('eastkilbride', 'East Kilbride', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastkilbride#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastkilbride#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.783138, -4.156448, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eastkilbride', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000033198ee733a010c09f20b1dd3de44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'East Kilbride Golf Club represents the modern face of Scottish parkland golf. While the club was founded in 1900, it moved to its current location at Nerston in the late 1960s to accommodate the development of the \"New Town.\" The course was designed by the well-known architect Fred Hawtree, whose family firm is one of the oldest in the business. Hawtree\'s design at East Kilbride is a masterclass in modern parkland architecture, featuring strategic bunkering, water hazards, and a variety of tree species that have now matured to provide a true sense of enclosure.\r\n\r\nOne of the club\'s most famous former members was Jack McLean, a three-time Scottish Amateur Champion in the 1930s who also reached the final of the US Amateur. His legacy continues to inspire the competitive spirit of the club today. The course is a frequent host of West of Scotland PGA events and is renowned for its excellent drainage, meaning it remains playable when other nearby courses are struggling with the Scottish weather. With a sleek, modern clubhouse opened in 2011, it remains one of the most popular and professional clubs in the central belt.', ''),
('eastrenfrewshire', 'East Renfrewshire', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastrenfrewshire#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eastrenfrewshire#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.755356, -4.367871, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eastrenfrewshire', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000005796e82cb37811c02f6b6281afe04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'High on the moors above the village of Newton Mearns sits East Renfrewshire Golf Club, a course that breathes with the legacy of the \"Great Triumvirate.\" Established in 1922, the layout was designed by the five-time Open Champion James Braid. Braid was a master of using natural hazards, and here he utilized the rugged moorland terrain, rocky outcrops, and sweeping elevation changes to create a course that feels far more remote than its proximity to Glasgow suggests. On a clear day, the views from the highest points of the course stretch across the Clyde Valley to the peaks of Ben Lomond and the Southern Highlands.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich history of hosting prestigious events, including the Scottish Professional Championship and the Scottish Youths\' Championship. Its most famous \"member\" in spirit is arguably Braid himself, as the course remains one of the purest examples of his design philosophy in the West of Scotland. The holes are characterized by their strategic demand; Braid\'s bunkering forces players to choose between the aggressive line and the safe play. With its lush, springy turf and challenging wind conditions, it offers a stern but fair test that has remained largely unchanged for over a century.', ''),
('edzell', 'Edzell', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.799834, -2.661234, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'edzell', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000af06280d354a05c04b1de4f560664c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Edzell Golf Club is often described as one of the most aesthetically pleasing inland courses in Scotland. Situated at the gateway to the Grampian Mountains, the course was originally laid out in 1895 by Bob Simpson, the legendary clubmaker from Elie. However, it was a redesign in the 1930s by James Braid that truly elevated Edzell to its current status. The \"Old Course\" is a sophisticated blend of parkland and heathland, framed by majestic Scots pines and silver birches that provide a vibrant backdrop through the changing seasons.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its immaculate conditioning and its historic \"Arch\" which marks the entrance to the village and the club. One of the most notable tournaments held here was the Scottish Girls\' Championship, reflecting the club\'s long-standing commitment to nurturing young talent. The layout is renowned for its consistency, with greens that are famously true and fast. It is a course that requires precision rather than power, particularly on the stretch of holes that run alongside the West Water river, where the margin for error is slim but the rewards for a well-placed drive are immense.', ''),
('edzell9', 'Edzell - West Water', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/edzell9#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.805762, -2.653815, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'edzell9', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ec12d55b033b05c0062e8f3523674c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While the Old Course at Edzell takes much of the spotlight, the West Water course is a vital and distinct part of the club\'s identity. Opened in 2001, this 9-hole layout was designed by Graeme Webster, one of Scotland\'s most respected modern architects. Webster\'s task was to create a course that complemented the historic Old Course while offering a different kind of challenge. The West Water is shorter and perhaps more \"player-friendly\" for high handicappers, but it is by no means a pushover, featuring modern bunkering and undulating greens that require a sharp short game.\r\n\r\nThe course takes its name from the river that borders the property, and the sound of rushing water provides a serene soundtrack to the round. It is an ideal venue for those looking for a quicker game or for members wishing to sharpen their iron play before tackling the longer 18-hole layout. Despite its relatively young age, the West Water has matured quickly, with the planting of thousands of native trees helping it blend seamlessly into the ancient landscape of the Angus glens. It represents the club\'s forward-thinking approach, ensuring that golf at Edzell remains accessible and varied for all generations.', ''),
('elderslie', 'Elderslie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elderslie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elderslie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.833948, -4.472302, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'elderslie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007157af22a3e311c04548ddcebeea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elderslie Golf Club, located just outside Paisley, holds a unique place in golfing history as the home club of James Braid during the time he was designing some of his most famous layouts. Although Braid didn\'t design the original course (which was laid out by the club\'s first professional), he lived nearby and frequently offered his expertise on improvements. The course as it stands today is a lush, rolling parkland paradise that provides a surprisingly quiet escape from the industrial heartlands of Renfrewshire.\r\n\r\nThe club is perhaps most famous for the Elderslie Trophy, a prestigious amateur event that has seen many future professionals compete over its challenging 6,100 yards. The terrain is characterized by \"whins\" (gorse) and mature woodland, with several blind shots that require local knowledgeor at least a very trusty yardage book. The 6th hole, \"The Monument\" is a highlight, offering views of the Wallace Monument in nearby Elderslie, the birthplace of Scottish hero William Wallace. It is a friendly, traditional club that prides itself on a warm \"19th hole\" welcome and a course that is always presented in championship condition.', ''),
('elgin', 'Elgin', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elgin#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elgin#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.627887, -3.315695, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'elgin', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000f415a4198b860ac0b24ae9995ed04c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elgin Golf Club is widely considered the finest inland course in the north of Scotland. Located in the heart of \"Whisky Country\" the club moved to its current site at Hardhillock in 1906. The course was originally designed by Peter McArthur, but like many of the greats, it saw significant refinement by James Braid. It is a classic heathland layout, sitting on a bed of free-draining sandy soil that allows for firm, fast playing conditions year-round. The fairways are lined with thick gorse and heather, making a straight drive an absolute necessity.\r\n\r\nElgin has a long history of hosting top-tier amateur events, including the Northern Open and various Scottish Golf national championships. The club has produced a number of high-profile players, and the level of local competition is notoriously high. The signature par-three 5th hole, played over a valley to a plateau green, is one of the most photographed in Moray. After a round, many golfers take advantage of the club\'s proximity to some of Scotland\'s most famous distilleries, making Elgin a central pillar of any Highland golf tour that values tradition and a high-quality test of skill.', ''),
('elie', 'Elie', 'https://elie.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.190112, -2.836491, 0, 0, '', 'https://elie.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000cb2f833122b106c0e0490b9755184c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'To play Elie is to step back in time. Formally known as The Golf House Club, golf has been played on this stunning piece of Fife coastline since the 16th century. The course reached its current 18-hole form in 1895 with the help of Old Tom Morris and James Braid, the latter of whom was born in the adjacent village of Earlsferry. Elie is unique among world-class courses because it has no par-fives and only two par-threes; however, its collection of long, testing par-fours, many of which are played over blind ridges, makes it a formidable challenge.\r\n\r\nThe most famous feature of Elie is the submarine periscope located in the starter\'s hut. Because the opening tee shot is played over a hill, the starter uses the periscope (salvaged from HMS Excalibur) to ensure the fairway is clear. Famous members include Braid himself and the legendary Sir Michael Bonallack, one of the most decorated amateurs in history. The course is a pure links, with firm turf, hidden pot bunkers, and the ever-present wind from the Firth of Forth. It is a \"member\'s club\" in the truest sense, exuding an air of understated elegance and historical significance that few places can match.', ''),
('eliesportsclub', 'Elie Sports Club', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/elie#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.191463, -2.827599, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'elie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000529e7939ec9e06c070b20ddc81184c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just inland from the famous links of the Golf House Club, the Elie Sports Club (formerly the Elie Relief Course) offers a more relaxed, community-focused golfing experience. This 9-hole course is the perfect antidote to the high-pressure environment of championship links golf. It was designed to provide a space for beginners, juniors, and families to enjoy the game in the same coastal air as its more famous neighbor but without the intimidating length or the periscope-guarded blind shots.\r\n\r\nThe Sports Club is part of a larger facility that includes tennis and bowling, making it a hub of activity in the East Neuk of Fife. Despite its shorter length, the course is beautifully maintained and features many of the same links characteristicssandy soil and coastal breezesthat define Fife golf. It is a particularly popular spot for \"warm-up\" rounds or for golfers who want to enjoy a morning game before a afternoon of sightseeing in the historic fishing villages nearby. It serves as a vital nursery for the next generation of Scottish golfers, maintaining the inclusive spirit that has kept the game alive in Fife for centuries.', ''),
('elmwood', 'Elmwood', 'https://www.elmwoodgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.elmwoodgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.298290, -3.049250, 0, 2571, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000be9f1a2fdd6408c0a75ce15d2e264c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Elmwood Golf, situated near Cupar in Fife, is a fascinating modern addition to the Scottish golf scene. Opened in the mid-1990s, it was designed by Graeme Webster and serves a dual purpose: it is both a popular public pay-and-play course and a key training facility for SRUC (Scotland\'s Rural College). Because it is used to train the next generation of greenkeepers and golf managers, the course is often in \"textbook\" condition, serving as a living classroom for sustainable turf management and modern course design.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a modern parkland-style course that makes clever use of environmentally friendly features, such as wildflower meadows and wetlands, which provide a rich habitat for local wildlife. It is not an overly long course, but the bunkering is strategic, and the greens are known for being remarkably smooth and receptive. Elmwood has hosted various PGA pro-ams and regional qualifying events, earning a reputation as a high-quality facility that punches well above its weight. It is perhaps the best place in Fife to see the future of the Scottish golf industry in action while enjoying a fun, accessible round of golf.', ''),
('eriska', 'Isle of Eriska', 'https://www.eriska-hotel.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.532936, -5.412279, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000724f57772ca615c0376e313f37444c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Isle of Eriska offers what is arguably the most exclusive and picturesque short-course experience in the British Isles. Located on a private 300-acre island off the west coast of Scotland near Oban, the 9-hole course is part of the world-renowned Isle of Eriska Hotel and Spa. The course was designed by Howard Swan and is intended to provide a luxury recreational experience for guests of the estate. It is a \"hidden\" course in the most literal sense, accessible only by a private bridge that connects the island to the mainland.\r\n\r\nThe holes wind through ancient woodland and along the rugged shoreline, offering views of Loch Linnhe and the Morvern mountains that are nothing short of cinematic. While it is a shorter course, the island\'s terrain provides natural defenses, with rocky outcrops and the sea breeze adding to the difficulty. It is a favorite haunt of celebrities and high-profile guests seeking total privacy. Playing here is less about the scorecard and more about the atmospherethe scent of wild garlic in the air, the sight of golden eagles overhead, and the absolute silence that comes with playing on your own private island.', ''),
('erskine', 'Erskine', 'https://erskine.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://erskine.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.921585, -4.488157, 0, 0, '', '', 'erskine', 392, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ff40b96ddff311c0f9bd4d7ff6f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Erskine Golf Club is a powerhouse of West of Scotland golf, located on the banks of the River Clyde with views across to the Kilpatrick Hills. Founded in 1904, the course was redesigned in the late 1920s by the legendary duo of James Braid and Willie Gaudin. The result is a premier parkland course that blends traditional design with the scale and drama of the Clyde estuary. The course is famously divided by the Bishopton-to-Erskine road, with the holes on either side offering slightly different charactersone more wooded and sheltered, the other more open to the elements.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of hosting major championships, including the Scottish Professional Championship and the British Seniors\' Championship. Its quality is such that it has long been used as a final qualifying venue for the Open Championship when it is held at nearby Royal Troon or Prestwick. Famous members have included several titans of Scottish industry, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette and tradition. With its massive mature trees, deep bunkers, and slick greens, Erskine remains one of the most respected and physically demanding parkland tests in the country.', ''),
('eyemouth', 'Eyemouth', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eyemouth#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/eyemouth#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.867214, -2.079868, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'eyemouth', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b5f97fd591a300c011514cde00ef4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Eyemouth Golf Club offers a heart-pounding experience on the Berwickshire coast that rivals the most famous cliff-top courses in the world. Originally a 9-hole course founded in 1894, it was extended to 18 holes in 1997 by architect William Swan. The modern layout is a spectacular hybrid of rolling parkland and \"extreme\" coastal golf. It is most famous for its 6th hole, \"A\' v weel\" which was once voted Britain\'s most extraordinary golf hole. This par-three requires a daunting 160-plus yard carry over a deep, churning Atlantic inlet known as \"Gull\'s Nest\" to a green perched on a jagged promontory.\r\n\r\nThe course is a regular host of the Scottish Borders Open and is a favorite for visitors seeking a visual spectacle. Beyond the terrifying carries over the sea, the course offers panoramic views that stretch toward the Bass Rock in the north and Holy Island in the south. The wind is the primary defender here; on a calm day, the course is a delight of manicured turf, but when the North Sea gales blow, it becomes a survival test. It is a bold, modern links-style experience that emphasizes the raw, rugged beauty of Scotland\'s eastern coastline.', ''),
('fairmontKittocks', 'Fairmont - Kittocks', 'https://www.fairmont.com/en/hotels/st-andrews/fairmont-st-andrews/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.320903, -2.730651, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000004c512e8d5fd805c01a18795913294c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The Kittocks course at the Fairmont St Andrews resort is a sprawling, modern masterpiece that commands the clifftops just outside the \"Home of Golf.\" Originally a collaboration between Bruce Devlin and the legendary Gene Sarazen, the course was later refined by Gary Stephenson. It is named after the Kittocks Den, a natural ravine that meanders through the property. The design is American in scalefeaturing large, undulating greens and expansive bunkersbut Scottish in soul, with fescue grasses and breathtaking views of the St Andrews skyline and the Eden Estuary.\r\n\r\nKittocks has hosted several prestigious events, including the Scottish Senior Open and EuroPro Tour events. One of its most famous features is the double green shared by the 14th and 17th holes, a nod to the historic Old Course nearby. The closing stretch is particularly dramatic, with the 17th hole running precariously along the very edge of the cliffs. It offers a more rugged, \"wilder\" feel than its sister course, the Torrance, and provides a stern test of ball-striking, especially when the wind whips off the North Sea.', ''),
('fairmonttorrance', 'Fairmont - Torrance', 'https://www.fairmont.com/en/hotels/st-andrews/fairmont-st-andrews/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.320903, -2.730651, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000004c512e8d5fd805c01a18795913294c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The Torrance Course, the Kittocks\' sister at the Fairmont resort, was originally designed by the late, great Ryder Cup legend Sam Torrance. It was later extensively remodeled by Gary Stephenson to give it a more traditional Scottish links character. Torrance\'s vision was to create a walking-friendly course that felt like a classic links despite its clifftop location. This was achieved by adding revetted bunkering and undulating fairways that encourage the \"ground game\" so vital to Scottish golf.\r\n\r\nThe Torrance has a high-profile tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and hosting the DP World Tour\'s Hero Open. It is a challenging par-72 that demands strategic thinking; Sam Torrance himself was known as a master tactician, and his course reflects that, with subtle risks and rewards built into every hole. With the iconic Fairmont hotel looming in the background and the sea stretching out to the horizon, it offers a luxury golfing experience that blends modern amenities with the timeless challenge of coastal golf.', ''),
('falkirk', 'Falkirk', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirk#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirk#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.010231, -3.826269, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirk', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c896e5eb329c0ec0e333d93f4f014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Known locally as \"Carmuirs\" Falkirk Golf Club is one of the premier parkland venues in Central Scotland. Founded in 1922, the course was laid out by the prolific James Braid, whose influence is evident in the clever use of the natural landscape and the strategic bunkering that protects the greens. The course is characterized by its lush, mature woodland and remarkably consistent playing surfaces. It serves as a green oasis in an area otherwise known for its industrial heritage, providing a peaceful and highly scenic round of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a hub for competitive amateur golf, frequently hosting the Stirlingshire County Championships. Its layout is famously fair; there are few \"tricky\" holes, but the length and the tightness of the tree-lined fairways require a disciplined approach. The signature 14th hole, a par-three across a valley, is often cited as the most beautiful on the course. Famous for its friendly membership and an active social scene, Falkirk remains a traditional Scottish club that prides itself on maintaining Braid\'s original design principles while providing a modern, high-quality experience for its members and visitors.', ''),
('falkirkantonine', 'Falkirk - Antonine', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.010231, -3.826269, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirk', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c896e5eb329c0ec0e333d93f4f014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located on the outskirts of the village of Bonnybridge, the Antonine course (part of the Falkirk Golf Club ecosystem but distinct in character) is steeped in ancient history. The course takes its name from the Antonine Wall, the Roman Empire\'s northernmost frontier, which runs directly through the property. Playing here is as much a history lesson as it is a sporting challenge; several fairways are literally built over the remains of the Roman turf fortifications. This historical significance gives the course a unique atmosphere that few other venues in the world can match.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a hilly, demanding parkland course that provides spectacular views across the Forth Valley to the Ochil Hills. While it may not have the championship length of some neighbors, its defenses lie in its elevation changes and tricky, sloping greens. It is a course that favors the accurate iron player over the long hitter. Because of its unique location, it is a frequent stop for \"golf historians\" who want to walk the same ground as the Roman legions while trying to save par. It is a charming, community-focused club that offers a rugged and memorable Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('falkirktryst', 'Falkirk Tryst', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirktryst#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkirktryst#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.030543, -3.820600, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkirktryst', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e3c798bb96900ec0950f41d5e8034c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Falkirk Tryst Golf Club, located in Larbert, occupies a site of immense historical importance. Long before golf was played here, the land hosted the \"Great Tryst\"the largest cattle fair in Scotlandand was also the site of the Battle of Falkirk (1746). The golf club was established in 1885, making it one of the oldest in the region. The course was originally a 9-hole layout but was expanded to 18 in the early 20th century, with contributions from the legendary James Braid, who refined the bunkering and green complexes to modern standards.\r\n\r\nTryst is a unique \"inland links\" style course, built on sandy, free-draining soil that allows for firm, fast-running fairways even in the depths of winter. This makes it a popular choice for year-round golf. The course has a long-standing association with the PGA and has hosted many regional professional events over the decades. Its most famous member is likely the former Ryder Cup player and successful commentator Ken Brown, who honed his creative game on these very fairways. The layout is relatively flat, making it a pleasant walk, but the strategic placement of Braid\'s bunkers ensures that a good score is never easily earned.', ''),
('falkland', 'Falkland', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/falkland#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.255178, -3.201499, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'falkland', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e469f981ab9c09c0505436aca9204c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Falkland Golf Club is a delightful 9-hole parkland course situated in the shadow of the historic Falkland Palace, the former country residence of the Stuart monarchs. Founded in 1902, the course is a classic example of a \"village\" clubunpretentious, welcoming, and deeply integrated into the local community. The layout was designed by the members themselves, and over the century, it has matured into a scenic and testing little course. The backdrop of the Lomond Hills provides a dramatic and ever-changing landscape for the golfer.\r\n\r\nWhile it lacks the \"famous architect\" branding, Falkland makes up for it with sheer charm and tricky, small greens. The course is known for being remarkably well-kept by a dedicated team of locals. It is a favorite for those who enjoy the \"short game\" as the yardage is modest but the margin for error around the greens is slim. Many visitors combine a round here with a trip to the nearby Palace, making it a perfect day out for those who love Scottish history as much as they love the game of golf. It is the quintessential Fife hidden gem.', ''),
('fereneze', 'Fereneze', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/fereneze#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/fereneze#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.805533, -4.414612, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'fereneze', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000da1d520c90a811c0a46c91b41be74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched high on the hills overlooking Barrhead, Fereneze Golf Club offers some of the most spectacular panoramic views in the West of Scotland. On a clear day, golfers can see as far as the Arran hills, Ben Lomond, and the city of Glasgow shimmering in the distance. The club was founded in 1904, and the course is a rugged, moorland layout that tests both your stamina and your shot-making. The terrain is undulating and natural, with gorse, heather, and rocky outcrops providing the main hazards.\r\n\r\nThe course was designed by Willie Fernie, the 1883 Open Champion, who specialized in creating layouts that worked with the natural \"lie of the land.\" Fereneze is famous for its steep inclinesthere are several holes where you\'ll need your \"mountain legs\"but the reward is the exhilaration of hitting shots from elevated tees into the valley below. The club has a reputation for producing tough, resilient golfers and has hosted various Renfrewshire county events. It is a course that doesn\'t rely on artificial features; instead, it uses the raw, windswept beauty of the Scottish moors to provide a timeless challenge.', ''),
('forbesofkingennie', 'Forbes of Kingennie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forbesofkingennie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forbesofkingennie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.514634, -2.846959, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forbesofkingennie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000446cb07092c606c070b4e386df414c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forbes of Kingennie, located near Dundee, is a modern 9-hole course that feels more like a private estate retreat than a traditional golf club. Opened in 2007, it was designed by Ian Rae as part of a luxury resort that includes fishing lochs and holiday lodges. The design is unique, featuring \"USGA-spec\" greens that are exceptionally large and undulating, providing a level of green-side challenge rarely found on 9-hole courses. It is a highly visual course, with water hazards and manicured bunkers that wouldn\'t look out of place on a professional tour.\r\n\r\nThe resort has gained fame beyond golf, partly due to its owner, Mike Forbes, a well-known local entrepreneur. The course has become a popular venue for the Scottish Hickory Championship, where players use pre-1935 wooden-shafted clubs to tackle the modern layouta fascinating clash of eras. Despite its short length, the course is no pushover; the elevation changes and frequent water features require precise club selection. It is widely regarded as one of the best-conditioned short courses in the country, making it a perfect spot for a high-quality, quick round in a beautiful Angus setting.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/ndkB1kgx4vg?si=JwmFlgDCFNnQQ1oj'),
('forfar', 'Forfar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forfar#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forfar#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.652824, -2.896393, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forfar', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000019e8da17d02b07c09f05a1bc8f534c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forfar Golf Club holds a special place in the history of golf architecture: it was the first course in the world to be designed from its inception as an 18-hole layout. Founded in 1871, the course was laid out by the legendary Old Tom Morris. However, the site\'s topography is its most famous featurethe \"rig and furrow\" patterns left by medieval farming are still visible today. These natural ridges create a unique, undulating fairway surface that provides a variety of unpredictable lies, making it a fascinating tactical challenge.\r\n\r\nIn the 1920s, the course was updated by James Braid, who added his signature bunkering to Old Tom\'s original routing. Forfar is a classic heathland course, lined with Scots pine and carpeted in heather. It has hosted many major amateur events, including the Scottish Boys\' Championship. The club is proud of its heritage, and the clubhouse is a treasure trove of early golfing memorabilia. The layout is a stern test of ball-striking, as the narrow fairways and firm, fast greens require both power and finesse. Forfar remains a \"must-play\" for anyone interested in the evolution of golf course design.', ''),
('forres', 'Forres', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forres#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/forres#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.603161, -3.621988, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'forres', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001c0934d8d4f90cc0809c306134cd4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Forres Golf Club is a beautifully manicured parkland course that sits on the sunny Moray coast. Originally established in 1889, the course was significantly redesigned by the legendary James Braid and Willie Park Jr., two of the most influential names in the history of the game. The result is a layout that provides a stern but fair challenge, characterized by its narrow, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally smooth greens. The course is famously well-protected from the elements by the surrounding dense woodland, making it a pleasant retreat even when the coastal winds are whipping across the nearby Moray Firth.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich tournament history, having hosted the Scottish Professional Championship and the Northern Open. One of its most famous members is the former Ryder Cup player Harry Bannerman, who represented Great Britain & Ireland in 1971. The signature hole is the 16th, aptly named \"Pond\" which requires a nerve-wracking approach over water to a well-guarded green. Forres is frequently cited as one of the best-value courses in the north of Scotland, offering a championship-quality experience in a tranquil, hospitable Highland setting.', ''),
('ForresterParkResort', 'Forrester Park Resort', 'https://www.forresterparkresort.com/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.066201, -3.532865, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000de76a1b94e430cc033fb3c4679084c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located near Dunfermline in the Kingdom of Fife, Forrester Park Resort is a modern parkland course that has quickly established itself as a premier destination for both casual and competitive golfers. Opened in 1999, the course was designed by Robert Sandow and is set within 350 acres of rolling countryside. Unlike the ancient links nearby, Forrester Park offers a contemporary challenge with wide, undulating fairways and large, multi-tiered greens that demand a high level of putting skill.\r\n\r\nThe resort is known for its excellent practice facilities and its luxurious clubhouse, making it a popular choice for corporate events and society outings. The layout features several water hazards and strategically placed bunkers that require careful navigation. While it doesn\'t boast the centuries-old history of some of its Fife neighbors, it has become a staple of the local golf scene and is a regular host of the Fife PGA Professional Championship. It is the perfect example of a modern Scottish golf resortaccessible, high-quality, and designed to provide an enjoyable experience for players of all ability levels.', ''),
('FortAugustus', 'Fort Augustus', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.137150, -4.689712, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000090a2cedc43c212c0bd5296218e914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Fort Augustus Golf Club is arguably the most scenic 9-hole course in the Scottish Highlands. Tucked away at the southern tip of Loch Ness, the course was established in 1924 and was designed by Harry Shapland Coltthe man responsible for masterpieces like Muirfield and Royal Portrush. To have a Colt-designed course in such a remote and beautiful location is a rare treat. The layout is a classic heathland style, featuring thick gorse, heather, and some of the most breathtaking views of the Great Glen you will ever encounter.\r\n\r\nThe course is famously challenging due to its hilly terrain and \"wild\" feel; it isn\'t uncommon to share the fairways with local sheep or deer. Despite its short length, Colt\'s strategic genius is evident in the green placements and the way the natural slopes are used to defend par. It is a traditional \"honesty box\" club that embodies the soul of Highland golf. For any golfer traveling the North Coast 500 or visiting Loch Ness, a stop at Fort Augustus is a mandatory pilgrimage to experience one of the world\'s most famous architects working on a miniature, natural canvas.', ''),
('fortrose', 'Fortrose and Rosemarkie', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/fortrose/visitor_home.php', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/fortrose/visitor_home.php', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.578077, -4.104405, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'fortrose', 1, 0, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000d027f224e96a10c0efc8586dfec94c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Situated on the Chanonry Peninsula, Fortrose and Rosemarkie Golf Club is the 15th oldest club in the world. This is a pure links experience on a narrow strip of land that juts out into the Moray Firth. The course was redesigned in 1932 by James Braid, who made ingenious use of the restricted space to create a layout that feels much larger than it is. The course is surrounded by water on three sides, and the Chanonry Lighthouse serves as a stunning backdrop. It is also one of the best places in the world to spot bottlenose dolphins playing in the surf just yards from the fairways.\r\n\r\nThe club has received numerous accolades, including being named \"Scotland\'s Best Golfing Experience\" in its category. Its most famous member is likely the former British Amateur Champion Alan Affleck. The course is notorious for its small, firm greens and the encroaching gorse that penalizes any wayward shot. The wind is a constant factor here, shifting direction as you loop around the peninsula. It is a rugged, historic, and utterly unique links that provides one of the most memorable rounds of golf in the Highlands.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/0PL8S8TBHTg?si=OjACGin7GDQjtqY7'),
('fortwilliam', 'Fort William', 'https://fortwilliam.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://fortwilliam.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'highlands', 'No', 56.801850, -5.134291, 0, 0, 'no data', '', 'fortwilliam', 8299, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ab967494838914c018265305a3664c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located at the foot of Ben Nevis, Britain\'s highest mountain, Fort William Golf Club offers a playing environment that is quite literally overshadowed by greatness. The course was opened in 1974 and provides a classic Highland parkland experience. The fairways wind through mature trees and over peat moorland, with the massive granite face of the mountain providing a constant, dramatic reference point. Because of its location in the \"Outdoor Capital of the UK\" the course is built to handle the high rainfall of the region, featuring excellent drainage and lush, green turf.\r\n\r\nWhile it is a relatively young club, it has become a central part of the Highland golfing community. The layout is relatively flat, making it an easy walk, but the challenge comes from the various mountain streams that crisscross the course and the unpredictable winds coming off the surrounding peaks. It is a popular spot for tourists who want to combine a morning hike up the mountain with an afternoon round of golf. The hospitality at the 19th hole is legendary, reflecting the warm, welcoming spirit of the Lochaber region.', ''),
('Foulford', 'Foulford', 'https://foulfordinn.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.419848, -3.787054, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e57cb1f7e24b0ec040a54a94bd354c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Foulford, located near Cowdenbeath in Fife, is a charming and somewhat eccentric 9-hole course that offers a glimpse into the industrial-meets-rural history of the region. While it may not have the pedigree of the \"Open\" venues nearby, Foulford is a beloved local institution known for its quirky layout and undulating greens. It is a parkland course that requires a \"target golf\" approach, as the small greens are often tucked away behind natural hillocks or protected by mature trees.\r\n\r\nThe course is a testament to the passion of local golfers who have maintained it for generations. It offers a relaxed, unpretentious atmosphere where the focus is firmly on the fun of the game. It is particularly well-suited for beginners or those looking for a quick, low-stress round. What it lacks in championship length, it makes up for in character; every hole feels unique, and the rolling Fife countryside provides a pleasant, pastoral backdrop. It is the kind of course where you can focus on your game without the pressure of a crowded tee sheet, making it a true community gem.', ''),
('fraserburgh', 'Fraseburgh - Corbiehill', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.677330, -1.994960, 2060, 2262, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000025404d2d5bebffbfc24cdbbfb2d64c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Fraserburgh Golf Club is the 7th oldest club in the world and the oldest in the North East of Scotland. The Corbiehill course is a high-octane links experience that was redesigned by James Braid in 1922. It is a \"raw\" links, meaning the land hasn\'t been overly manicured, preserving the massive sand dunes and natural hollows that make Scottish coastal golf so famous. The course features significant elevation changes, with many tees perched high atop dunes, offering views across the North Sea toward Norway.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted numerous prestigious events, including the Scottish Area Team Championships. Despite its incredible history and architectural pedigree, Fraserburgh remains one of the most underrated links in Scotland. It is often described as \"Braid\'s best-kept secret.\" The layout is punishing for those who can\'t control their ball flight in the wind, but it is immensely rewarding for those who enjoy creative shot-making. With its towering dunes and classic pot bunkers, Corbiehill is a masterclass in traditional links design that every serious golfer should experience at least once.', ''),
('fraserburghrosehill', 'Fraserburgh - Rosehill', 'https://fraserburghgolfclub.org/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.677330, -1.994960, 2061, 2262, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000025404d2d5bebffbfc24cdbbfb2d64c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Rosehill course at Fraserburgh serves as the perfect companion to its older, more intimidating brother, Corbiehill. This 9-hole layout offers a gentler introduction to links golf, making it an ideal spot for juniors, seniors, and those looking for a more casual round. While it lacks the massive dunes of Corbiehill, it still possesses the firm, sandy turf and coastal breezes that define the region. It is beautifully maintained to the same high standards as the main course, ensuring a quality playing surface year-round.\r\n\r\nRosehill is often used by members as a \"warm-up\" or for a quick evening game when time is short. The layout is relatively flat and easy to walk, but the small, well-protected greens still require a deft touch. It is a vital part of the club\'s identity, helping to foster a welcoming and inclusive environment for all ages. Playing Rosehill allows you to soak in the historic atmosphere of one of the world\'s oldest golf clubs without the physical and mental demands of the championship layout, making it a delightful addition to any visit to the Buchan coast.', ''),
('Gairloch', 'Gairloch', 'https://gairlochgolfclub.co.uk/index.html#', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.716994, -5.683642, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000029b000a60cbc16c0d0b69a75c6db4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gairloch Golf Club is a stunning 9-hole course located on the edge of a white sandy beach in the Northwest Highlands. Established in 1898, the course offers some of the most beautiful views in the world, stretching across the Minch to the Isle of Skye and the Outer Hebrides. The layout is a hybrid of links and heathland, with the salt-spray from the Atlantic often reaching the fairways. It is a natural course in every sense of the word, with the routing dictated by the rugged coastal terrain.\r\n\r\nThe club is a community-run gem, and the sense of local pride is evident in the warm welcome every visitor receives. The 9th hole is a standout, requiring a shot over the corner of the beach to reach the green. While it hasn\'t hosted major professional tournaments, it is a favorite for \"golf adventurers\" seeking the most remote and scenic courses in Scotland. It is a place where time slows down, and the only distractions are the sound of the waves and the occasional sighting of a sea eagle. Gairloch is the epitome of the \"hidden Highland gem.\"', ''),
('galashiels', 'Galashiels', 'https://www.galashielsgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.621111, -2.803650, 0, 2264, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000076711b0de06d06c0ca17b49080cf4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Galashiels Golf Club, known locally as \"Ladhope\" is a classic Scottish Borders hill course. Founded in 1884, the layout was refined by the great James Braid, who was a master at utilizing steep terrain to create interesting golfing challenges. The course is built on the side of a hill, meaning you will rarely have a flat lie, and your \"mountain legs\" will definitely be tested. The reward for the climb is a set of panoramic views over the town of Galashiels and the surrounding Eildon Hills that are nothing short of spectacular.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its lush fairways and tricky, sloping greens that require a lot of local knowledge to read correctly. Galashiels has produced many fine amateur players over the years and remains a competitive hub in the Borders golf scene. The 5th hole, \"The Pulpit\" is a famous test, requiring a precise drive from a high elevated tee. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on being a \"true test of golf and fitness.\" For those who enjoy the rugged beauty of the Borders and the challenge of moorland golf, Galashiels is an essential stop.', ''),
('gandkgc', 'Garmouth and Kingston', 'https://gandkgc.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://gandkgc.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.666845, -3.102549, 0, 0, '', '', 'gandkgc', 2312, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000068e6c93505d208c025404d2d5bd54c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Garmouth and Kingston Golf Club is a fascinating coastal course situated where the River Spey meets the Moray Firth. Originally a 9-hole course founded in 1923, it was extended to a full 18 holes by the legendary James Braid in the 1930s. Braid\'s ability to work with natural terrain is on full display here; the course is built on a series of raised beaches and shingle banks, providing a firm, fast-playing surface that is quintessentially Scottish. The proximity to the river means that the local topography is constantly shifting, giving the course a raw, organic feel.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its challenging wind conditions and small, tricky greens. While it may not have the international fame of nearby Lossiemouth, it is a favorite for those who appreciate traditional, unpretentious golf. The club has a strong local following and is often used for Moray County events. One of the highlights of a round here is the wildlife; the area is a haven for ospreys and seals. It is a peaceful, scenic layout that offers a genuine links-style challenge without the crowds, making it one of the best-kept secrets on the Moray coast.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('GatehouseofFleet', 'Gatehouse of Fleet', 'https://www.gatehousegolfclub.com/website/index.php', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 54.889370, -4.181159, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001781b1be81b910c092054ce0d6714b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the breathtaking Galloway Forest Park, Gatehouse of Fleet is a 9-hole parkland course that defines \"hidden gem.\" Established in 1921, the course was laid out on the hills overlooking the Fleet estuary, offering views that stretch toward the Isle of Man on a clear day. The layout is natural and rugged, featuring stone dykes, gorse, and significant elevation changes. It is a course that doesn\'t rely on manicured perfection; instead, it embraces the wild beauty of the Dumfries and Galloway countryside.\r\n\r\nThe club is a community-run facility that prides itself on its accessibility and friendliness. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the routing is clever, making excellent use of the sloping terrain to create holes that play much longer than their yardage. The small clubhouse is the heart of the village\'s sporting life, and the \"honesty box\" system for visitors adds to the traditional charm. It is the perfect spot for a quiet, contemplative round of golf, where the only sound is the wind through the trees and the distant bleating of sheep.', ''),
('giffordgc', 'Gifford', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/giffordgc#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/giffordgc#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.895914, -2.760667, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'giffordgc', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e52b8194d81506c0a703594fadf24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gifford Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the best 9-hole courses in the UK. Located in the heart of East Lothianthe \"Cradle of Golf\"it was founded in 1904 and designed by the local professional Tom Anderson. Gifford offers a parkland experience that rivals the quality of the famous links nearby. The course is characterized by its lush, manicured fairways and exceptionally fast, true greens. It feels more like a private estate than a public course, with mature trees and the Lammermuir Hills providing a stunning backdrop.\r\n\r\nThe club has a reputation for being a \"golfer\'s golf club\" focusing on the quality of the playing surface above all else. Famous members of the local community have long frequented these fairways, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette. Despite having only nine holes, the separate tee positions for the second loop provide a fresh perspective on every hole. Gifford is often used as a \"breather\" for golfers tackling the grueling links of Muirfield and North Berwick, offering a tranquil and refined alternative that still demands precise shot-making.', ''),
('girvan', 'Girvan', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gsacarrick#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.247314, -4.858642, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gsacarrick', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005ce333d93f6f13c0e6eb32fca79f4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Girvan Golf Club is a unique hybrid course that provides two distinct golfing experiences in one round. The front nine is a pure links, running alongside the Firth of Clyde with spectacular views of Ailsa Craig, while the back nine moves inland to a lush parkland setting. The course was originally designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, and his influence remains in the strategic layout of the coastal holes. The \"links half\" is exposed to the elements, requiring low-trajectory shots to navigate the sea breeze.\r\n\r\nGirvan has a strong connection to the professional game through its proximity to Turnberry. It has often been used as a practice ground for professionals visiting the region. The course is famously compact, meaning that accuracy is far more important than power. The transition from the sandy, wind-swept turf of the first nine to the sheltered, tree-lined fairways of the second is a fascinating tactical challenge. It is a friendly, municipal-run course that offers championship-standard views and a varied test of golf at a fraction of the cost of its more famous neighbors.', ''),
('glasgow', 'Glasgow Gailes', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/glasgow/visitor_home.php', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.596021, -4.664101, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glasgow', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000adf6b0170aa812c0575d876a4acc4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Glasgow Gailes is a titan of Scottish golf. Owned by Glasgow Golf Club (the 9th oldest in the world), this pure links course was redesigned by Willie Park Jr. in 1912. It is a classic \"out and back\" layout, characterized by its thick heather, gorse, and deep pot bunkers. Gailes is a perennial Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship, a testament to its difficulty and quality. It has also hosted the Scottish Amateur Championship and the Palmer Cup, making it a bucket-list destination for any serious student of the game.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its conditioning; even in the depths of winter, the fairways are firm and the greens are lightning-fast. Famous members over the years have included many of Scotland\'s leading industrialists and champion amateurs. Unlike many links that are flat, Gailes features subtle undulations that can kick a slightly off-center drive into the punishing heather. The clubhouse is a masterclass in Edwardian elegance, offering a refined atmosphere that reflects the club\'s prestigious status. It is a pure, uncompromising test of golf that requires every club in the bag.', ''),
('gleddoch', 'Gleddoch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gleddoch#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.918614, -4.584087, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gleddoch', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000034130ce71a5612c0e9d2bf2495f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gleddoch Golf Club offers a modern, high-elevation parkland experience on the hills overlooking the River Clyde. The course was designed in the 1970s as part of the Gleddoch House Hotel estate, which was formerly the home of the shipping magnate Sir William Lithgow. Because of its hilltop location, the course offers some of the most expansive views in Renfrewshire, stretching toward the Erskine Bridge and the mountains of the Trossachs. It is a physically demanding course, with significant climbs and dramatic drops that make for an exhilarating round.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its \"resort\" style, with wide fairways and large greens, but the elevation changes and frequent wind make it a tough scoring test. Gleddoch has hosted several PGA regional events and is a popular choice for corporate golf days. The signature hole is the par-four 17th, where the tee is perched high above the fairway, requiring a drive that seems to stay in the air forever. Following a major renovation of the hotel and spa, Gleddoch has become one of the premier stay-and-play destinations in the West of Scotland, offering luxury and spectacular scenery in equal measure.', ''),
('glenbervie', 'Glenbervie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenbervie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenbervie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.039249, -3.850306, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenbervie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000098bd6c3b6dcd0ec04ab3791c06054c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glenbervie Golf Club is widely considered one of the finest parkland courses in the country. Located near Larbert, the course was designed by the legendary James Braid and opened in 1932. Braid\'s routing through the mature pine and larch forests is masterful, creating a sense of total isolation on almost every hole. The course is famously long and testing, with a \"championship\" feel that has made it a regular host of the Scottish Professional Championship and the Girls\' Home Internationals.\r\n\r\nOne of the club\'s most famous associations is with the legendary John Panton, one of Scotland\'s greatest-ever professional golfers, who served as the club\'s honorary president. The course is known for its exceptional greens, which are often cited as the truest in the region. The layout requires strategic placement off the tee to navigate the tree-lined corridors, and the bunkering is classic Braiddeep and unforgiving. Glenbervie is a \"pure\" golf club with a focused, competitive membership, offering a polished and professional experience for anyone looking to test their game on a top-tier inland layout.', ''),
('glencorse', 'Glencorse', 'https://glencorsegolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.849702, -3.200246, 0, 2280, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000103d29931a9a09c043acfe08c3ec4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glencorse Golf Club, located in Milton Bridge near Edinburgh, is a charming and historic course that punches far above its weight. Founded in 1890, the layout was refined by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie. While it is a relatively short course by modern standards (a par-68), it is famously difficult to play to your handicap. The course is defined by the Glencorse Burn, which meanders through the property and comes into play on no fewer than ten holes, requiring constant vigilance and precise club selection.\r\n\r\nThe club\'s most famous member was the 19th-century author Robert Louis Stevenson, who spent much of his childhood in the area and is said to have enjoyed the tranquility of the Glencorse valley. The course is a lush, parkland oasis with small, undulating greens that require a deft touch. It is a frequent host of the Lothians Champion of Champions tournament. Glencorse is proof that a course doesn\'t need 7,000 yards to be a great test; its defense lies in its clever routing and the ever-present threat of the water, making it a favorite for those who value strategy over power.', ''),
('glencruitten', 'Glencruitten', 'https://www.golfoban.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.golfoban.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.413600, -5.450760, 0, 2281, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003d61890794cd15c014d044d8f0344c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Known as the \"Hillside Gem of the Highlands\" Glencruitten Golf Club is located in the hills above the coastal town of Oban. The course was designed by James Braid and is a masterclass in utilizing difficult, rocky terrain. It is a short but incredibly hilly layout, featuring blind shots, dramatic elevation changes, and greens perched on rocky outcrops. While it may be physically taxing, the views over Oban Bay and the surrounding islands are worth every step.\r\n\r\nThe course\'s most famous son is the PGA Tour professional Robert MacIntyre, who grew up playing these rugged fairways and still represents the club on the world stage. MacIntyre\'s creative short game was undoubtedly forged on the tricky, sloping greens of Glencruitten. The course is characterized by its lush flora, including thousands of rhododendrons that bloom in the spring. It is a unique, charismatic course that doesn\'t fit the mold of a standard parkland or links layout; instead, it offers a purely Highland adventure that tests your imagination and your stamina in equal measure.', ''),
('gleneagleskings', 'Gleneagles - Kings', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/21459/?', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280540, -3.750691, 160448, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000593673486a010ec0249c16bce8234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The King\'s Course at Gleneagles is arguably the most famous inland course in the world. Opened in 1919 and designed by James Braid, it was intended to be a \"highland links\"-a course that played like a coastal links but was set among the dramatic peaks of the Ochil Hills. Braid\'s masterpiece is a symphony of springy turf, massive bunkers, and blind shots over ridges (the \"whins\"). It has hosted legendary events, including the first-ever unofficial Ryder Cup in 1921, as well as countless European Tour events.\r\n\r\nFamous members and visitors are too numerous to count, ranging from Hollywood royalty to world leaders. The King\'s is a grand, aristocratic layout where every hole has a name and a story. The 18th hole, \"Dun Whinny\" is one of the most iconic finishes in golf, requiring a climb up toward the majestic hotel. Following a massive restoration project to return the course to Braid\'s original vision, the fairways are wider and the bunkers more rugged, ensuring that the King\'s remains the gold standard for moorland golf and a primary reason why Gleneagles is known as a \"Golfer\'s Paradise.\"', ''),
('gleneaglespga', 'Gleneagles - PGA', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/22053/?', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280564, -3.750537, 160454, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ed80eb8a19010ec0ac376a85e9234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The PGA Centenary Course at Gleneagles is a modern titan of the game, designed by the legendary Jack Nicklaus. Opened in 1993, it was created specifically to host the world\'s biggest stages. Nicklaus described the land as the \"finest parcel of ground in the world\" he had ever been given to work with. Unlike the older Braid designs at the resort, the PGA Centenary is an American-style \"stadium\" course, featuring large, fast greens, expansive white sand bunkers, and multiple teeing options that can stretch the course to over 7,000 yards.\r\n\r\nThis course etched its name into history as the venue for the 2014 Ryder Cup, where Europe triumphed under Paul McGinnity, and the 2019 Solheim Cup, arguably one of the most dramatic finishes in women\'s golf history. It is a course of dramatic risk and reward, particularly the par-five 18th, which has witnessed countless eagles and heartbreak alike. With the backdrop of the Perthshire mountains and the impeccable maintenance standards of the Gleneagles estate, it offers a tour-professional experience that demands power, precision, and nerves of steel.', ''),
('gleneaglesqueens', 'Gleneagles - Queens', 'https://pursuits.gleneagles.com/reservations/template/22052/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'gleneagles', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280540, -3.750691, 160451, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000593673486a010ec0249c16bce8234c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'While the Kings is grand and the PGA Centenary is formidable, many regular visitors to Gleneagles consider the Queen\'s Course to be the most beautiful of the three. Another James Braid masterpiece, the Queen\'s is shorter and more sheltered than its \"royal\" sibling, winding its way through woodland, past natural lochans, and along the base of the hills. It is the epitome of \"bijou\" golf-small, perfectly formed, and utterly charming. However, do not let its beauty fool you; its defense lies in its tricky, small greens and the strategic requirement to place your ball on the correct side of the fairway.\r\n\r\nThe Queen\'s has hosted many notable figures over the decades, from Sean Connery to world leaders who appreciated its more tranquil, private feel. It is a course that emphasizes the \"joy of the game.\" Following recent renovations to restore Braid\'s original bunker shapes and fairway widths, the course plays as a true heathland gem. It is the perfect choice for a morning round where the focus is on the spectacular Highland scenery and the pure satisfaction of a well-struck iron shot into a secluded, pine-fringed green.', ''),
('gleneagleswee', 'Gleneagles - Wee', 'https://gleneagles.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.280564, -3.750537, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ed80eb8a19010ec0ac376a85e9234c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Wee Course at Gleneagles proves that great things come in small packages. Originally a 9-hole layout designed by George Alexander and later refined by the resort\'s professional staff, it serves as the perfect \"nursery\" for the championship courses. However, it is far more than just a beginner\'s track. It is a beautifully maintained par-three and par-four layout that features the same manicured turf and high-quality greens as its world-famous neighbors. It provides a relaxed environment for families, juniors, and those looking to sharpen their short game.\r\n\r\nThe course is located right in the heart of the resort, making it an easy addition to a golf-heavy itinerary. It has become a vital part of the Gleneagles Golf Academy, helping to introduce the next generation to the traditions of the game. For the seasoned golfer, the Wee Course offers a delightful challenge of wedge play and putting, all while enjoying the same crisp mountain air and luxury atmosphere of the wider estate. It is a testament to the club\'s philosophy that every golfer, regardless of age or ability, deserves a world-class experience.', ''),
('glengolfclub', 'Glen North Berwick', 'https://www.glengolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.057260, -2.702740, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.glengolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000073ba2c26369f05c03aafb14b54074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Glen Golf Club, also known as the \"East Links\" of North Berwick, offers a dramatic contrast to the town\'s famous West Links. While the West is a traditional low-lying links, the Glen is perched atop the rugged cliffs, offering a \"clifftop links\" experience that provides some of the most stunning views in golf. Founded in 1894, the course was originally a 9-hole layout before being extended by James Braid and Ben Sayers. Every hole offers a different perspective of the iconic Bass Rock, which sits just offshore, teeming with gannets.\r\n\r\nThe signature hole, the par-three 13th \"Sea Hole\" is one of the most photographed in Scotland; it requires a blind shot from an elevated tee toward a green tucked against a beach and a rock wall. The course has a vibrant history and a famously friendly membership. It provides a rugged, adventurous alternative to the more formal East Lothian courses. The wind here is a constant factor, and the elevation changes make for a physically engaging round. It is a must-play for anyone visiting the area who wants to experience the raw, natural beauty of the Firth of Forth.', ''),
('glenisla9', 'Glen Isla', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenisla9#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenisla9#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.621310, -3.205200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenisla9', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000151dc9e53fa409c0c1560916874f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the heart of the \"Valleys of Angus\" Glen Isla is a modern parkland course that was opened in 1994. Designed by Tony Wardle, who worked with the Robert Trent Jones design group, the course has a spacious, contemporary feel that makes great use of the Perthshire countryside. Unlike the tight, tree-lined corridors of older inland courses, Glen Isla offers wide, rolling fairways that encourage a more expansive style of play. The course is built on the site of an old farm, and many of the original drystone dykes have been incorporated into the design.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its excellent drainage and year-round playability, making it a popular choice for local golfers during the wetter months. While it may not have the ancient history of other clubs, it has built a strong reputation for its relaxed atmosphere and high-quality greens. The layout features several significant water hazards, particularly the burn that meanders through the back nine, requiring careful strategy. It is a peaceful, scenic retreat that offers a high-quality \"modern Scottish\" golfing experience at a very accessible price point.', ''),
('glenrothes', 'Glenrothes', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenrothes#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/glenrothes#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.186977, -3.211678, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'glenrothes', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f2423a3c84b109c0560dc2dcee174c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Glenrothes Golf Club is a premier municipal course located in the heart of Fife. Established in 1967 to serve the \"New Town\" of Glenrothes, the course was designed by the esteemed J.R. Stutt. It is a sprawling, 18-hole parkland layout that offers a sense of space and tranquility rarely found in an urban setting. The course is characterized by its significant undulations and large, well-protected greens. Because it was designed as part of a modern urban plan, the routing is excellent, providing a smooth and logical flow from hole to hole.\r\n\r\nThe club is a hub of competitive amateur golf in Fife, regularly hosting county events and regional qualifying. It is particularly known for its challenging closing stretch, where a series of long par-fours can make or break a scorecard. The course is maintained to a high standard, reflecting the town\'s pride in its sporting facilities. For visitors, Glenrothes offers a welcoming, \"no-frills\" golfing experience that focuses on the quality of the layout and the warmth of the local community. It is a fantastic example of the high-quality public golf that makes Scotland the envy of the world.', ''),
('gogarburn', 'Gogarburn', 'https://gogarburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://gogarburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.932691, -3.343357, 0, 0, '', '', 'gogarburn', 1908, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000046d26ef431bf0ac003232f6b62f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gogarburn Golf Club is a unique 12-hole course located on the western fringes of Edinburgh, near the airport. It is a club with a fascinating history, having originally been the private course for the staff of the nearby Gogarburn Hospital. Today, it is a thriving independent club that provides a vital service for golfers looking for a high-quality, \"quick\" round. The 12-hole format is increasingly popular for modern lifestyles, allowing for a satisfying game of golf that fits into a busy schedule.\r\n\r\nThe course is a lush parkland layout, featuring mature trees and remarkably well-kept greens. Despite its proximity to the city and the airport, it feels surprisingly secluded and peaceful. The layout is relatively flat, making it an easy walk for golfers of all ages. Gogarburn has a reputation for being one of the friendliest clubs in the Lothians, with a compact but lively clubhouse that serves as the heart of the community. It is a perfect example of how the game is adapting to the 21st century while maintaining the traditional values of Scottish golf.', ''),
('golfit', 'Golf It', 'https://www.golf-it.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.877123, -4.176904, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000058207a5226b510c0e2c8039145f04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Golf It! is the newest and most revolutionary addition to the list, representing the cutting edge of golf development. Located on the banks of Hogganfield Loch in Glasgow, this is a community-focused \"hub\" rather than a traditional golf club. Opened by The R&A in 2023, the facility includes a redesigned 9-hole course, adventure golf, a double-decker driving range, and padel courts. The goal of Golf It! is to make golf accessible to everyone, regardless of background or experience, in a fun, non-intimidating environment.\r\n\r\nThe 9-hole course was designed to be \"short but sharp\" offering a fun challenge for experienced players while remaining playable for beginners. There is no dress code, and the focus is firmly on inclusivity and enjoyment. The facility also serves as a vocational center, providing jobs and training for local young people. While it doesn\'t have the \"Old Tom Morris\" pedigree, it is arguably one of the most important sites in modern Scottish golf, proving that the game can be a vibrant, accessible, and essential part of modern city life.', ''),
('golspie', 'Golspie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/golspie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/golspie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.964870, -3.990210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'golspie', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000095607138f3eb0fc01d7233dc80fb4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Golspie Golf Club is a hidden gem of the Northern Highlands that offers one of the most varied and intereting rounds of golf in the country. Designed in 1889 by the local professional and later refined by James Braid, the course is a unique \"triple threat\": it begins as a pure links, moves into a stretch of heathland, and then finishes in a lush parkland setting. This variety means that in a single round, you will encounter sand dunes, gorse-lined fairways, and mature woodland.\r\n\r\nThe course sits in the shadow of Ben Bhraggie and offers spectacular views across the Dornoch Firth. It is often overshadowed by its famous neighbor, Royal Dornoch, but many connoisseurs of the game argue that Golspie is equally enjoyable due to its eclectic layout. The club has a warm, traditional feel and is a regular host of the Highland Golf Week. One of the most famous features is the 16th hole, a par-three played toward the sea that requires a steady nerve. Golspie is the quintessential \"hidden gem\" that rewards the traveler who ventures further north.\r\n', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/UttMAV1lz4g?si=k8Ig9kVj5V0HSQB3'),
('gourock', 'Gourock', 'https://www.gourockgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.gourockgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.946340, -4.843449, 0, 2294, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000028603b18b15f13c0c5724bab21f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Gourock Golf Club, perched on the hills above the Firth of Clyde, offers views that are frequently described as the best in Scottish golf. From the clubhouse and the higher holes, you can see the gateway to the Highlands, the Argyll Hills, and the Holy Loch. Founded in 1896, the course moved to its current location in 1925, with a layout that utilizes the rugged, sloping moorland to create a physically demanding and visually spectacular test of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club is a pioneer in modern technology, being one of the first in Scotland to install a full-scale Toptracer driving range alongside its traditional course. The layout itself is characterized by its narrow fairways and undulating terrain, requiring players to be creative with their shot-making. Gourock has a strong local membership and is known for its social atmosphere. While the climb can be steep, the exhilaration of hitting a drive from one of the elevated tees into the valley belowwith the Clyde shimmering in the distanceis a feeling that every golfer should experience.', ''),
('Grangemouth', 'Grangemouth', 'https://www.grangemouthgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 55.996225, -3.686666, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007b336abe4a7e0dc0933a014d84ff4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Grangemouth Golf Club is a polished parkland course that serves as a testament to the high standards of public golf in Scotland. While the club\'s history dates back to 1909, the current layout was designed in 1974 by the esteemed F.W. Hawtree, a member of the oldest golf course design firm in the world. Hawtree brought a sense of modern championship scale to the site, creating a par-71 course that is famously long and testing. The fairways are broad and inviting, but the strategic placement of mature trees and large, undulating greens ensures that a low score is never guaranteed.\r\n\r\nThe course is widely recognized for its exceptional drainage and year-round conditioning, often remaining open when other local courses are closed due to rain. This reliability has made it a popular venue for regional PGA events and amateur tournaments alike. While the town is known for its industrial heritage, the course itself is a peaceful, green sanctuary. Its signature hole, the 14th, requires a precise approach to a green guarded by significant bunkering. It is a friendly, accessible club that prides itself on offering a high-quality \"touring professional\" experience to the local community and visitors.', ''),
('grantownonspey', 'Grantown on Spey', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/grantownonspey#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/grantownonspey#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.333724, -3.594991, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'grantownonspey', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008f5033a48ac20cc0f5f1d077b7aa4c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Set within the heart of the Cairngorms National Park, Grantown-on-Spey Golf Club is a masterclass in Highland golf design. Established in 1890, the course was originally the work of Willie Park Jr., with later refinements made by the legendary James Braid in 1921. This \"double-architect\" pedigree is evident in the clever routing, which takes players through a diverse mix of lush parkland and rugged woodland. The backdrop of the Cromdale Hills and the Cairngorm mountains provides a cinematic setting that has captivated golfers for over a century.\r\n\r\nThe course is particularly famous for its spectacular closing holes. The 16th, \"Murdie\'s View\" offers a panoramic vista that is frequently cited as one of the best in the Highlands. The club has a long history of tourism, attracting many notable visitors who seek the tranquility of the Speyside region. Grantown has also produced numerous high-level amateurs, reflecting the quality of the challenge. It is a course that rewards strategy over brute force, with Braid\'s signature bunkering requiring careful thought. For any golfer touring the whisky-rich Spey Valley, this course is an essential stop that blends historic design with natural grandeur.', ''),
('greenburn', 'Greenburn', 'https://greenburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://greenburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'central', 'Yes', 55.821238, -3.704642, 0, 0, '', '', 'greenburn', 1765, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b11a4b581ba30dc0c11da8531ee94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Greenburn Golf Club, located near the village of Fauldhouse in West Lothian, is a charming moorland-style course with a history rooted in the local coal-mining community. The club was instituted in 1894 and has moved several times before settling into its current, well-established layout. The course sits on high ground, offering sweeping views of the surrounding hills and the central belt. Its character is defined by its firm, springy turf and the ever-present Highland breeze, which makes the relatively modest yardage play much longer than it appears on the scorecard.\r\n\r\nWhile it may not have a \"celebrity\" architect attached to its modern iteration, the course is a model of traditional Scottish golf. It features natural hazards like ditches and patches of rushes that require accurate ball-striking to avoid. The club is known for its resilient, competitive membership and a clubhouse that radiates local hospitality. It is a course that demands respect, particularly on the par-threes, which are often cited as the layout\'s strongest defense. For those looking for an authentic, unpretentious round of golf in a rugged landscape, Greenburn offers a high-value experience that captures the true spirit of the Scottish game.', ''),
('greenock', 'Greenock', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/greenock#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.950728, -4.779566, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'greenock', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004d4bac8c461e13c01cb28174b1f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched in a commanding position high above the town, Greenock Golf Club offers some of the most stunning vistas in the country, looking across the Clyde Estuary toward the Argyll hills. Founded in 1890, the club made a significant move in 1924 when they invited the \"busiest of all architects\" James Braid, to redesign the layout. Braid recommended purchasing the leased farmland to create a truly permanent and professional facility. The result was a majestic 18-hole moorland course that remains one of the premier tests in the West of Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its wide, wind-swept fairways and large, undulating greens that Braid designed to be both fair and challenging. Over the decades, the club has hosted many prestigious events, including regional qualifying for the Open Championship. Its most famous member in the modern era is likely the professional Stephen Gallacher, who has often praised the course\'s strategic depth. With its dramatic elevation changes and the sound of the wind through the trees, playing Greenock is an atmospheric experience that combines championship-standard architecture with the raw beauty of the Renfrewshire hills.', ''),
('greenockwee', 'Greenock - Wee', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/greenock#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.950728, -4.779566, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'greenock', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004d4bac8c461e13c01cb28174b1f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The \"Wee Course\" at Greenock is a delightful 9-hole layout that shares the same spectacular hillside site as its larger 18-hole sibling. Also part of the 1924 James Braid redesign, this course was intended to provide a high-quality alternative for those with limited time or those looking to hone their short game. Despite its name, the Wee Course is built to the same exacting standards as the championship layout, featuring Braid\'s signature strategic bunkering and undulating green complexes that demand a sharp touch with the putter.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a par-32 and measures just over 2,100 yards, but its defense lies in its free-draining nature and the natural hazards of the parkland terrain. The stretch from the 4th to the 8th hole is particularly acclaimed, featuring elevated tees that provide \"eye-level\" views of the River Clyde. It is a popular choice for juniors and seniors, serving as a vital nursery for the club\'s talent. Playing the Wee Course allows golfers to experience the genius of Braid on a smaller canvas, making it a perfect addition to a day of golf at Greenock for those who simply can\'t get enough of the view.', ''),
('greenockwhinhill', 'Greenock Whinhill', 'https://greenockwhinhill.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.935805, -4.762385, 0, 0, '', '', 'greenockwhinhill', 9755, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000006d847a7ae0c13c076374f75c8f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1911, Greenock Whinhill Golf Club is a rugged and charismatic 18-hole moorland course that sits adjacent to the Greenock club. The course was designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, whose philosophy of working with the natural \"lie of the land\" is evident in every hole. While it is a relatively short par-68, the Whinhill is famously difficult to \"master\" due to its unpredictable lies and the natural gorse and heather that line the fairways. It offers a raw, traditional golfing experience that contrasts with the more manicured parkland courses nearby.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for having one of the most unusual starts in golf: a challenging par-three opening hole that immediately tests the player\'s nerves. Whinhill has a loyal and fiercely competitive membership, often producing strong results in local Renfrewshire county tournaments. The panoramic views over the Clyde and the surrounding mountains are as dramatic as those of any course in the region. It is a \"working man\'s\" course in the best sensehonest, tough, and full of character. For golfers who enjoy the challenge of navigating natural obstacles in a windswept environment, Whinhill is a true hidden gem.', ''),
('gullane', 'Gullane - 1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'No', 'Gullane No. 1 is the flagship of the three courses at Gullane and is a titan of world golf. While golf has been played on this site since the mid-17th century, the course reached its current form in 1884. Its architect is officially unknown, though it has been refined by many hands over the years. It is a championship links that has hosted almost every major event in the game, including Final Qualifying for the Open and the Scottish Open in 2015 and 2018 (won by Rickie Fowler and Brandon Stone, respectively).\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for the \"King\'s Chair\" a natural stone formation on the 7th hole that offers what is widely considered the best view in golf-a 360-degree panorama of East Lothian, the Firth of Forth, and Fife. Notable members have included legends like Babe Zaharias and Peter Thomson. The turf here is the gold standard of links golf: firm, fast, and remarkably free-draining. With its deep revetted bunkers and \"perfect\" greens, Gullane No. 1 is an uncompromising test of skill that requires every shot in the bag, all played out on some of the most historic links land in existence.', ''),
('gullane2', 'Gullane - 2', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 3, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Laid out in 1898 by the two-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr., Gullane No. 2 runs alongside its older sibling for the first few holes before sweeping down toward the Aberlady Bay nature reserve. Park, who also designed Sunningdale, brought a refined architectural eye to the links, creating a layout that many members actually prefer to No. 1 for its variety and flow. At over 6,300 yards, it is a formidable championship course in its own right and has frequently been used for Final Qualifying for the Open Championship.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its collection of par-threes, particularly the 11th, which features a long carry to a green framed by breathtaking coastal views. Champions from Babe Zaharias to Peter Thomson have triumphed here, cementing its reputation as a high-caliber venue. The transition from the high ridges of the hill to the lower coastal land provides a fascinating tactical shift mid-round. Gullane No. 2 offers all the charm and challenge of the Gullane hill-including the same impeccable conditioning-but with a unique character that emphasizes the beauty of the East Lothian coastline.', ''),
('gullane3', 'Gullane - 3', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gullane', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.034281, -2.837353, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gullane', 5, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000efa83121e6b206c0e5efde5163044c40, 'links', 'No', 'Gullane No. 3 may be the shortest of the trio, but it is often described as the most \"fun\" course on the hill. Another Willie Park Jr. masterpiece, opened in 1910, No. 3 was designed to emphasize shot-making and accuracy over raw power. Despite its modest yardage, it is maintained to the exact same championship standards as the other two courses, offering the same firm links turf and lightning-fast greens. It is the perfect venue for those who appreciate the strategic \"short game\" side of golf.\r\n\r\nThe course offers some of the most intimate views of the village and the Firth of Forth. Because it is less physically demanding than No. 1 and No. 2, it is a favorite for those playing 36 holes in a day. However, the small, tricky greens and the 100-plus bunkers ensure that it is no soft option. It celebrated its centenary in 2010 and remains a beloved part of the Gullane landscape. For many visitors, No. 3 is the \"secret favorite\"-a course that proves you don\'t need 7,000 yards to have a world-class golfing experience in the heart of East Lothian.', ''),
('haddington', 'Haddington', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haddington#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haddington#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.957044, -2.758470, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'haddington', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001afa27b8581106c0a16af46a80fa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Haddington Golf Club claims a remarkable place in the history of the game as the 19th oldest golf course in the world. Founded in 1865, the club eventually settled at its current home, Amisfield Park, in 1960. The land was formerly a grand 18th-century estate, and while the mansion was demolished in 1928, the historic stable block and walled garden still remain, providing a stately atmosphere. The course is a lush, mature parkland layout that offers a peaceful alternative to the nearby windswept links of the East Lothian coast.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its wide, inviting fairways and the River Tyne, which meanders along the boundary and comes into play on several holes. One of the highlights is the \"Quarry Hole\" a challenging par-three played uphill over a cliff face. While it hasn\'t hosted the professional majors of its coastal neighbors, Haddington is a pillar of the local community and a frequent host of Lothians county championships. It is a traditional, friendly club where history and nature combine to provide a relaxed but testing round of golf in one of Scotland\'s most beautiful market towns.', ''),
('haggscastle', 'Haggs Castle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/haggscastle#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.834630, -4.319715, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1594, 'haggscastle', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009e29745e634711c05721e527d5ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Haggs Castle Golf Club is widely regarded as one of the premier parkland courses in the West of Scotland. Set within the lush, wooded grounds of Pollok Country Park on the outskirts of Glasgow, the course was designed in 1910 by the prolific James Braid. Braid\'s genius is on full display here, as he utilized the rolling terrain and mature oaks to create a layout that feels both grand and intimate. The course famously hosted the Scottish Open in 1986, which saw David Feherty claim victory, as well as several other European Tour events throughout the 1980s.\r\n\r\nThe club takes its name from the historic Haggs Castle, built in 1585, which stands near the entrance. Notable members have included some of Glasgow\'s most prominent industrial and sporting figures. The course is known for its impeccably fast greens and its challenging closing stretch, where the tree-lined fairways demand absolute precision. Despite being located just minutes from the city center, Haggs Castle provides a serene, high-caliber golfing experience that maintains a championship standard of conditioning year-round. It remains a \"must-play\" for those who value the strategic depth of a classic Braid parkland design.', ''),
('hamilton', 'Hamilton', 'https://www.hamiltongolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.761277, -4.007059, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e29178793a0710c03719558671e14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hamilton Golf Club is an aristocratic parkland gem situated in the historic town of Hamilton. Founded in 1892, the course was significantly redesigned by James Braid in 1925, who transformed it into the challenging and scenic layout that exists today. The course is characterized by its dramatic elevation changes and a series of deep ravines that come into play on several of the most memorable holes. The fairways are lined with a diverse range of mature trees, including majestic copper beeches, which provide a stunning color palette throughout the seasons.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of hosting top-tier amateur and professional events, including the Scottish Professional Championship. It has produced many talented golfers over the years, most notably Belle Robertson, one of the most decorated female amateur golfers in history and a member of the World Golf Hall of Fame. The signature \"ravine holes\" require both nerve and accuracy, as any wayward shot is likely to disappear into the lush undergrowth. With its grand clubhouse and a reputation for providing a stern test of ball-striking, Hamilton is a quintessential example of high-end Scottish inland golf.', ''),
('harburn', 'Harburn', 'https://harburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://harburn.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.830085, -3.543056, 0, 0, '', '', 'harburn', 93, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000302c7fbe2d580cc038f3ab3940ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Harburn Golf Club, located in West Lothian, is an atmospheric moorland-parkland hybrid that sits on the northern slopes of the Pentland Hills. Founded in 1925, the course was originally a 9-hole layout before being extended to 18 holes in the 1930s. At an elevation of over 800 feet, Harburn offers a refreshing \"mountain air\" experience and panoramic views that stretch across the central belt. The course is famously well-wooded, with thousands of trees planted over the decades to create a sheltered, forest-like environment on many of the holes.\r\n\r\nWhile Harburn may not have a \"famous name\" architect attached to its origins, the members themselves have refined the layout into a clever and testing course. It is known for its excellent drainage and high standard of maintenance. The club has a strong reputation for its inclusive and friendly social scene, making it a popular choice for visitors. The signature hole is the par-five 18th, which requires a climb back toward the clubhouse and provides a challenging finish to a round. It is a course that rewards the thinking golfer, as the narrow, tree-lined corridors punish those who try to overpower the layout.', ''),
('hawick', 'Hawick', 'https://www.hawickgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.hawickgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.411913, -2.799938, 0, 2311, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000069fe6e4456606c00ce6af90b9b44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hawick Golf Club is the oldest club in the Scottish Borders, founded in 1877. The course is situated on the Vertish Hill, a location that provides some of the most spectacular views in the region, overlooking the historic town and the surrounding Cheviot Hills. The layout was refined by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, who maximized the natural slopes of the hill to create a challenging and varied test of golf. The course is characterized by its undulating fairways, small greens, and the \"whins\" (gorse) that add a traditional Scottish bite to the round.\r\n\r\nThe club\'s most famous member is undoubtedly the legendary rugby commentator Bill McLaren, who was a lifelong supporter and frequent visitor to the fairways. Hawick is also known for producing high-quality amateur golfers who have excelled in the Borders circuit. The course is a physically demanding walk, but the reward is a series of elevated tees that allow for heroic drives into the valleys below. It is a traditional, unpretentious club that prides itself on its history and its warm Borders hospitality, making it a favorite for those touring the south of Scotland.', ''),
('hayston', 'Hayston', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hayston#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hayston#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.942564, -4.182918, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hayston', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001f662fdb4ebb10c08731e9efa5f84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Kirkintilloch, Hayston Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course that sits in the shadow of the Campsie Fells. Founded in 1922, the course was designed by the esteemed James Braid, who was a master at creating challenging green complexes. Hayston is known for its lush, mature woodland and the Kelvinside Burn, which meanders through the property and provides a natural hazard on several holes. The course has a \"championship\" feel, with well-placed bunkers and narrow fairways that require careful navigation.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history of hosting regional qualifying for the Open Championship and has been a frequent venue for the Glasgow Open. It is often cited as having some of the best-conditioned greens in the Dunbartonshire area. The layout is relatively flat, making it an enjoyable walk, but the strategic placement of Braid\'s hazards ensures that it remains a formidable test for low handicappers. Hayston is a traditional \"member-focused\" club that offers a professional and welcoming environment, perfectly blending historic design with the natural beauty of the Stirlingshire countryside.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('hazlehead', 'Hazlehead - MacKenzie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 56.487305, -3.015692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007d789620232008c0b1169f02603e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The MacKenzie Course at Hazlehead is the \"Crown Jewel\" of Aberdeen\'s municipal golf offering. Designed in 1920 by the legendary Dr. Alister MacKenziethe man responsible for Augusta National and Cypress Pointit is one of the few places in the world where you can play a MacKenzie masterpiece for a public green fee. The course is a classic heathland-parkland hybrid, winding through dense pine forests and over rolling hills. MacKenzie\'s signature style is evident in the large, undulating greens and the strategic use of natural contours to defend par.\r\n\r\nThe course has a rich professional history, having hosted the Aberdeen City Open and many prestigious amateur championships. It is famously long and testing, particularly when the wind blows through the trees. Despite its municipal status, the course is maintained to a very high standard, reflecting the city\'s pride in its MacKenzie heritage. Playing here offers a fascinating glimpse into the early design philosophy of one of golf\'s greatest architects. It is a rugged, beautiful, and intellectually stimulating course that provides a world-class experience without the high price tag of a private club.', ''),
('hazlehead9', 'Hazlehead 9 Holer', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.137760, -2.181710, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead9', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006ad95a5f247401c03659a31ea2914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The 9-hole course at Hazlehead serves as the perfect entry point for beginners and a vital practice facility for the more experienced golfers of Aberdeen. While it lacks the international pedigree of its \"MacKenzie\" sibling, it is built on the same high-quality parkland terrain and offers a fun, relaxed environment. The layout is relatively short, but it features several challenging par-threes and narrow fairways that require a respectable level of accuracy. It is the quintessential \"nursery\" course, fostering a love for the game in generations of local Aberdonians.\r\n\r\nThe course is frequently used for \"Quick Golf\" and by families who want to enjoy the spectacular scenery of the Hazlehead estate without committing to a full four-hour round. It is remarkably well-maintained and provides a scenic escape from the urban hustle of the city. Because it shares the same clubhouse and facilities as the two 18-hole courses on the site, it benefits from a lively and professional atmosphere. It is a shining example of how public golf facilities can cater to every level of the game, ensuring that golf remains an accessible and central part of Scottish community life.', ''),
('hazleheadpines', 'Hazlehead - Pines', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/hazlehead#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 56.487305, -3.015692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'hazlehead', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007d789620232008c0b1169f02603e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Pines Course at Hazlehead is the perfect \"middle ground\" between the championship MacKenzie Course and the beginner-friendly 9-hole layout. Opened in the early 1970s and designed by John Stutt, the course was created to alleviate the pressure on the increasingly popular MacKenzie course. As its name suggests, the Pines is a heavily wooded parkland layout where the fairways are framed by magnificent corridors of Scots pine and larch. It offers a slightly more modern challenge, with wider fairways but smaller, more target-oriented greens.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its excellent drainage and for being a slightly easier walk than the hilly MacKenzie. However, don\'t let its \"second course\" status fool you; it is a stern test of golf in its own right and is a favorite for local society outings and corporate days. The Pines offers a sense of total seclusion, as the dense forest separates each hole from the next. It is a beautifully peaceful environment where the only sound is the wind through the needles and the occasional chatter of a red squirrel, providing a tranquil and high-quality round of Aberdeen parkland golf.', ''),
('helensburgh', 'Helensburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/helensburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/helensburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 56.013645, -4.707896, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'helensburgh', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007ae063b0e2d412c080608e1ebf014c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Helensburgh Golf Club, situated on the hills overlooking the Firth of Clyde and the Gare Loch, offers a dramatic moorland golfing experience. Founded in 1893, the course was redesigned by the legendary James Braid in the early 20th century. Braid\'s layout makes full use of the rugged, undulating terrain, requiring golfers to navigate natural gullies, heather-clad slopes, and the occasional rocky outcrop. The panoramic views from the higher holes, stretching toward the mountains of Loch Lomond and the Trossachs, are among the finest in the West of Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong connection to the local community and has produced many fine golfers who have excelled in Dunbartonshire county events. The course is known for its fast, true greens and its challenging \"out and back\" routing. While the wind is a frequent and formidable defender of the course, the springy moorland turf ensures that the playing conditions remain excellent throughout the year. It is a traditional, friendly club with a lively social atmosphere, offering a rugged and authentic Highland-edge golfing experience just a short train ride from the center of Glasgow.', ''),
('Helmsdale', 'Helmsdale', 'http://www.helmsdale.org/golf.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.121058, -3.657729, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d80b056c07430dc0a7751bd47e0f4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Helmsdale Golf Club is a stunning and remote 9-hole course located on the east coast of Sutherland, far into the Northern Highlands. Originally established in 1923, the course is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense, offering a raw and natural golfing experience that has remained largely unchanged for a century. The layout is a hybrid of links and hill-land, featuring massive elevation changes and views over the North Sea and the village of Helmsdale that are simply breathtaking. The course is maintained by a small team of dedicated local volunteers.\r\n\r\nThe most famous feature of Helmsdale is the climb to the higher holes, which requires a fair degree of fitness but rewards the golfer with a spectacular descent back toward the sea. The layout is quirky and charismatic, with small greens perched on natural plateaus. It is a \"honesty box\" club where the focus is on the sheer enjoyment of the game in a wild and beautiful setting. For golfers exploring the North Coast 500, a stop at Helmsdale is a mandatory pilgrimage to experience the soul of Highland golfunpretentious, incredibly scenic, and deeply rooted in the local landscape.', ''),
('hiltonpark', 'Hilton Park - Hilton', 'https://hiltonpark.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.968482, -4.361614, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005d1abff04a7211c0e161da37f7fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Situated just ten miles from Glasgow but feeling worlds apart, Hilton Park is home to two of the finest moorland courses in Scotland. The Hilton Course, the longer of the two, was designed in 1927 by the five-time Open Champion James Braid. It is a majestic layout that offers sweeping views of the Campsie Fells to the north and the city of Glasgow to the south. The course is famous for its strategic demand; Braid\'s original vision was so challenging that he actually had to return to soften it slightly for the membership.\r\n\r\nThe club was the home course for PGA Tour winner Martin Laird during his formative years. One of its most distinctive features is the 17th hole, known as the \"Muckle Drap\" a dramatic par-three that plays from an elevated tee to a green far below. Legend also has it that an unexploded WWII shell remains buried beneath the 1st green, adding a unique (if quiet) bit of history to your opening shot.', ''),
('hiltonparkallander', 'Hilton Park - Allander', 'https://hiltonpark.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.968482, -4.361614, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005d1abff04a7211c0e161da37f7fb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Allander Course, also designed by James Braid, is shorter than its sibling but arguably tighter and more demanding of accuracy. While the Hilton Course allows for a few wayward drives, the Allander rewards the golfer who can shape shots through mature woodland and navigate the natural moorland hazards. It is named after the River Allander, which flows nearby, and it shares the same spectacular views of the Highland fringe.\r\n\r\nBecause both courses are maintained to a high standard, the Allander is often used for prestigious regional tournaments and serves as a vital part of the club\'s vibrant competitive scene. It is a favorite for those who enjoy \"thinking\" their way around a course rather than relying on power. The two courses together make Hilton Park one of the most substantial and high-quality golfing complexes in the West of Scotland.', ''),
('HoddomCastle', 'Hoddom Castle', 'https://www.hoddomcastle.co.uk/activities', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.041556, -3.310412, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a1496249b97b0ac0ee79feb451854b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set within the historic grounds of a 16th-century tower house near Annan, Hoddom Castle Golf Club offers a 9-hole parkland experience steeped in character. The course winds through ancient woodland and along the banks of the River Annan. It is a quintessential \"country estate\" course, where the focus is on natural beauty and a relaxed atmosphere. The castle itself provides a stunning backdrop to several holes.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its peaceful environment and its ability to challenge golfers of all levels with its variety of shots. It is a popular spot for visitors staying in the local caravan park and estate cottages, offering a high-quality \"holiday golf\" experience. While it doesn\'t host professional tour events, its charm lies in its simplicity and the historic weight of its surroundings.', ''),
('hollandbush', 'Hollandbush', 'https://hollandbush.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.613276, -3.885465, 0, 0, '', '', 'hollandbush', 306, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000680586ac6e150fc0fab5f5d37fce4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Hollandbush Golf Club, located in South Lanarkshire, is an 18-hole course that sits on the edge of the moorland, offering a distinct \"inland links\" feel. The club has its roots in the 1920s but was formally established in 1954 through the dedication of local miners and residents. The course was originally a 9-hole layout designed by James Lawson before being expanded by the local council to its current 18-hole form.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its panoramic views of the Southern Uplandson clear days, you can see as far as Ben More and Ben Vorlich. It is a rugged, honest course that emphasizes the community spirit of Scottish golf. The club recently named its lounge after Jim Hamilton, a founding member who served the club for 50 years, reflecting the deep personal history embedded in the fairways.', ''),
('hopemangolf', 'Hopeman', 'https://www.hopemangolf.club/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.709953, -3.419223, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.hopemangolf.club', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001bd99596915a0bc03a596abddfda4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Hopeman Golf Club is home to one of the most famous par-threes in Scotland. Located on the Moray Firth coast, this links course was originally a 9-hole design from 1909, later expanded to 18 holes in 1985. The legendary Paul Lawrie, the 1999 Open Champion, is an Honorary President and has described the signature 12th hole, \"The Prieshach\" as the best par-three he has ever played. The tee sits over 100 feet above a green nestled in a cove by the sea.\r\n\r\nThe course is a visual masterpiece, with gorse-lined fairways and the chance to spot dolphins playing in the Firth during your round. It is a rugged, windswept test that rewards accuracy over length. The club also counts former Prime Minister Ramsay MacDonald among its past honorary members, cementing its status as a cornerstone of Moray\'s golfing heritage.', ''),
('huntly', 'Huntly', 'https://huntly.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://huntly.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.454266, -2.774880, 0, 0, '', '', 'huntly', 1743, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000089981249f43206c0a5d7666325ba4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Huntly Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course in Aberdeenshire with a history that involves a consultation with Old Tom Morris himself. Established in 1892, the course sits between the River Bogie and the River Deveron. While it began as a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes in the 1930s. The layout is undulating and tree-lined, providing a classic inland challenge.\r\n\r\nThe club has a reputation for producing high-caliber professional talent, including John and David Chillas, both of whom went on to play on the European Tour. Huntly is known for its warm welcome and its remarkably consistent playing surfaces. The signature holes along the rivers require a steady hand and precise club selection, making it one of the most respected parkland tests in the North East.', ''),
('inbereshieestate', 'Invereshie Estate', 'https://invereshieestate.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.121485, -3.914198, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000828c800a47500fc02ffa0ad28c8f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Invereshie is a unique entrya private 9-hole course located within the historic Invereshie Estate in the heart of the Cairngorms National Park. The course is primarily available to guests staying in the estate\'s cottages. Set amongst Douglas Firs planted in the 1830s, it offers a serene, \"secret garden\" golfing experience where you are more likely to see red squirrels and roe deer than other golfers.\r\n\r\nThe course is natural and unpretentious, reflecting the wild beauty of Speyside. It isn\'t a championship venue in the traditional sense, but it represents the \"soul\" of Scottish estate golfa private playground carved out of a majestic Highland landscape. It is the perfect retreat for those who want to practice their game in total isolation surrounded by mountains.', ''),
('inchmarlo', 'Inchmarlo', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inchmarlo#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inchmarlo#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.058692, -2.531822, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inchmarlo', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b4588ae42b4104c0b7442e3883874c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in Banchory in the heart of Royal Deeside, the Queen\'s Course at Inchmarlo is a high-quality 9-hole layout designed by Graeme Webster. Opened in 1997, it was built to USGA standards, offering greens and fairways of exceptional quality. The course is characterized by its strategic bunkering and the spectacular views of the surrounding hills.\r\n\r\nInchmarlo is a premier training facility, featuring an extensive floodlit driving range and a short-game academy. The Queen\'s Course is designed to be \"fun but challenging\" making it a favorite for those looking to sharpen their skills before tackling the major courses of the North East. It provides a modern, professional resort atmosphere in one of Scotland\'s most scenic regions.', ''),
('Innellan', 'Innellan', 'https://www.innellangolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.898647, -4.955716, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000450e1137a7d213c002d369dd06f34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Innellan Golf Club, perched on the hills above the Firth of Clyde near Dunoon, is a rugged 9-hole moorland course that offers what many call the best views in the West of Scotland. Founded in 1891, the course is a physical test, with steep climbs rewarded by panoramic vistas of the Cumbrae islands and the Ayrshire coast.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its Royal Hotel Trophy, a prestigious open competition that attracts players from across the region. The greens are small and tricky, often protected by the natural contours of the hill rather than artificial bunkers. It is a traditional \"village\" club where the atmosphere is as memorable as the elevation changes, embodying the grit and beauty of Argyll golf.', ''),
('innerleithen', 'Innerleithen', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/innerleithen#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/innerleithen#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.640109, -3.056931, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'innerleithen', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005307793d987408c009707a17efd14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Innerleithen Golf Club is a delightful 9-hole course set in the Leithen Valley in the Scottish Borders. Designed by the three-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr. and established in 1886, it is a masterclass in utilizing a river as a natural hazard. The Leithen Water meanders through the course, coming into play on several holes and providing a soothing soundtrack to the round.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its \"Rockies\" feel, as it is surrounded by high hills on all sides. While it is a 9-hole layout, it features varying tee positions for the second nine to create an 18-hole experience. The opening par-three is notoriously difficult, requiring a shot over a road and a river. It is a friendly, scenic, and historic club that offers a tranquil escape in one of the most beautiful valleys in the Borders.', ''),
('insch', 'Insch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/insch#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/insch#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.345883, -2.621639, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'insch', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005c5837de1df904c0069fe6e445ac4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Insch Golf Club is a hidden treasure in the shadow of the spectacular Dunnideer Hill and its ancient hillfort. Founded in 1906 as a 9-hole course, it was extended to a full 18 holes in 1997, a project that transformed it into a modern parkland test with a distinct \"Highland edge.\" The layout is split between the older, flatter holes and the newer section, which climbs the hillside to offer panoramic views across the Garioch valley toward the peak of Bennachie.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its narrow, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally tricky greens. While it may not have a \"celebrity\" architect, the quality of the layout is a testament to the dedication of the local community who built it. Insch has gained a reputation for its conditioning, often described as a \"mini-Gleneagles\" by those who discover it. The signature 13th hole, \"Bennachie View\" requires a precise drive to a sloping fairway and provides one of the most photographed vistas in Aberdeenshire. It is a welcoming, traditional club where the spirit of the local village is as strong as the challenge on the course.', ''),
('inverallochygolfclub', 'Inverallochy', 'https://www.inverallochygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.inverallochygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.660228, -1.936152, 0, 2328, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000215c01857afafebfa5f3e15982d44c40, 'links', 'No', 'Inverallochy Golf Club is a pure, traditional links located on the rugged coast of the Buchan peninsula. This is a course where the sea is your constant companion; it is situated so close to the water that sea spray often coats the greens. Originally a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes by the legendary James Braid in the 1920s. Braid utilized the natural sand dunes and the firm, sandy turf to create a layout that feels as though it was discovered rather than built.\r\n\r\nThe course has a unique \"out and back\" routing that is heavily influenced by the North Sea gales. It is a short par-63, but the lack of length is more than compensated for by the tight fairways and the encroaching gorse. Inverallochy is famous for its six par-threes, each playing in a different direction to ensure the wind never attacks the same way twice. Notable members have included several titans of the local fishing industry, and the club maintains a rugged, unpretentious atmosphere. For those seeking the rawest form of links golf in a remote, beautiful setting, Inverallochy is an absolute must-play.', ''),
('Inveraray', 'Inveraray', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.220870, -5.086394, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000524832ab775814c07155d977451c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Inveraray Golf Club offers a truly regal setting on the shores of Loch Fyne. This 9-hole parkland course is located within the grounds of the historic Inveraray Castle, the ancestral home of the Duke of Argyll. Established in 1893, the course was redesigned in the 1920s by James Braid, who was invited by the Duke to create a layout worthy of the spectacular estate. The result is a course that winds through mature woodland and along the shoreline, offering views of the castle and the surrounding mountains that are second to none.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its peaceful, secluded atmosphere; you are more likely to hear the cry of an eagle or the splashing of a seal than any urban noise. While it is not a long course, Braid\'s strategic bunkering and the natural undulations of the estate land require a thoughtful approach. The 19th hole, located in the village, is a favorite for visitors who want to sample the world-famous local seafood after their round. It is a quintessential Highland estate course that blends high-level architecture with the timeless elegance of one of Scotland\'s most famous historical landmarks.', ''),
('invergordon', 'Invergordon', 'https://www.invergordongolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.invergordongolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.694398, -4.191557, 0, 2330, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008d47a98427c410c033349e08e2d84c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Invergordon Golf Club is a lush parkland course situated on the shores of the Cromarty Firth. The club\'s history is inextricably linked to the military; the land was formerly used as a naval base during both World Wars, and the clubhouse was once a naval officer\'s mess. The 18-hole course was designed by the prolific J.R. Stutt, who was a close associate of James Braid. Stutt took advantage of the mild coastal climate to create a course that features an extraordinary array of mature trees and rhododendrons, making it a spectacular sight in the spring.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its wide fairways and large, receptive greens, which are often cited as some of the best-conditioned in the Highlands. It has a \"resort\" feel, offering a more relaxed challenge than the punishing links of the nearby Moray Firth. One of the highlights is the view of the massive oil rigs being refurbished in the Firth, a unique industrial backdrop that contrasts with the natural beauty of the course. Invergordon is a friendly, community-focused club that provides a high-quality, scenic round of golf for players of all abilities.', ''),
('inverness', 'Inverness', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverness#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverness#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.471974, -4.204219, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inverness', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000026e318c91ed110c0fa47dfa469bc4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Inverness Golf Club is the premier parkland venue in the capital of the Highlands. Established in 1883, the course was significantly redesigned by George Smith and later refined by James Braid in the 1930s. Braid\'s influence is clear in the strategic bunkering and the clever routing that makes the course feel remarkably secluded despite its proximity to the city center. It is a classic parkland layout, characterized by its narrow, tree-lined fairways and the Culcabock Burn, which comes into play on several of the most challenging holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a long history of hosting top-tier amateur and professional events, including the Northern Open and the Scottish North District Championships. Notable members have included several Scottish internationalists, and the club maintains a high standard of etiquette and tradition. The signature hole, the par-four 14th, requires a precise drive to avoid the trees and a nerve-wracking approach over the burn. With its magnificent clubhouse and a reputation for fast, true greens, Inverness Golf Club offers a polished and professional golfing experience that serves as the perfect centerpiece for a Highland golf tour.', ''),
('inverurie', 'Inverurie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverurie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/inverurie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.278666, -2.394214, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'inverurie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b4006dab592703c0ea40d653aba34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the heart of the \"Garioch\" Inverurie Golf Club is a scenic parkland course that offers spectacular views of the Don Valley and the peaks of the Grampian Mountains. Originally established as a 9-hole course in 1902, it was expanded to 18 holes in the 1920s with input from the legendary James Braid. The course is built on a hillside, providing a variety of lies and a physical test that requires a fair degree of fitness. The fairways are lined with a mix of broom, gorse, and mature woodland, giving the course a colorful and natural feel.\r\n\r\nInverurie is known for its firm, well-draining turf and its remarkably consistent greens. The club has produced many talented golfers over the decades and remains a competitive hub in the Aberdeenshire region. The signature hole is the 18th, a challenging par-four that requires a climb back toward the elevated clubhouse, offering a dramatic finish to the round. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on its accessibility and its warm \"North East\" welcome. For those who enjoy the challenge of undulating terrain and the beauty of the Highland foothills, Inverurie is an essential stop.', ''),
('irvine', 'Irvine', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/irvine#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.626590, -4.685650, 0, 0, '', '', '', 2689, 'irvine', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000075029a081bbe12c01500e31934d04b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Irvine Golf Club, commonly known as Bogside, is a heavyweight of Scottish golf. This is a traditional links course that has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship on numerous occasions. Originally founded in 1887, the course was redesigned in 1926 by the great James Braid. Unlike many coastal links that are flat, Bogside is characterized by its massive ridges and deep hollows, which were created by the retreating sea centuries ago. The course is famously divided by a railway line, adding a unique industrial aesthetic to the rugged coastal landscape.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history, hosting the Scottish Amateur Championship and the Scottish Professional Championship. Its most famous member is likely the former Ryder Cup player Bernhard Langer, who won the European Open here in 1980. The turf at Bogside is the quintessence of links golf-firm, sandy, and fast-running. With its deep pot bunkers and the ever-present gorse, it is an uncompromising test of ball-striking. The traditional clubhouse is a treasure trove of golfing history, reflecting Irvine\'s status as one of the most respected and challenging links in the country.', ''),
('IrvineRavenspark', 'Irvine Ravenspark', 'https://www.irgc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.631399, -4.680627, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002f19c748f6b812c012ddb3aed1d04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just inland from the famous Bogside links, Irvine Ravenspark is a high-quality municipal course that offers a fascinating hybrid of links and parkland golf. Opened in 1907 to provide accessible golf to the local community, the course was refined by the esteemed architect J.R. Stutt. It features the same sandy, free-draining soil as its illustrious neighbor, ensuring excellent playing conditions year-round. While the front nine has a more open, links-like feel, the back nine moves into a more wooded environment with several challenging water hazards.\r\n\r\nRavenspark has a strong reputation for producing high-caliber amateur talent, including several Scottish internationalists. The course has frequently hosted regional qualifying for the Open Championship and the Scottish Public Courses Championship. One of the highlights of the round is the stretch of holes that run alongside the River Irvine, requiring precise club selection and a steady nerve. It is a friendly, inclusive club that prides itself on offering a championship-standard test at a public price point. For many local golfers, Ravenspark is the \"people\'s favorite\" providing a varied and engaging round of golf in the heart of Ayrshire.', ''),
('IsleofGigha', 'Isle of Gigha', 'https://www.visitgigha.co.uk/Golf', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.684323, -5.741755, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f3936a9f8ef716c0477364e597d74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Isle of Gigha Golf Club offers one of the most unique and remote golfing experiences in the world. This 9-hole course is situated on a community-owned island off the Kintyre peninsula. Established in the early 20th century, the course is a \"natural links\" in the truest sense, with the routing dictated by the rugged shoreline and the ancient rocky outcrops of the island. The views from the coursestretching across the Atlantic to the Isles of Islay and Juraare simply breathtaking and often distract golfers from their game.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its lack of formality; there are no tee times, and the \"honesty box\" for green fees reflects the island\'s relaxed and trusting atmosphere. The layout is quirky and challenging, featuring blind shots and small greens that are perched on natural plateaus. It is a place where you can find total peace, with the only sounds being the waves and the wind. For the \"golfing adventurer\" a trip to Gigha is a mandatory pilgrimage to play a course that has remained unchanged by modern design, offering a pure and atmospheric connection to the origins of the game.', ''),
('IsleofHarris', 'Isle of Harris', 'https://www.harrisgolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 57.831904, -7.035926, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ec4d0cc9c9241cc0afb48cd47bea4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Isle of Harris Golf Club, situated at Scarista, is often cited as the most beautiful 9-hole course in the world. Originally laid out in 1912 by Alick Marling, the course famously overlooks the turquoise waters of the Atlantic and the white sands of the Hebrides. It lay dormant for decades after the war until a group of determined locals revived it in 1985. The \"Links of Harris\" is a raw, natural experience where the fairways are grazed by sheep and the hazards are dictated by the rugged shoreline.\r\n\r\nThe club gained global fame when Sir Nick Faldo played here in the early 1990s as a quiet retreat to sharpen his game for the Masters. He was so charmed by the place that he left a signed 5 note in the \"honesty box\" for his green fee; that same fiver is now framed in the clubhouse and serves as the trophy for the annual \"Faldo Fiver\" competition. Without a single bunker to speak of, the course relies on the wind and the punishing Atlantic surf to defend its par. It is a spiritual home for golfers who prefer the elements and the \"honesty\" of the game over manicured perfection.', ''),
('isleofseilgolfclub', 'Isle of Seil', 'https://www.isleofseilgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 56.290632, -5.607163, 0, 2339, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000705d3123bc6d16c0e695eb6d33254c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just over the famous \"Bridge Over the Atlantic\" the Isle of Seil Golf Club is a quirky and charming 9-hole course that defines community-led golf. Formed in 1995 after residents realized the island\'s potential for a local track, it was built primarily through the manual labor of its members. The course occupies the site of a 1910 layout that had been lost to time. It is a parkland-style course set on a working farm, meaning players must often negotiate the local livestock alongside the undulating fairways.\r\n\r\nWhile it does not have a \"celebrity\" architect, the routing was cleverly devised by the founding committee to maximize the views of the Slate Islands. The club is a pioneer in modern golf governance, having been one of the first in Scotland to consistently elect female captains based purely on merit. Its most notable tournament is the Highland Arts Burns Crystal, an 18-hole open that draws players from across Argyll. It is a \"social\" club in the best sense, where the 19th hole is often as important as the first, making it a favorite for those touring the Inner Hebrides.', ''),
('isleofskye', 'Isle of Skye', 'https://isleofskye.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://isleofskye.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'islands', 'No', 57.310196, -6.094685, 0, 0, '', '', 'isleofskye', 2975, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e2afc91af56018c0cdaca580b4a74c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Isle of Skye Golf Club, originally known as Sconser, sits in the dramatic shadow of the Cuillin Mountains. The course was designed in 1964 by the esteemed Dr. Frank Deighton, a former Walker Cup player and one of Scotland\'s most talented amateur golfers. Deighton\'s layout is a masterful use of a narrow strip of coastal land, offering a 9-hole experience with eighteen different tee positions that completely change the angle of attack for the second loop.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rugged history; for years, electric fences were required around the greens to keep the local sheep at bay. In 1987, the club rebranded to its current name to better reflect its status as the island\'s premier golfing destination. Famous for its \"Sea Hole\" where a wayward slice will see your ball vanish into the Raasay Sound, the course is a visual masterpiece. Deighton was so fond of his creation that his ashes were scattered on the fairways following his passing in 2018. It is a course that requires a low ball flight and a steady nerve, particularly when the Highland mist rolls off the peaks.', ''),
('jedburgh', 'Jedburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/jedburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/jedburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'No', 55.470625, -2.584005, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'jedburgh', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000959a3dd00aac04c00ad7a3703dbc4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Jedburgh Golf Club is a scenic parkland course that embodies the quiet dignity of the Scottish Borders. Founded in 1893, the course was significantly improved in the early 20th century with input from the legendary Willie Park Jr., a two-time Open Champion. Park\'s influence is seen in the clever use of the natural slopes of the Dunion hill, ensuring that very few lies are ever truly flat. The course is famously divided by the Jed Water, which provides a serene soundtrack to a round that is often quite taxing on the legs.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a pillar of the Borders golfing community, producing numerous regional champions. It is known for its \"Lothian\" greensslick, undulating surfaces that require a soft touch. While it may not host the massive professional events of the coast, it is a regular venue for the Borders Golfers\' Association championships. The clubhouse, overlooking the historic abbey town, offers a warm, traditional welcome. For those who enjoy the \"mountain goat\" style of golf where elevation change is the primary hazard, Jedburgh is a classic example of late-Victorian inland design.', ''),
('keith', 'Keith', 'http://www.keithgolfclub.co.uk/', 'https://keith.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'No', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'No', 57.542279, -2.971117, 0, 0, 'no opens', '', 'keith', 840, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000091b75cfdd8c407c05f27f56569c54c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Keith Golf Club in Banffshire has a history of resilience. The original 1901 course was lost to the \"Dig for Victory\" campaign during World War II, but the club was resurrected in the 1960s thanks to a generous land donation from Colonel G.B. Kynoch. The current 18-hole layout was designed by Roy Phimister, the professional at Nairn, who created a parkland course that feels significantly more mature than its years. It is characterized by the Drum Burn, which snakes through the property and creates several \"do or die\" approach shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point for the local distilling community, with many members hailing from the world-famous Strathisla and Glenkeith distilleries. The layout is relatively short but notoriously tight, with gorse and broom punishing any lack of discipline off the tee. One of its most famous features is the 6th hole, which requires a blind shot over a corner of \"Out of Bounds\" territory to reach a green perched on a steep bank. It is an honest, welcoming Highland club that rewards accuracy and strategic play over raw distance, making it a favorite for local society outings.', ''),
('kelso', 'Kelso', 'https://kelso.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://kelso.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.612753, -2.431062, 0, 0, '', '', 'kelso', 1322, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000066344a2d07203c050c3b7b06ece4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kelso Golf Club offers one of the most unique settings in Scotland, as much of the course is situated within the perimeter of the Kelso Racecourse. Established in 1893, the course was significantly refined by James Braid, who managed to weave a challenging 18-hole parkland layout around the jumps and the grandstands. This proximity to the \"sport of kings\" gives the course a grand, expansive feel, with the flat racecourse land providing a fast-playing surface that stays remarkably dry even in the winter.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious reputation in the Borders and has hosted the Scottish Seniors\' Championship. Because the course is largely flat, it is an easy walk, but Braid\'s signature \"crater\" bunkers and the occasional racecourse rail provide plenty of strategic obstacles. Famous visitors over the years have included many of the UK\'s leading jockeys and trainers, who often squeeze in a round between races. It is a course of two halves: the holes inside the track are wide and inviting, while those outside the rails are tighter and more technical. Kelso is a masterclass in sharing space, offering a refined and historic golfing experience.', ''),
('kemnay', 'Kemnay', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kemnay#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kemnay#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.138475, -2.159094, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kemnay', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000029eb3713d34501c024287e8cb9914c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kemnay Golf Club is a lush, expansive parkland course in Aberdeenshire that has evolved significantly since its founding in 1908. While it began as a modest 9-hole track, it was transformed into a premier 18-hole venue in the 1990s under the guidance of architect Graeme Webster. Webster\'s design philosophy\"playability for all\"is evident here, with generous fairways that allow for a fun round while still incorporating enough bunkers and water to challenge the low handicapper.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its \"Amen Corner\" stretch near the end of the round, where the 16th, 17th, and 18th holes can ruin a good scorecard. The 18th in particular, a par-four with a daunting approach over a pond to a green in front of the clubhouse, was a later addition by Webster that provided the course with a truly dramatic finish. Kemnay is a frequent host of the Aberdeenshire County Championships and is widely regarded as having some of the most consistent greens in the North East. It is a friendly, modern club that manages to feel like a private estate, offering a high-quality, polished parkland experience.', ''),
('kilbirnieplace', 'Kilbirnie Place', 'https://www.kilbirnieplacegc.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.753457, -4.694477, 0, 2351, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f94b8bfa24c712c09cf86a4771e04b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilbirnie Place Golf Club, situated in the hills of North Ayrshire, is a course built on industrial pride. Founded in 1923, the course was established largely by and for the workers of the local steelworks. Originally a 9-hole course on the site of an old estate, it was extended to 18 holes by the members themselves, who hand-cleared the land to ensure the club\'s survival. This \"DIY\" history has resulted in a course with a rugged, honest character that follows the natural, rolling contours of the Garnock Valley.\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its spectacular views toward the Firth of Clyde and the mountains of Arran. While it lacks a \"famous name\" architect, the layout is highly respected for its natural defense; the \"Place\" burn comes into play on several holes, requiring precise iron play. The club maintains a fiercely loyal membership and a reputation for being one of the most welcoming in the West of Scotland. It is the perfect example of a \"working man\'s\" course that has matured into a scenic and testing parkland gem, proving that great golf is often born from the passion of its players.', ''),
('killermont', 'Killermont', 'https://www.glasgowgolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.908421, -4.301579, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003ca41820d13411c0f3ffaa2347f44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Killermont is the historic home of the Glasgow Golf Club, the 9th oldest in the world. The course was laid out in 1903 by the legendary Old Tom Morris and was famously his final full course design before his passing. Set within the grounds of a magnificent B-listed Georgian mansion that serves as the clubhouse, Killermont is a sanctuary of traditionalism. It is a pure parkland experience, characterized by massive, ancient trees and the winding River Kelvin, which guards several of the greens.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted the Scottish PGA Championship and the Scottish Amateur, and its membership roll is a \"who\'s who\" of Glasgow\'s professional history. Unlike the club\'s other course at Gailes, which is a links, Killermont is a tactical, refined test that emphasizes placement over power. One of its most daunting features is the 2nd hole, a par-three of over 240 yards that remains one of the toughest one-shotters in the country. To play Killermont is to walk in the footsteps of the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" on a canvas that has remained largely untouched for over a century.', ''),
('killin', 'Killin', 'https://www.killingolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 56.478979, -4.320978, 0, 2353, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000024f1f274ae4811c0433c122f4f3d4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Killin Golf Club is widely considered one of the most scenic 9-hole courses in the British Isles. Established in 1911 and situated at the heart of the Breadalbane region, the course was laid out with advice from John Duncan, the professional at Stirling. The course is a Highland parkland masterpiece, featuring dramatic elevation changes and views of the Falls of Dochart and the surrounding peaks of Ben Lawers. It is a course that doesn\'t just ask you to play golf; it asks you to admire the landscape.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich community history, having been founded by a diverse group that included the local schoolmaster, the gamekeeper, and the minister. The signature hole is the par-three 9th, \"The Chasm\" where players must hit from an elevated tee over a deep, wooded ravine to a green perched on the hillside. While it hasn\'t hosted international professional tours, it is a favorite for visitors and was famously a haunt of the novelist Sir Walter Scott\'s descendants. It is an atmospheric, rugged, and intensely beautiful course that embodies the wild heart of Perthshire golf.', ''),
('kilmacolm', 'Kilmacolm', 'https://kilmacolm.hub.clubv1.com/visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.889688, -4.617044, 0, 0, '', '', 'kilmacolm', 1610, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a8c5e061da7712c063d2df4be1f14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilmacolm Golf Club is a stunning moorland course that feels like a Highland escape just half an hour from Glasgow. Established in 1891, the layout was refined by the prolific James Braid, who capitalized on the rugged, undulating terrain of the Knapps. The course is a riot of color in the summer, with purple heather and yellow gorse framing the fairways. Because it sits on high ground, it offers expansive views across the Clyde Valley to the peaks of Ben Lomond and the southern Highlands.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine players, including the 1935 Scottish Amateur champion Jack McLean. The course is notoriously difficult to play to your handicap, as the springy turf and natural hollows create unpredictable lies. One of its most famous features is the \"Valley of the Shadow\" a deep natural ravine that must be negotiated on the back nine. It is a traditional, friendly club that prides itself on maintaining Braid\'s strategic vision, offering a \"pure\" golfing experience where the wind and the terrain are the primary defenders.', ''),
('kilmarnockbarassie', 'Kilmarnock Barassie', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.562570, -4.650210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ef2076a6d09912c0f9da334b02c84b40, 'links', 'No', 'Kilmarnock (Barassie) Golf Club is a heavyweight of Scottish links golf. Founded in 1887, the course underwent a significant redesign in the 1930s by James Braid, creating a layout that is often mentioned in the same breath as Troon and Prestwick. It is a classic links, characterized by deep bunkers, firm fairways, and a constant, shifting sea breeze. The club has an immense tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and hosting the Scottish Amateur on multiple occasions.\r\n\r\nFamous members have included several Walker Cup players, and the club\'s professional tradition is strong. The course is unique for having 27 holes, with the main 18-hole championship layout known for its brutal closing stretch. The railway line runs parallel to several holes, adding to the traditional Ayrshire links atmosphere. Barassie is a true ball-striker\'s course; it doesn\'t rely on gimmicks, only on the quality of its turf and the strategic placement of its hazards. For any golfer touring the Ayrshire coast, it is an essential and historically significant stop.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/jZBFUlXRoXc?si=msR5aFCztII5cN8_');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('kilmarnockbarassie9', 'Kilmarnock Barassie - Hillhouse', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'https://www.kbgc.co.uk/visitor-booking-form', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.562570, -4.650210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ef2076a6d09912c0f9da334b02c84b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Hillhouse course at Barassie consists of nine holes that, when combined with the nine holes of the \"new\" loop, create a second full 18-hole experience at this prestigious club. Despite being the \"secondary\" layout, Hillhouse is maintained to the same exacting championship standards as the main links. It offers a slightly different character, blending traditional links turf with areas that feel more like a sheltered heathland course, providing a varied and engaging round for those who have already tackled the main championship track.\r\n\r\nHillhouse is particularly popular with members for a quick, competitive game and serves as an excellent venue for junior development. It shares the same sandy, free-draining soil that makes Barassie playable throughout the year. While it may lack the international spotlight of the Open Qualifying holes, it features several tricky par-threes and tight fairways that demand precision. It is the perfect example of the \"depth of quality\" found at Scotland\'s premier golf clubs, ensuring that every golferfrom the high handicapper to the elite amateurhas a world-class surface to play on.', ''),
('kilspindie', 'Kilspindie', 'https://www.kilspindiegolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.010189, -2.879093, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kilspindiegolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000e62329e9610807c0b4e386df4d014c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Kilspindie Golf Club is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense of the word. Tucked away on the Aberlady Bay in East Lothian, this 18th-oldest club in the world offers a pure, traditional links experience that is almost entirely unchanged since the 19th century. Originally a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 in 1898 by the local professional Ben Sayers and Willie Park Jr. It is a short, par-69 course, but what it lacks in length, it makes up for in sheer charm and coastal beauty.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its intimacy; the first hole starts right beside the clubhouse wall, and the sea is in view on almost every shot. Notable members have included legends like Babe Zaharias, who reportedly loved the course for its fun and accessibility. Kilspindie is the perfect antidote to the \"modern championship\" course; it is a walking-friendly links where a creative short game is far more valuable than a 300-yard drive. With its hidden bunkers, stone walls, and proximity to the bird sanctuary, it is one of the most atmospheric and enjoyable rounds of golf in the \"Cradle of Golf.\"', ''),
('kilsythlennox', 'Kilsyth Lennox', 'https://www.kilsythlennox.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.985964, -4.047780, 0, 0, 'scottish golf app', '', '', 0, '', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008d9c853ded3010c045847f1134fe4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kilsyth Lennox Golf Club is a rugged and scenic parkland-moorland hybrid that sits at the foot of the Kilsyth Hills. Founded in 1905, the course was redesigned and extended to its current 18-hole form in the 1970s. The layout is characterized by significant elevation changes, offering spectacular views across the Kelvin Valley toward the city of Glasgow and beyond. The course is built on a series of natural terraces, meaning you will often find yourself hitting from elevated tees to greens tucked into the folds of the hills.\r\n\r\nWhile it hasn\'t hosted the major professional tours, Kilsyth Lennox has a reputation for producing tough, resilient golfers who excel in the Stirlingshire county circuits. The course is known for its \"Burn holes\" where the local water system creates natural hazards that require careful management. It is a traditional, community-focused club that offers a warm welcome to visitors. The 13th hole, \"The Spectacles\" is a highlight, requiring a blind shot over twin mounds to reach the green. It is a course that rewards local knowledge and a steady nerve, offering a high-value, authentic Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('kingarrockhickory', 'Kingarrock Hickory', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingarrockhickory#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingarrockhickory#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.294680, -3.002980, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingarrockhickory', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002e56d4601a0608c084640113b8254c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingarrock Hickory Golf is a unique time-capsule and the only course of its kind in Europe. Located at Hill of Tarvit Mansion in Fife, this 9-hole course is played exclusively with original wooden-shafted hickory clubs and authentic low-compression balls from the 1920s. The course was originally the private plaything of the Sharp family, who owned the estate, but it was lost to farming during the war and only painstakingly restored in 2008 using the original 1924 plans.\r\n\r\nThere are no modern amenities hereno yardage markers, no graphite shafts, and no oversized heads. Golfers are provided with a heritage bag containing five clubs: a brassie, a mashie, a niblick, a mid-iron, and a putter. Playing Kingarrock is a masterclass in the \"art\" of the game over the \"science.\" Notable visitors have included golf historians from around the world seeking to experience the game as Bobby Jones or Walter Hagen would have played it. It is a peaceful, nostalgic experience that reminds every golfer that the heart of the game is about feel, creativity, and a touch of luck.', ''),
('kinghorn', 'Kinghorn', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinghorn#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinghorn#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.067432, -3.179766, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kinghorn', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003e761728297009c0185a9d9ca1084c40, 'links', 'No', 'Kinghorn Golf Club is a delightful seaside links that offers one of the most enjoyable \"walks with a view\" in Fife. Founded in 1887, the course was originally designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris. It is a short but tricky layout that clings to the cliffs and hillsides overlooking the Firth of Forth. Because of its elevation, the wind is a constant and formidable opponent, often turning a modest par-four into a grueling struggle for par.\r\n\r\nThe course is municipal in nature, meaning it remains a vital part of the local community. While it lacks the length of championship tracks, it features some of the most memorable holes in the region, including several that require shots across deep coastal ravines. The view toward Edinburgh and the Bass Rock is a constant companion throughout the round. Kinghorn is proof that Old Tom Morris could create a challenging and engaging layout on any piece of land, regardless of size. It is a friendly, accessible course that provides a high-octane links experience without the high-octane green fee.', ''),
('kingjamesvi', 'King James VI', 'https://www.kingjamesvi.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.388760, -3.422660, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kingjamesvi.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006f9eea909b610bc019ff3ee3c2314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'King James VI Golf Club holds the distinction of being the only golf course in the world situated on a river island. Located on Moncreiffe Island in the middle of the River Tay in Perth, the club was founded in 1858 and the course was designed by Old Tom Morris in 1897. Access to the course is via a narrow walkway attached to a railway bridge, which immediately sets the tone for a unique golfing adventure. The island setting means the course is perfectly flat, but it is surrounded by the rushing waters of the Tay and lined with mature trees.\r\n\r\nThe club is steeped in history and was named after the Scottish monarch who was a known enthusiast of the game. Because it is an island, the course has a unique microclimate and is famously lush and green throughout the summer. It has hosted many regional championships and is a favorite for those seeking a tranquil, \"secret\" golfing experience right in the heart of the city. While the river rarely comes directly into play, the psychological pressure of playing on an islandand the occasional sound of the trains overheadadds a fascinating layer of character to this historic Old Tom Morris gem.', ''),
('kings', 'Kings', 'https://kings.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://kings.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.463218, -4.262284, 0, 0, '', '', 'kings', 272, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000670e492d940c11c0927538ba4abb4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kings Golf Club in Inverness (formerly Torvean) is a relatively new addition to the Highland golf scene but one that has made a massive impact. Opened in 2019 to replace the old municipal course, the layout was designed by Stuart Rennie. It is a modern, championship-standard parkland course that was built to rival the quality of the famous links nearby. Rennie utilized the rolling terrain to create a \"stadium\" feel, with large, undulating greens and expansive white sand bunkers that give it a very high-end, professional look.\r\n\r\nDespite its young age, Kings has already hosted several prestigious amateur events and is a regular venue for the PGA Highlands Open. The course offers spectacular views over the city of Inverness and the Caledonian Canal. The signature hole is the par-three 14th, which plays across a valley to a well-guarded green. The modern clubhouse is a hub of activity and reflects the club\'s ambition to be a premier golfing destination. It is the perfect example of how modern design can create a challenging, visually stunning course that complements the traditional Highland landscape.', ''),
('kingsacre', 'Kings Acre', 'https://kingsacre.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.892600, -3.104520, 0, 0, '', 'https://kingsacre.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002e39ee940ed608c06e3480b740f24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located on the southern outskirts of Edinburgh, Kings Acre is a modern parkland course and academy that has become a center for golf development in the Lothians. Opened in the late 1990s, the course was designed by Graeme Webster and features a layout that is both challenging for the low-handicapper and accessible for the casual player. The design is characterized by large, USGA-spec greens and several significant water hazards that require strategic navigation.\r\n\r\nKings Acre is perhaps best known for its world-class academy and practice facilities, which have attracted many of Scotland\'s leading professionals for practice sessions. The course itself is beautifully manicured and offers views toward the Pentland Hills. It has a \"commercial\" feel in the best senseprofessional, well-organized, and focused on providing a high-quality experience. The par-five 18th is a fantastic finishing hole, requiring a brave approach over water to reach the green in two. It is a popular choice for corporate days and for golfers in the capital who want a polished, modern round of golf without the formality of an ancient private club.', ''),
('kingsbarns', 'Kingsbarns', 'https://www.kingsbarns.com/reservations', 'https://www.kingsbarns.com/reservations', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'fife', '', 56.298953, -2.643927, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000005517f032c32605c04205871744264c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Kingsbarns Golf Links is a modern masterpiece that feels as though it has been part of the Fife coastline for centuries. While golf was played here in the 1700s, the current course was designed by Kyle Phillips and opened in 2000. It is a man-made links of extraordinary scale, featuring wide, undulating fairways and tiered greens that offer spectacular views of the North Sea from every single hole. It is most famous as a co-host of the Alfred Dunhill Links Championship on the DP World Tour, where it consistently ranks as a favorite among the world\'s top professionals.\r\n\r\nThe course has hosted many of the game\'s greats, including Rory McIlroy. Its signature hole, the par-three 15th, requires a nerve-wracking carry over the surging Atlantic waves to a green perched on a rocky outcrop. Unlike the traditional \"out and back\" links, Kingsbarns is designed in two loops that maximize the dramatic elevation changes of the site. It is a high-end, world-class experience that combines the rugged beauty of traditional links golf with the polished service of a premier resort.', ''),
('kingsfield', 'Kingsfield', 'https://kingsfield.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.982968, -3.553245, 0, 2365, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007767edb60b6d0cc0dc813ae5d1fd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingsfield Golf & Leisure, located near Linlithgow, is a vibrant and modern facility designed to foster a love for the game. The 9-hole course was designed by Graeme Webster and serves as a high-quality \"short course\" that challenges experienced players while remaining accessible to beginners. The greens are built to USGA specifications, ensuring that the putting surfaces are among the truest in West Lothian. It is a parkland layout that emphasizes the \"fun\" aspect of golf, featuring wide fairways and clever bunkering.\r\n\r\nThe facility is particularly famous for its \"Ochil Course\" putting green, a massive, undulating 18-hole putting surface inspired by the Himalayas at St Andrews. Kingsfield is also home to a top-tier academy where several Scottish professionals, including Stephen Gallacher, have been known to practice. It is a community-focused hub that includes a TaylorMade performance center and high-tech driving range. For those looking for a relaxed yet high-quality golfing experience that fits into a busy schedule, Kingsfield is a pioneer of the modern Scottish golf model.', ''),
('kingsknowe', 'Kingsknowe', 'https://www.kingsknowe.com/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.914031, -3.262603, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.kingsknowe.com', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e3a6069acf190ac0dd43c2f7fef44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kingsknowe Golf Club is a classic Edinburgh parkland course with a history dating back to 1908. The layout was originally designed by the legendary Alec Herd, the 1902 Open Champion, and later refined by the \"busiest man in golf\" James Braid. The course is characterized by its hilly terrain and mature woodland, providing a peaceful escape from the nearby city center. Its most distinctive feature is the railway line that runs parallel to several holes, adding a touch of Victorian industrial charm to the lush surroundings.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history of competitive amateur golf and has hosted numerous Lothians County events. Notable members have included prominent figures in Edinburgh\'s legal and medical professions, reflecting the club\'s traditional status. The greens at Kingsknowe are notoriously tricky, often sloping significantly and requiring a precise read. The signature 12th hole offers a stunning view across the city toward the Pentland Hills. It is a friendly, well-established club that rewards accuracy and stamina, offering a quintessential \"city parkland\" round with a historic pedigree.', ''),
('kingslinks', 'Kings Links', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingslinks#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingslinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.166720, -2.082972, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingslinks', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a4de5339eda900c068cbb91457954c40, 'links', 'No', 'Kings Links is a historic coastal course that provides the city of Aberdeen with a pure links experience right on its doorstep. As one of the oldest sites of golf in the worldwith records of the game being played here as far back as 1625it is a place of immense heritage. The current 18-hole layout is a traditional \"out and back\" links, running parallel to the North Sea beach. It is a flat, walking-friendly course characterized by firm turf, hidden pot bunkers, and the ever-present, biting coastal wind.\r\n\r\nThe course is municipal in nature, meaning it has served generations of Aberdonians as a training ground for the more famous links nearby. While it may not host the professional tours, its defense lies in its exposure to the elements; on a calm day, it is a delight, but in a gale, it is a formidable test of low-ball flight. It is famously free-draining, making it a popular choice for year-round golf. For visitors, Kings Links offers an authentic, \"no-frills\" connection to the origins of the game, played on land that has seen over 400 years of golfing history.', ''),
('kingussie', 'Kingussie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingussie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kingussie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.091834, -4.053811, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kingussie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000004a9143b1a3710c097546d37c18b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Founded in 1891, Kingussie Golf Club is a spectacular Highland moorland course that sits high above the Spey Valley. The layout was refined by both Old Tom Morris and Harry Vardon, two of the most iconic figures in the history of the sport. Their influence is evident in the way the course works harmoniously with the natural peat hags, heather, and birch woodland. It is a physically demanding course, but the reward is a series of panoramic views of the Cairngorm Mountains that are among the best in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, traditional Highland hospitality and its small, tricky greens. Kingussie has long been a favorite for visiting societies who appreciate the \"raw\" nature of the terrain. The Gynack Burn meanders through the course, providing a natural hazard on several holes. It is a course that requires creativity rather than brute force, as the undulating fairways and mountain breezes demand a variety of shot shapes. To play Kingussie is to experience the \"Golden Age\" of golf architecture in one of the most breathtaking natural settings in the country.', ''),
('kinross', 'Kinross - Montgomery', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'No', 56.210740, -3.414141, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'kinross', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003e76172829500bc0c2fa3f87f91a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Montgomery Course at the Green Hotel in Kinross is a premier parkland test that offers a \"championship\" feel. Designed by Colton & Co. and opened in the early 20th century, it was significantly updated by Donald Steel to meet modern standards. The course is named after the local estate and is characterized by its large, undulating greens and significant water hazards. It has a reputations for being the more challenging of the two courses at the resort, often used for regional qualifying and high-level amateur tournaments.\r\n\r\nThe layout is lush and well-wooded, providing a sheltered environment that contrasts with the windswept links of the coast. Famous visitors over the decades have included many of Scotland\'s leading political and business figures who frequent the hotel. The signature par-three 16th, played over a pond to a well-guarded green, is a notorious \"card-wrecker.\" The Montgomery offers a polished, professional golfing experience with manicured fairways and fast, true greens, making it a staple for those touring the heart of Scotland.\r\n', ''),
('kinrossbruce', 'Kinross - Bruce', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kinross#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.209096, -3.421079, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kinross', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005342b0aa5e5e0bc0badc60a8c31a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Bruce Course, the Montgomery\'s sibling at the Green Hotel, is often perceived as the more relaxed and \"fun\" of the two Kinross layouts, but it is certainly no pushover. Named after the legendary Scottish King, the course features a unique par-73 layout that includes four par-fives on the back nine. This makes it a favorite for long hitters and those looking to improve their birdie count. The design is more open than the Montgomery, allowing for a bit more freedom off the tee while still requiring a sharp short game.\r\n\r\nThe Bruce is particularly popular for society outings and corporate days due to its playability and scenic views over Loch Leven. Despite its more \"user-friendly\" reputation, it features several tricky dog-legs and well-placed bunkers that require strategic thinking. The course shares the same high maintenance standards as its sister, ensuring a quality playing surface year-round. It is a delightful, walking-friendly parkland course that provides a perfect complement to the tougher Montgomery, making the Kinross resort a comprehensive destination for any golfing group.', ''),
('kintore', 'Kintore', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kintore#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kintore#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.243763, -2.319758, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kintore', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000030134548dd8e02c0c87c40a0339f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kintore Golf Club, located in Aberdeenshire, is a fascinating hybrid course that has evolved from a 9-hole layout founded in 1911 into a premier 18-hole parkland venue. The \"original\" nine holes are characterized by their hilly, moorland nature, while the newer nine, added in the 1990s and designed by Graeme Webster, offer a more modern, flatter parkland experience. This contrast makes for a varied and engaging round, as the player must adapt their strategy as they move between the two distinct sections of the course.\r\n\r\nThe club is a hub of the local community and is known for its friendly, inclusive atmosphere. The views from the higher holes stretch across the Don Valley toward the peak of Bennachie, providing a classic Highland backdrop. Kintore has hosted various North East District championships and is highly regarded for the quality of its greens. The signature 13th hole, \"The Tuach\" is a challenging par-four that requires a precise drive to a narrowing fairway. It is a course that perfectly blends the old and the new, offering a high-value and scenic round of golf in the heart of the \"Garioch.\"', ''),
('kirkcaldy', 'Kirkcaldy', 'https://kirkcaldygolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://kirkcaldygolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.099280, -3.193263, 0, 2372, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000fc36c478cd8b09c0cd920035b50c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirkcaldy Golf Club, known locally as \"Balwearie\" is a magnificent parkland course that was famously designed by Tom Morris Jr. (Young Tom Morris) in 1904. To play a course designed by the four-time Open Champion is a rare privilege, and the layout still retains much of its original character. The course is set in a secluded valley and is characterized by its lush, mature woodland and the Raith Burn, which meanders through the property and comes into play on several of the most challenging holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine amateur players who have represented Fife and Scotland. It is a regular host of the Fife County Championships. The layout is known for its fast, sloping greens and its \"stadium\" finish in front of the clubhouse. While it is located near the town center, the dense tree-lining provides a sense of total isolation. Kirkcaldy is a \"pure\" golf club that prides itself on its traditions and its challenging, high-quality playing surface. It is a must-play for anyone interested in the history of the Morris family and the development of parkland golf in Fife.', ''),
('Kirkcudbright', 'Kirkcudbright', 'https://www.kirkcudbrightgolf.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 54.841017, -4.041712, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002c67ef8cb62a10c0a530ef71a66b4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1893, Kirkcudbright Golf Club (pronounced \"Kir-coo-bree\") is a beautiful parkland course that offers spectacular views over the Dee Estuary and the historic \"Artists\' Town.\" The course was originally a 9-hole layout but was extended to 18 holes in the early 20th century with input from the legendary James Braid. Braid\'s influence is evident in the strategic use of the naturally undulating terrain and the well-protected greens. The course is famously lush, featuring a wide variety of mature trees and vibrant gorse.\r\n\r\nThe club has long been a favorite of the artistic community that made the town famous, and the clubhouse features several works by local artists. Notable tournaments held here include the South of Scotland Championship. The layout is relatively compact, requiring accuracy and a delicate touch around the greens rather than brute force. The 13th hole, \"The Pulpit\" offers a panoramic view that is often cited as the best in Dumfries and Galloway. It is a friendly, scenic, and historic club that provides a tranquil and refined golfing experience in one of the most beautiful corners of the country.', ''),
('kirkhill', 'Kirkhill', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirkhill#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirkhill#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.800443, -4.167457, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kirkhill', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f1f109d979ab10c0f4a78dea74e64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirkhill Golf Club, located on the southern fringes of Glasgow, is a prestigious parkland course that celebrated its centenary in 2010. The layout was designed by the legendary James Braid, who masterfully utilized the rolling terrain to create a course that tests every facet of a player\'s game. It is characterized by its lush, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally fast, undulating greens. Because of its elevated position, the course offers panoramic views across the Clyde Valley toward the Campsie Fells.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history of competitive success, with its members frequently featuring in the final stages of the Lanarkshire County Championships. Notable members have included several professional footballers and prominent local businessmen, contributing to a vibrant and social atmosphere. The signature 13th hole, a par-three known as \"The Dell\" requires a precise shot to a green nestled in a natural hollow. Kirkhill remains a \"pure\" golf club that prioritizes the quality of its playing surface, offering a challenging and traditional Braid experience just a stone\'s throw from the city.', ''),
('kirkintilloch', 'Kirkintilloch', 'https://kirkintilloch.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.948759, -4.170037, 0, 0, '', 'https://kirkintilloch.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009770e82d1eae10c0916456ef70f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1895, Kirkintilloch Golf Club is a beautiful parkland gem situated at the foot of the Campsie Fells. The course reached its modern 18-hole form in the 1920s under the guidance of James Braid. Braid\'s signature strategic bunkering is evident throughout, forcing golfers to think their way around the course rather than simply relying on distance. The layout is divided by the Antonine Wall, providing a unique historical backdrop to several holes.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its \"Amen Corner\" stretch near the end of the round, where water hazards and tight fairways can quickly derail a good score. It has hosted various Dunbartonshire County events and is a regular venue for the PGA Scotland regional circuit. The clubhouse is known for its warm hospitality and overlooks a fantastic finishing hole that requires an approach over a burn. It is a traditional, friendly club that offers a varied and engaging test of golf, perfectly blending the tranquility of the countryside with a historic architectural pedigree.', ''),
('kirriemuir', 'Kirriemuir', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirriemuir#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/kirriemuir#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.689962, -2.998286, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'kirriemuir', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ef6fd05e7dfc07c0cbbdc0ac50584c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Kirriemuir Golf Club, located in the \"Gateway to the Glens\" is a scenic parkland course with a design history involving the great James Braid. Established in 1908, the course sits on the edge of the Angus glens, offering views of the Grampian Mountains that are nothing short of spectacular. The layout is characterized by its wide fairways and a diverse range of mature trees, including silver birch and pine. It is the birthplace of Sir J.M. Barrie, the creator of Peter Pan, and the club embraces this heritage with several holes named in honor of the \"Boy Who Never Grew Up.\"\r\n\r\nThe course is known for its immaculate conditioning and its remarkably true greens. While it is not an overly long course, the subtle undulations and the local breezes provide a constant challenge. Notable tournaments held here include the Scottish Seniors\' Championship. It is a welcoming, community-focused club where the focus is on the sheer enjoyment of the game in a beautiful Highland setting. For those looking for a tranquil and historic round of golf in the heart of Angus, Kirriemuir offers a refined and charming experience.', ''),
('knightswood', 'Knightswood', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/knightswood#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 55.894479, -4.351611, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'knightswood', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000caa7c7b60c6811c0b9fab1497ef24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Knightswood Golf Course is one of Glasgow\'s most popular municipal 9-hole layouts, providing an essential gateway to the game for the city\'s residents. Originally part of a larger estate, the course was opened to the public in the mid-20th century to meet the rising demand for accessible sport. It is a flat, easy-to-walk parkland course that features surprisingly large greens and well-placed bunkering. Despite its urban location, the course is remarkably peaceful, acting as a green lung for the West End of Glasgow.\r\n\r\nThe course is a vital \"nursery\" for the local golfing community, where many of Glasgow\'s club golfers first learned their swing. While it does not host professional tours, it is a hub for the Glasgow Municipal Golf Clubs\' Association and hosts regular amateur competitions. The layout is designed to be forgiving for beginners while still providing enough of a challenge to keep experienced players coming back for a quick afternoon round. It is a shining example of public-sector golf, proving that high-quality, fun, and affordable golf can thrive in the heart of a major city.', ''),
('krtb', 'Turnberry - King Robert the Bruce', 'https://www.turnberry.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'turnberry', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.315405, -4.833056, 24433, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000041f2cea10c5513c058ffe7305fa84b40, 'links', 'No', 'The King Robert the Bruce course at the world-famous Turnberry resort is a spectacular links that underwent a total transformation in 2017. Designed by Martin Ebert (who also handled the Ailsa redesign), it was named in honor of the Scottish King who was born in the adjacent Turnberry Castle in 1274. The course utilizes the dramatic, rugged coastline of Ayrshire, offering views of the Ailsa Craig and the lighthouse that rival those of its world-ranking sibling.\r\n\r\nWhile it shares the same hallowed turf as the Ailsa, the King Robert the Bruce course has its own distinct personality, with several holes playing across high ridges and deep coastal ravines. It has hosted the AIG Women\'s Open and remains a favorite for high-end corporate events. Famous visitors include every major name in modern golf, from Tiger Woods to Jack Nicklaus. It is an uncompromising and visually stunning test of links golf, featuring \"infinity\" greens and deep, revetted bunkers that demand total commitment from the tee to the cup.', ''),
('KylesofBute', 'Kyles of Bute', 'https://www.kylesofbutegolfclub.co.uk/visitors', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.887552, -5.250987, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000076e272bc020115c0ecbfce4d9bf14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Kyles of Bute Golf Club, situated near Tighnabruaich, is a 9-hole moorland course that offers what many consider to be the most breathtaking views in the British Isles. Established in 1906, the course is perched on the hills overlooking the \"Kyles\"the narrow straits of water separating the Isle of Bute from the Cowal Peninsula. The layout is rugged and natural, with the fairways carved out of the heather and gorse.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility, reflecting the relaxed and welcoming nature of the local community. While it lacks a celebrity architect, the routing is genius, forcing golfers to navigate steep hills and rocky outcrops. The most famous feature is the 4th hole, where the view of the Loch Ruel is so distracting it\'s a wonder anyone hits the fairway. It is a place of total tranquility, where the only sound is the wind and the cry of the gulls. For the golfing adventurer, a round at Kyles of Bute is a mandatory pilgrimage to see the raw, wild beauty of Argyll from the fairways.', ''),
('ladybank', 'Ladybank', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/ladybank#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.282370, -3.124200, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1058, 'ladybank', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000003c4ed1915cfe08c08eaf3db324244c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ladybank Golf Club in Fife is one of the most prestigious and historic heathland courses in the world. Originally a 6-hole course designed by Old Tom Morris in 1879, it was eventually expanded to 18 holes, with the layout we see today largely being the work of J.R. Stutt. Ladybank is a premier Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and has hosted some of the greatest names in the game during their quest to reach the world\'s oldest major.\r\n\r\nThe course is a sanctuary of Scots pine, heather, and silver birch. Famous members include Dale Reid, the legendary Solheim Cup captain, and the club has a reputation for producing elite amateur talent. Unlike the nearby links, Ladybank offers a sheltered, tactical test where a driver is often best left in the bag in favor of a well-placed iron shot. The greens are famously fast and true, requiring a delicate touch. It is a refined, aristocratic club that offers a pure and uncompromising test of golf, representing the very pinnacle of Scottish inland course design.', ''),
('lamlash', 'Lamlash', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lamlash#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lamlash#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.545452, -5.129485, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lamlash', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004d4a41b7978414c0d6c4025fd1c54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Situated on the beautiful Isle of Arran, Lamlash Golf Club is an 18-hole course that offers a dramatic \"Highland in miniature\" experience. Founded in 1889, the course was redesigned by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, who utilized the steep, undulating terrain to create a layout that provides constant challenges and rewards. The views across Lamlash Bay to the Holy Isle are cinematic, particularly from the higher holes on the back nine.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the island\'s community and has a history of hosting the Arran Open Championship. Notable visitors have included world leaders and celebrities seeking the privacy of the island. The course is known for its short but tricky par-threes and its lush, springy turf. The signature hole, the par-three 4th, requires a shot over a valley to a green perched on a plateau. It is a friendly, traditional club where the hospitality is as memorable as the views. For anyone visiting Arran, Lamlash provides a rugged and authentic Scottish golfing experience that tests your skill and your fitness.', ''),
('lanark', 'Lanark', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lanark#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lanark#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.672256, -3.745194, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lanark', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000004567994528f60dc017450f7c0cd64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lanark Golf Club is the 25th oldest golf club in the world and a true heavyweight of the Scottish moorland game. Founded in 1851, the course was originally laid out by Old Tom Morris and later refined by James Braid. It sits on high ground overlooking the Clyde Valley and is characterized by its firm, sandy, and fast-draining soil-giving it the playing characteristics of a links course despite being miles from the sea. It is a perennial Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship.\r\n\r\nThe course is a masterclass in strategic design, with deep bunkers and thick heather punishing any wayward shots. Famous members have included titans of the Scottish textile industry and champion amateurs like Charlie Green. Lanark is known for its impeccable conditioning and its sense of history; the clubhouse is a treasure trove of early golfing artifacts. The layout is a stern but fair test that requires every club in the bag and a creative approach to shot-making. It is one of the most respected courses in the country, offering a world-class experience in a peaceful and historic setting.', ''),
('Langholm', 'Langholm', 'https://www.langholmgolfclub.co.uk/visitors/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.152513, -2.994835, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004c546f0d6cf507c0809bc58b85934b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Langholm Golf Club is a charming and historic 9-hole course situated in the \"Muckle Toon\" of the Scottish Borders. Established in 1892, the course is built on the steep slopes of the Castle Hill, offering views that stretch across the Esk Valley toward the Solway Firth. The layout was refined by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, who used the natural elevation changes to create a course that plays much longer than its yardage.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its connection to the Langholm Common Riding, one of the oldest and grandest border festivals, with several holes crossing the ancient boundaries of the town. It is a \"mountain goat\" course that requires a good level of fitness, but the exhilaration of the elevated tees is unparalleled. Notable members have included local sporting legends and prominent members of the Borders wool industry. It is a traditional, unpretentious club that prides itself on its warm welcome and its beautifully maintained greens. For those who enjoy the rugged, hilly nature of Borders golf, Langholm is a hidden gem that offers an authentic taste of local history.', ''),
('Langlands', 'Langlands', 'https://www.langlandsgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.731091, -4.170693, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e09f5225caae10c031b3cf6394dd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Langlands Golf Course is a polished 18-hole parkland facility situated on the southern edge of East Kilbride. Operated by South Lanarkshire Leisure, it serves as a premier municipal test that feels significantly more \"private\" than its status suggests. The course is characterized by its wide, lush fairways and large, receptive greens, making it a favorite for those who enjoy opening their shoulders with the driver. However, the layout is cleverly punctuated by mature woodland and subtle dog-legs that require thoughtful positioning.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant community spirit and is known for its \"Noonies Sweep\" a legendary local gathering that fosters a competitive but friendly atmosphere. While it may not host the international professional tours, it is a stalwart of the Lanarkshire county circuit and is frequently praised for its year-round conditioning. The signature par-three 16th, \"The Quarry\" requires a precise shot over a natural depression and provides a dramatic challenge late in the round. It is a welcoming, high-value course that offers a professional-standard parkland experience for golfers of all levels.', ''),
('largs', 'Largs', 'https://largs.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://largs.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.774287, -4.852142, 0, 0, '', '', 'largs', 1284, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002f3196e9976813c0e65b1fd61be34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Largs Golf Club is one of the most picturesque parkland courses in the West of Scotland, offering breathtaking views across the Firth of Clyde to the mountains of Cumbrae and Arran. Founded in 1891, the club moved to its present site within the Kelburn Estate shortly after, playing alongside the 13th-century Kelburn Castle. The course was originally a 9-hole layout designed by Willie Campbell, but it was expanded to a full 18 holes in 1953 with input from local figures, including the legendary coach Bob Torrance.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious tournament history, recently serving as the host for the 2026 Scottish Men\'s Area Team Championship. The layout is notoriously tight in places, with mature trees framing the fairways and the Kelburn Burn providing a natural hazard on several holes. Notable holes include the par-four 6th, which dog-legs toward the castle, and the daunting par-four 15th, \"Cockleshells.\" Largs is a refined, aristocratic club that manages to feel both historic and modern, providing an impeccable playing surface and some of the finest scenery in Ayrshire.', ''),
('Larkhall', 'Larkhall', 'https://www.slleisureandculture.co.uk/info/243/larkhall_golf_course', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.736228, -3.951482, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000083dc4598a29c0fc0223317b83cde4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Larkhall Golf Club, located adjacent to the M74 motorway, is a resilient 9-hole parkland course that is widely regarded as having some of the best greens in Lanarkshire. Established in 1909, the course is a municipal facility that has long been the sporting heart of the town. While it is a shorter par-35 layout, it offers a varied mix of holes that test both length and accuracy. The course is known for its excellent drainage, often remaining open and playable in the depths of winter when other local tracks are closed.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its inclusive and friendly atmosphere, where \"Arlene and the staff\" are local legends for their hospitality in the clubhouse. It serves as a vital nursery for the game, with its ACE children\'s activities introducing generations of local kids to the sport. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the layout is a masterclass in community-led golf, featuring narrow fairways and well-protected greens that demand respect. For those looking for an honest, unpretentious, and highly playable round of golf, Larkhall provides a high-quality experience that punches well above its weight.', ''),
('Lauder', 'Lauder', 'https://lauder.golf-club.website/website/index.php', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'borders', '', 55.710961, -2.749932, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007dca3159dcff05c0a0dd21c500db4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lauder Golf Club is a historic 9-hole gem nestled in the heart of the Scottish Borders. Established in 1896, the initial layout was overseen by the two-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr., whose strategic fingerprints are still visible on the course today. Park\'s design philosophy of \"using the land\" is evident in the clever routing over the undulating parkland, where natural slopes and hollows dictate the play. The course features 17 separate tees to provide a distinct and varied challenge for those playing a full 18-hole loop.\r\n\r\nA remarkable piece of history at Lauder is the course record of 70, set by Willie Park Jr. himself in 1905, which remarkably remained unbeaten for over a century. The course features iconic holes like \"The Wood\" and \"The Quarry\" which offer a stern test for the low handicapper while remaining enjoyable for the casual player. It is a \"walking-friendly\" club with a reputation for being one of the most equitable challenges in the region. For the golfing historian, a trip to Lauder is a chance to play on a canvas designed by one of the game\'s first true masters in a tranquil Borders setting.', ''),
('Leadhills', 'Leadhills', 'https://www.leadhillsgolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.414034, -3.756604, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a92ee065860d0ec04eb7ec10ffb44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Leadhills Golf Club is a unique and rugged 9-hole course that holds the distinction of being the highest golf course in Scotland, sitting at an elevation of over 1,500 feet. Founded in 1889, the course is situated in the heart of the Lowther Hills, where the thin mountain air makes your ball travel noticeably further. Originally established by the local \"natives\" of Leadhills and Wanlockhead, the club has a history rooted in the local lead-mining industry and the resilient spirit of the high-country communities.\r\n\r\nThe course is a raw, moorland experience where the fairways are shared with local sheep and the weather can change in an instant. It is a \"community asset\" in the truest sense, with free memberships offered to local students and a dedicated band of volunteers maintaining the greens. Notable historical figures like the Rev. Mr. Symington were among the early medal winners. Playing Leadhills is not just about the golf; it\'s about the sheer exhilaration of the landscape. For any golfer looking to tick off a \"bucket list\" experience, playing at the roof of Scotland is an absolute must.', ''),
('leitfie', 'Leitfie', 'https://www.strathmoregolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.601703, -3.219379, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f86ef3c649c109c0da73999a044d4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Leitfie Links is the charming 9-hole sister course at the Strathmore Golf Centre near Alyth. While its larger sibling, Rannaleroch, draws the championship crowds, Leitfie is a high-quality \"short course\" designed to hone the iron play and short game of all golfers. Measuring just over 1,100 yards with a par of 27, it consists of nine par-threes that range from 92 to 157 yards. Far from being a \"pitch and putt\" Leitfie is built to the same exacting standards as a championship course, with manicured greens and strategic bunkering.\r\n\r\nThe course is the perfect \"warm-up\" venue or a place for beginners to learn the etiquette and basics of the game without the pressure of a long course. It is particularly famous for its 9th green, which features two distinct levels that will test even the most confident putter. The facility is a hub of modern golf, featuring a professional academy and excellent catering. For families or those with limited time, Leitfie Links offers a high-speed, high-quality golfing experience that proves you don\'t need par-fives to have a memorable day on the links.', ''),
('lenzie', 'Lenzie', 'https://www.lenziegolfclub.co.uk/', 'competition2', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'intelligent', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.912971, -4.149136, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.lenziegolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000002a08a1bb79810c02499d53bdcf44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lenzie Golf Club is a classic parkland course situated in East Dunbartonshire, just north of Glasgow. Founded in 1889 as a 9-hole layout, it was extended to its current 18-hole form in 1907. The course is characterized by its lush fairways and an impressive collection of mature trees that provide both shelter and a significant tactical challenge. From the highest point of the course at the 10th tee, players are rewarded with panoramic views of the Campsie Hills and, on clear days, the distant peak of Ben Lomond.\r\n\r\nA unique feature of Lenzie is its four par-three holes, which are cleverly routed to face different points of the compass, ensuring that the prevailing wind affects each one differently. The club has a long history of competitive success and is a regular host of regional Glasgow and Dunbartonshire tournaments. Under the guidance of PGA professionals like Alan Waugh, the club has maintained a high standard of tuition and playability. It is a traditional, welcoming club where the quality of the greens and the friendliness of the clubhouse have made it a favorite for over 130 years.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('leslie', 'Leslie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/leslie#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.205103, -3.213206, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'leslie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e17cea58a5b409c0dfa7aad0401a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Leslie Golf Club in Fife is a historic 9-hole parkland course that acts as a living link to the \"Golden Age\" of golf architecture. Founded in 1898, the course was designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris in collaboration with Charles Anderson. Despite its modest length, Leslie is notoriously difficult, featuring small, plateau greens that require surgical precision with the short irons. It has remained largely unchanged for over 125 years, offering a pure and nostalgic look at how the game was played at the turn of the century.\r\n\r\nThe course\'s signature 2nd hole was once described by legendary broadcaster Peter Alliss as \"probably the most difficult hole in world golf\"a narrow, 423-yard par-four that requires a nerve-wracking drive to a \"bottle\" green. The club is a pioneer in modern recreational golf, being one of the first in the region to incorporate a 9-hole FootGolf course alongside the traditional layout. It is a community-focused club with a popular caf, Susan\'s Kitchen, providing a warm welcome. For those who want to experience the strategic genius of Old Tom Morris on a compact and affordable canvas, Leslie is a true hidden gem.', ''),
('levenlinks', 'Leven', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/levenlinks', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/levenlinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.197846, -2.988865, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'levenlinks', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000b745990d32e907c07cd2890453194c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Leven Links is a giant of the Scottish game and one of the oldest and purest links courses in the world. Originally founded in 1846, the course took its modern 18-hole form in 1868 following input from Old Tom Morris. To celebrate its opening, an exhibition match was held and won by the 17-year-old Young Tom Morris, the greatest player of his era. It is a classic links characterized by ancient sand dunes, deep pot bunkers, and the famous \"Scoonie Burn\" that guards the final green.\r\n\r\nThe course has an immense tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship on six occasions between 1978 and 2005. It remains a regular host for the Standard Life Leven Gold Medal, the world\'s oldest amateur stroke-play tournament. Leven is a \"thinking man\'s links\" where the bump-and-run shot is an essential tool, especially during the dry summer months. Shared between the Leven Thistle Golf Club and the Leven Golfing Society, the course represents the absolute pinnacle of traditional Fife links golf, offering a historic and uncompromising test of skill.', ''),
('liberton', 'Liberton', 'https://www.libertongc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.918928, -3.147244, 0, 0, '', '', '', 4571, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ff4124438e2d09c079b0c56e9ff54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Liberton Golf Club, located just four miles from Edinburgh city center, is a charming parkland course that made history upon its founding in 1920 as one of the first clubs in Britain to put male and female members on an equal footing. The course is situated on 89 acres of undulating land and, despite its relatively short length of 5,344 yards, it is widely respected as a \"card-wrecker\" due to its tight, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally small greens guarded by deep bunkers.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud competitive history, frequently hosting the Lothians Seniors and Junior Championships. A notable figure in the club\'s history is W. Dakers, a former club champion who served as the Secretary of the Scottish Golf Union for 25 years. Under the guidance of PGA professional Iain Seath, the club has developed excellent practice facilities, including a dedicated pitching and chipping area. Liberton is a friendly, progressive club that offers a tactical and refined round of golf, where accuracy is rewarded far more than brute force, making it a favorite for the capital\'s golfers.', ''),
('lilliardsedge', 'Lilliardsedge', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lilliardsedge#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.532688, -2.602684, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lilliardsedge', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000068942efd4bd204c05f7cd11e2fc44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lilliardsedge Golf Club is a hidden gem tucked away within the rolling hills of the Scottish Borders. Originally a 9-hole layout, the course now utilizes 18 separate tees to create a varied and challenging 5,299-yard experience. Set within a beautifully landscaped holiday park, the course feels significantly more established than its modern origins suggest. The layout is characterized by its natural water features, including a central lake and several winding burns that come into play on the most critical approach shots.\r\n\r\nWhile the course does not have a \"celebrity\" architect attached to its name, it is a masterclass in modern, community-focused design. The greens are notoriously tricky, featuring subtle slopes that require a sharp eye. The club is a popular venue for the Borders Golfers\' Association and maintains a high standard of conditioning year-round. It is a friendly, relaxed environment where the tavern at the turn offers some of the best golfing hospitality in the region. For those touring the south of Scotland, Lilliardsedge provides a peaceful and scenic round of golf that rewards accuracy and strategic placement over raw distance.', ''),
('Lilliesleaf', 'Lilliesleaf', 'https://www.dimpleknowe.co.uk/index.php/golf-course', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'borders', '', 55.493330, -2.784459, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000446cb070924606c05e11fc6f25bf4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lilliesleaf Golf Course, also known as Dimpleknowe, is a quirky and charismatic 11-hole course that offers a refreshing alternative to the traditional 18-hole format. Situated on a private country estate in the heart of the Borders, the course measures a testing 2,563 yards for its primary loop. It is a \"fun\" course in the truest sensethe dress code is informal, children and dogs are welcomed, and the focus is firmly on the enjoyment of the game. Despite its relaxed atmosphere, the layout features genuine challenges, including a testing par-five and several tight par-threes.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its natural, unpretentious beauty, with fairways that wind through mature woodland and over natural slopes. There is no \"famous\" architect here; instead, the course has been lovingly shaped by the estate owners to reflect the rugged charm of the surrounding landscape. The club recently added a covered BBQ area near the starter\'s hut, making it a favorite for family outings and social groups. It is an honest, traditional Scottish \"village\" course where the spirit of the game is kept alive through community passion and a total lack of pretense.', ''),
('linlithgow', 'Linlithgow', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/linlithgow#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/linlithgow#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.965327, -3.625338, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'linlithgow', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000082919735b1000dc01079cbd58ffb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Linlithgow Golf Club is a magnificent parkland course that celebrated its centenary in 2013. The original layout was designed in 1913 by Robert Simpson, the legendary professional at Carnoustie, and four of his original holes still survive today. The course was eventually expanded to 18 holes in the 1950s thanks to the patronage of the MacKinnon family (of Drambuie fame), who purchased the surrounding farmland to protect the club\'s future. Mrs. Gena MacKinnon was a beloved figure at the club, famously performing the opening ceremony every year for decades.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its dramatic elevation changes and panoramic views over the Forth Valley and the Ochil Hills. It is a tactical test where the \"braehead\" winds often dictate play. Notable tournaments include the West Lothian County Championships, and the club has a reputation for producing high-caliber amateur talent. The signature holes along the ridge require nerve and a steady hand. With its deep connection to Scottish industry and its classic Simpson-influenced design, Linlithgow offers a polished and historic golfing experience in the shadow of the royal burgh\'s famous palace.', ''),
('littlehill', 'Littlehill', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/littlehill#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.897048, -4.217077, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'littlehill', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ecdade6e49de10c09a780778d2f24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Littlehill Golf Course is a historic 18-hole parkland gem located just north of Glasgow city center. Opened in 1923, the course was designed by the most prolific architect in history, James Braid. Littlehill carries a significant championship pedigree, having served as an Open Championship Qualifying venue in the mid-20th century. Braid utilized the relatively flat terrain to create a layout that emphasizes strategic bunkering and large, subtly sloping greens, making it a fair but formidable test for golfers of all abilities.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal course, Littlehill has been a vital training ground for generations of Glasgow golfers. Its lush fairways are lined with a diverse range of mature trees, providing a sense of seclusion despite its proximity to the city. The course is famously well-maintained, with its greens often cited as some of the fastest in the municipal circuit. Notable for its friendly, unpretentious atmosphere, Littlehill represents the \"Braid\" philosophy of accessible, high-quality golf for the people. It remains a popular choice for those seeking a historic and well-conditioned round of golf without the formality of a private estate.', ''),
('Lochcarron', 'Lochcarron', 'https://lochcarrongolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.413842, -5.472430, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000dd989eb0c4e315c00adb4fc6f8b44c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochcarron Golf Club offers one of the most cinematic 9-hole experiences in the Scottish Highlands. Founded in 1908 on the shores of Wester Ross, the course is surrounded by the dramatic peaks of the Strathcarron mountains. Little has changed in its layout over the last century, with the shores of the loch serving as a natural (and terminal) boundary for many holes. The names of the holes, such as \"Churchyard\" and \"Burnside\" reflect the course\'s deep roots in the local community.\r\n\r\nWhile it lacks a professional \"name\" architect, the layout is a masterpiece of natural design, with the routing dictated by the rugged shoreline and the surrounding hills. The club recently secured its future by purchasing the land and building a modern clubhouse that offers some of the finest views in the Highlands. It is an \"honesty box\" course that rewards the adventurous golfer with a pure, raw connection to the origins of the game. For those traveling the North Coast 500, a stop at Lochcarron is a mandatory pilgrimage to play a course that feels as though it was carved out of the landscape by the elements themselves.', ''),
('lochgelly', 'Lochgelly', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochgelly#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochgelly#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.126646, -3.321588, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lochgelly', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d449b6ba9c920ac0a915a6ef35104c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochgelly Golf Club is a rugged and rewarding parkland course in the heart of Fife. Established in 1895, the course was originally a 9-hole layout before being extended to 18 holes in the 1920s with input from the legendary James Braid. The course is built on a series of natural ridges, providing a physical test and offering expansive views across the Forth toward Edinburgh. It is a course with an \"industrial heart\" founded by local miners who shaped the land with their own hands.\r\n\r\nThe layout is known for its firm, well-draining turf and its challenging par-fives that require both power and precision. Notable tournaments held here include the Fife County Championships, and the club has a reputation for its fiercely competitive but welcoming membership. The signature \"ridge holes\" demand a creative approach, as the wind often sweeps across the exposed fairways. It is a traditional, no-nonsense Scottish club where the quality of the golf and the warmth of the hospitality are the primary attractions. For those seeking an authentic and challenging Fife parkland experience, Lochgelly is a hidden gem that punches well above its weight.', ''),
('Lochgilphead', 'Lochgilphead', 'https://www.lochgilpheadgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.044228, -5.415238, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ce39782634a915c0a3c85a43a9054c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochgilphead Golf Club is a delightful 9-hole course situated at the head of Loch Gilp in Argyll. Established in 1891, the course was refined in the early 20th century by James Braid, who was a frequent visitor to the region. Braid\'s influence is seen in the clever use of the undulating terrain and the placement of several strategic hazards that protect the small, fast greens. The course offers spectacular views over the loch and the surrounding mountains of Knapdale.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its \"open\" and inclusive atmosphere. While it may be short in yardage, the course is notoriously difficult to play to your handicap, as the natural slopes often funnel well-struck shots toward the rough. It has produced many fine local champions and is a regular venue for Argyll and Bute regional events. The signature par-three holes require surgical precision with the short irons. It is a quintessential West Highland courserugged, scenic, and deeply traditionaloffering a tranquil and engaging round of golf in one of the most beautiful corners of the country.', ''),
('lochgoilhead', 'Lochgoilhead', 'https://lochgoilhead.info/golf-club/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 56.172492, -4.905291, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000da73999a049f13c02b69c53714164c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochgoilhead Golf Club is a stunningly located 9-hole course set within the Drimsynie Estate in the Cowal Peninsula. Originally laid out in the 1970s to complement the local holiday resort, the course has matured into a scenic parkland layout that provides a stern test of accuracy. It is surrounded by the dramatic peaks of the \"Arrochar Alps\" and the views from the tees are among the most photographed in the region. The course is characterized by its steep elevation changes and narrow, tree-lined fairways.\r\n\r\nWhile it lacks a historic architect, the layout is a clever use of a challenging site, requiring golfers to navigate natural gullies and rocky outcrops. The club has a relaxed, resort-style atmosphere, making it a favorite for families and visitors. However, the greens are remarkably well-maintained and can be quite slick in the summer months. Notable for its peace and seclusion, Lochgoilhead offers a \"mountain golf\" experience where the scenery is as much a part of the challenge as the hazards themselves. It is a perfect example of how modern recreational design can harmonize with a wild and ancient landscape.', ''),
('LochLomond', 'Loch Lomond', 'https://www.lochlomond.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 56.061076, -4.632450, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000ba6b09f9a08712c006499f56d1074c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Loch Lomond Golf Club is a world-renowned masterpiece of parkland design. Opened in 1993, the course was designed by the legendary partnership of Tom Weiskopf and Jay Morrish. It is consistently ranked as one of the top 100 courses in the world and served as the long-time home of the Scottish Open on the European Tour. The course is set within the ancestral lands of the Colquhoun Clan, with the 18th-century Rossdhu House serving as the most magnificent clubhouse in the sport.\r\n\r\nThe club is notoriously exclusive, with a membership that includes global titans of industry and major-winning professionals. Each hole is entirely secluded from the next, winding through ancient woodland and along the \"bonnie banks\" of the loch. Notable members have included Sir Jackie Stewart and Sean Connery. The ruins of Rossdhu Castle overlook the 18th green, providing a hauntingly beautiful backdrop to the finishing hole. To play Loch Lomond is to experience the absolute pinnacle of luxury golf-an impeccably manicured sanctuary where history, nature, and world-class architecture meet.', ''),
('lochmaben', 'Lochmaben', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochmaben#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochmaben#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.127530, -3.441140, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lochmaben', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d6a8876874870bc023a12de752904b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochmaben Golf Club is a historic parkland course in Dumfriesshire with a layout of immense archaeological significance. Founded in 1926, the original 9-hole course was designed by the five-time Open Champion James Braid. The course is built on the site of one of King Robert the Bruce\'s first castles, and the mottes of the ancient fortress are clearly visible on the 2nd and 4th holes. The layout was eventually expanded to 18 holes, creating a scenic and testing circuit that encircles the Kirk Loch.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its \"Swan\'s Nest\" hole, a dramatic dog-leg where the water of the loch sits just yards behind the green. Notable tournaments include the South of Scotland Championships, and the club is highly regarded for its fast-running turf and immaculate conditioning. The connection to the Bruce family is central to the club\'s identity, with the town\'s motto, \"From us is born the liberator king\" proudly displayed in the clubhouse. It is a friendly, scenic, and intellectually stimulating course that offers a unique blend of championship-standard golf and ancient Scottish history.', ''),
('lochnessfairways', 'Loch Ness - Fairways Golf Centre', 'https://fairwaysgolfcentreandrestaurant.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.454269, -4.210326, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000076feedb25fd710c0164b917c25ba4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Loch Ness Golf Club, specifically the Fairways Golf Centre, provides a modern and inclusive approach to the game in the capital of the Highlands. Opened in the late 1990s, the facility features a championship-length 18-hole course alongside a shorter, family-friendly 9-hole layout. The main course is a lush parkland design that offers expansive views of the surrounding hills. It was designed to be a \"fair\" testwide enough to accommodate the casual golfer but long enough to challenge the local low-handicappers.\r\n\r\nThe centre is a hub for golf development in the North, boasting a state-of-the-art driving range and a popular golf academy. While it may not have the ancient pedigree of its coastal neighbors, it has become a staple for regional PGA Scotland events. Notable for its relaxed atmosphere and lack of stuffy traditions, Fairways is where many of Inverness\'s rising stars first gripped a club. The par-four finishing hole, requiring a carry over water to a green overlooked by the clubhouse balcony, provides a theatrical end to a round that highlights the growth of modern Scottish golf.', ''),
('lochoremeadows', 'Lochore Meadows', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochoremeadows#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochoremeadows#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.149960, -3.329590, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lochoremeadows', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000089b5f81400a30ac0a5daa7e331134c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochore Meadows Golf Course is a scenic 9-hole parkland layout situated within a massive country park in Fife. Developed on the site of a former colliery, the course is a triumph of land reclamation, transforming an industrial landscape into a tranquil sporting haven. Opened in the 1980s, the course wraps around the shores of Loch Ore, with several holes offering stunning water views. The layout is relatively flat, making it an accessible walk, but mature tree-planting and strategic bunkers ensure it remains a respectable test.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vital community asset, serving as a primary venue for the Fife Municipal Golf Association. It is particularly famous for its abundant wildlife; it is not uncommon to see deer or ospreys while lining up a putt. While it does not boast a celebrity architect, the routing is praised for its logical flow and its ability to drain well during the wet Scottish winters. It is a \"people\'s course\" in the best sense, offering high-quality golf at a very affordable price, proving that the heart of the Scottish game often beats strongest in these reclaimed community spaces.', ''),
('lochranza', 'Lochranza', 'https://www.arran-campsite.com/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.700019, -5.273260, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000047382d78d11715c010cafb389ad94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located at the northern tip of the Isle of Arran, Lochranza Golf Course is a 9-hole moorland and parkland hybrid that offers a truly unique Highland experience. Surrounded by dramatic mountains and the ruins of a 13th-century castle, the course is as much a nature reserve as it is a sporting venue. It is famously the home of a massive herd of red deer, who are so accustomed to golfers that they often remain lounging on the fairways while players hit their shotsa local rule dictates that a ball coming to rest near a deer may be dropped without penalty!\r\n\r\nThe course is natural and unpretentious, reflecting the wild beauty of its surroundings. There is no \"famous\" architect here; instead, the terrain dictates the play, with natural burns and steep banks serving as the primary hazards. The club is a favorite for visitors staying at the nearby youth hostel or distillery, offering a relaxed and incredibly atmospheric round. Playing at Lochranza is less about the technicalities of the swing and more about the spiritual connection to the Scottish landscape, making it a \"must-play\" for any golfing romantic.', ''),
('lochview', 'Lochview', 'https://www.activenl.co.uk/lochview-family-golf-centre', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.872854, -4.058692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b72572c1193c10c065170caeb9ef4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochview Family Golf Centre, located in Coatbridge, is a premier municipal facility that has become a cornerstone of golf in North Lanarkshire. The 18-hole parkland course is designed with playability in mind, featuring wide fairways and large, consistent greens. As the name suggests, the course offers pleasant views over the local loch and parkland. It was developed to provide a high-quality, professional environment for the general public, and it succeeds through meticulous maintenance and excellent practice facilities.\r\n\r\nThe centre is a pioneer in the \"Golf for All\" movement, featuring a floodlit driving range and a comprehensive junior program that has introduced thousands of local children to the sport. While it doesn\'t host the professional majors, it is a frequent venue for Lanarkshire County junior events. The layout is strategic without being punishing, rewarding those who can navigate the gentle undulations of the Lanarkshire countryside. For many in the central belt, Lochview represents the ideal balance of affordability, quality, and a welcoming, modern club atmosphere.', ''),
('lochwinnoch', 'Loch Winnoch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochwinnoch#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lochwinnoch#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.795790, -4.638190, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lochwinnoch', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007689eaad818d12c0ee3d5c72dce54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lochwinnoch Golf Club is a spectacular 18-hole parkland-moorland hybrid perched on the hills overlooking the Renfrewshire countryside. Founded in 1923, the course was significantly redesigned by the esteemed James Braid in the late 1920s. Braid\'s genius is evident in the way the course utilizes the steep terrain to create a variety of challenging shots, including several dramatic elevated tees. On a clear day, the views from the higher holes stretch across the Clyde to the mountains of the southern Highlands.\r\n\r\nThe club has a reputation for being one of the friendliest in the region, with a lively social scene. Notable for its impeccably fast greens, the course is a regular host for the Renfrewshire County Championships. The signature 12th hole, a par-three played from a high tee to a green guarded by a burn, is one of the most memorable in the county. While the climb can be physically demanding, the reward is a high-quality, historic Braid layout that offers a tranquil escape from the urban hustle of nearby Glasgow.', ''),
('lockerbie', 'Lockerbie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lockerbie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lockerbie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.124990, -3.346060, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lockerbie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004da1f31abbc40ac0dc291dacff8f4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lockerbie Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course in Dumfriesshire with a layout that dates back to 1889. The course was significantly refined by the legendary James Braid in the 1920s, who turned it into a challenging 18-hole test that winds through mature woodland and over natural slopes. Braid\'s influence is seen in the well-placed bunkering and the trueness of the greens. The course offers a peaceful, sheltered environment with views stretching toward the Lake District on a clear day.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history and was famously a favorite of the local community who rebuilt the clubhouse following the tragedy of 1988, turning it into a symbol of resilience and hospitality. Notable tournaments held here include the South of Scotland Amateur Championship. The course is known for its \"hidden\" challengessmall streams and subtle dog-legs that punish the overly aggressive player. It is a traditional, unpretentious club where the quality of the playing surface is matched by the warmth of the welcome, representing the very best of Borders parkland golf.', ''),
('longniddry', 'Longniddry', 'https://www.longniddrygolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.976589, -2.908344, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.longniddrygolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000008124ecdb494407c011514cde00fd4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Longniddry Golf Club is a unique and prestigious course on the East Lothian \"Golf Coast.\" Founded in 1921, it was designed by the esteemed Harry Colt, one of the most famous architects in the history of the game. Longniddry is a rare hybrid, blending the characteristics of a traditional links with the shelter and trees of a woodland course. It famously has no par-fives, meaning its par of 68 is one of the toughest to beat in the country. It has frequently served as an Open Championship Qualifying venue.\r\n\r\nThe course has a high-society pedigree and has counted many prominent figures from Edinburgh\'s legal and medical circles among its members. Notable visitors have included Sir Henry Cotton, who praised the strategic demands of Colt\'s design. The layout is notorious for its sea breezes and its fast, undulating greens. Because there are no par-fives, accuracy and a sharp short game are absolutely paramount. Longniddry offers a refined, aristocratic experience that bridges the gap between the wild links of Gullane and the manicured parklands of Edinburgh, making it an essential stop for the serious golfer.', ''),
('longsidegolfclub', 'Longside', 'https://www.longsidegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.longsidegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.520184, -1.936980, 0, 2417, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e71890bddefdfebf84f3a96395c24c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Longside Golf Club, located in the heart of the Buchan countryside in Aberdeenshire, is a relatively modern 18-hole parkland course that has quickly built a reputation for its conditioning. Opened in 1979 as a 9-hole course and extended to 18 in 1996, the layout was designed by the local committee to provide a testing alternative to the nearby links. The course is characterized by its wide-open spaces and the South Ugie Water, which meanders through the property and provides a natural hazard on no fewer than seven holes.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point for the local agricultural community and is known for its incredibly relaxed and welcoming atmosphere. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the layout is highly regarded for its clever use of the water and the prevailing North Sea winds. The greens are often cited as some of the most consistent in the North East. Longside is a frequent host of Aberdeenshire County junior events, reflecting its commitment to growing the game. For those looking for an honest, wind-swept parkland challenge in a peaceful rural setting, Longside offers a high-value and enjoyable round of golf.', ''),
('loudoungowf', 'Loudoun Gowf', 'https://loudoungowf.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://loudoungowf.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.605190, -4.363000, 0, 0, '', '', 'loudoungowf', 132, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c1caa145b67311c0e1eeacdd76cd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Loudoun Gowf Club is a historic and unique parkland gem in Ayrshire. The club uses the archaic spelling \"Gowf\" reflecting its deep roots in Scottish tradition; while founded in 1908, golf was played in the area for centuries before. The course was designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie and refined by the legendary James Braid. It is set within the magnificent grounds of Loudoun Castle, and the ancient trees and stone walls of the estate provide a stately atmosphere throughout the round.\r\n\r\nThe course is famously flat, making it an enjoyable walk, but its defense lies in its incredibly narrow fairways and small, well-protected greens. Notable members over the years have included various Ayrshire dignitaries and sporting legends. Loudoun has hosted many prestigious amateur events, including the Ayrshire Strokeplay Championship. The 18th hole, finishing right in front of the traditional clubhouse, is a highlight. It is a refined, \"gentleman\'s\" club that prioritizes precision and etiquette, offering a polished parkland experience steeped in the history of the Ayrshire aristocracy.', ''),
('Luffness', 'Luffness New', 'https://www.luffnessnew.com/visitor-booking/', 'https://www.luffnessnew.com/visitor-booking/', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sun', 'eastlothian', '', 56.022171, -2.842449, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000001b62bce655bd06c0b6f5d37fd6024c40, 'links', 'No', 'Luffness New Golf Club is a titan of East Lothian golf and one of the most traditional clubs in the world. Founded in 1894, the course was designed by Old Tom Morris, and it remains a pure, unadulterated links experience. Luffness is famous for its lack of modern \"clutter\"-there are no yardage markers, no flashy signage, and a strict adherence to traditional dress codes and etiquette. It has a formidable tournament pedigree, having served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship for decades.\r\n\r\nThe course is a sanctuary of fast-running turf, deep revetted bunkers, and thick, punishing rough. Notable members have included legends of the game and members of the British establishment who value its privacy and tranquility. Unlike the hilly Gullane nearby, Luffness is relatively flat, but the wind is a constant and brutal defender of par. The clubhouse is a time capsule of 19th-century golfing elegance, and the lunch is as famous as the greens. To play Luffness is to step back into the \"Golden Age\" of golf, offering a quiet, serious, and immensely rewarding links challenge.', ''),
('lumphanangolfclub', 'Lumphanan', 'https://www.lumphanangolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.lumphanangolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.126173, -2.682287, 0, 2422, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003be3fbe2527505c0b151d66f26904c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lumphanan Golf Club is a captivating 9-hole course in Aberdeenshire that provides a classic \"Highland\" golfing experience. Founded in 1923, the course is perched on the slopes of the Marr area, offering panoramic views of the surrounding mountains and valleys. It is a physically engaging course, characterized by its significant elevation changes and the lush, springy turf typical of the region. The layout was designed to work with the natural contours of the hill, meaning level lies are a luxury rather than a guarantee.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vibrant hub for the local community and is known for its incredibly warm and unpretentious welcome. While it may not have a \"celebrity\" architect, the clever routing makes excellent use of natural hazards like the winding burns and granite outcrops. The signature hole, \"The Coffin\" requires a precise shot over a deep hollow to a green perched on a plateau. Lumphanan is the quintessential village clubpeaceful, scenic, and deeply traditional. It offers a high-value round of golf for those who appreciate the raw beauty of the North East countryside and the challenge of mountain-style play.', ''),
('lundingc', 'Lundin Links', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lundingc#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/lundingc#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.216630, -2.949101, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'lundingc', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000a3cedc43c29707c08faa2688ba1b4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Lundin Links is a powerhouse of Scottish golf and a perennial Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship. Originally founded in 1868, the course was redesigned in 1909 by the legendary James Braid after the club split with its neighbor, Leven. Braid utilized the dramatic, undulating links land and the adjacent higher ground to create a hybrid masterpiece. The first five holes are pure links, the middle section offers a more elevated \"parkland\" feel with spectacular views over the Firth of Forth, and the finishing stretch returns to the classic dunes.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted almost every major amateur championship in Scotland and has seen legends like Gene Sarazen and Gary Player grace its fairways. Notable for its narrow fairways, deep bunkers, and the \"Miles Burn\" that crosses the course twice, it is a formidable test of accuracy and nerve. The clubhouse is an architectural gem, and the sense of history is palpable. Lundin Links is a \"pure\" golfer\'s course-historic, challenging, and impeccably maintained-offering one of the most varied and rewarding links experiences in Fife.', ''),
('lundinladies', 'Lundin Ladies', 'https://lundinladiesgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.214615, -2.953575, 0, 2425, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000fe43faedeba007c0931d1b81781b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Lundin Ladies\' Golf Club holds a unique and prestigious place in the history of the game as the oldest women\'s golf club in the world, founded in 1891. Situated just inland from the famous championship links, this 9-hole course was designed by James Braid in 1910. While the club was founded for women, it is now a welcoming destination for all, but it retains its traditional, intimate charm. The course is a beautiful parkland-links hybrid, featuring small, tricky greens and several significant natural hazards, including the ancient Standing Stones of Lundin.\r\n\r\nThe course is famously well-manicured and provides a shorter, more tactical alternative to the punishing championship tracks nearby. Notable members have included pioneers of women\'s golf who fought for the right to play on equal terms. Despite its modest yardage, the course is notoriously difficult to \"master\" due to the precision required on the approach shots. It is a peaceful, historic sanctuary that offers a relaxed and incredibly atmospheric round. For the golfing historian, a visit to Lundin Ladies is a mandatory pilgrimage to experience the roots of the inclusive modern game in a setting of timeless beauty.', ''),
('Lybster', 'Lybster', 'https://lybstergolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.304533, -3.283954, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000000d8cbcac89450ac0c1c6f5effa264d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Lybster Golf Club is a hidden gem of the far North, located on the rugged coast of Caithness. This 9-hole course is one of the shortest in Scotland, but what it lacks in distance, it more than makes up for in character and challenge. Founded in 1905, the course is situated on a cliff-top site overlooking the North Sea. The layout is a raw, natural links experience where the wind is the primary architect and defender. On a clear day, the views stretch across the Moray Firth to the hills of Aberdeenshire.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility, maintained by a dedicated group of local volunteers who take immense pride in their small piece of golfing heaven. The greens are remarkably true, and the fairways are lined with gorse and wildflowers. One of the most famous features is the proximity to the historic Grey Cairns of Camster and the local \"Whaligoe Steps.\" It is a place of total solitude, where the only sound is the crashing of the waves against the cliffs. For those traveling the North Coast 500, Lybster offers a pure, unadulterated connection to the origins of Scottish golf in a wild and stunning landscape.', ''),
('Lynedoch', 'Murrayshall - Lynedoch', 'https://www.murrayshall.co.uk/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.419170, -3.368315, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008a027d224ff20ac06fbbd05ca7354c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Lynedoch Course at Murrayshall Country Estate near Perth is a high-quality parkland test that complements the main championship course. Opened in 2000 and designed by Graeme Webster, the Lynedoch is a shorter, tighter, and more technical layout that winds through towering Scots pine and mature woodland. Webster utilized the natural undulations of the estate to create a \"target golf\" experience where accuracy from the tee is far more important than raw power.\r\n\r\nThe course has a modern, professional feel and is maintained to an exceptionally high standard. It is a frequent venue for regional PGA Scotland events and serves as an excellent challenge for those looking to hone their iron play. The greens are notoriously fast and feature subtle breaks that demand a sharp eye. With the backdrop of the Perthshire hills and the luxury of the estate hotel, the Lynedoch offers a polished and secluded golfing experience. It is the perfect choice for a second round of the day, providing a varied and engaging contrast to the more expansive championship layout at the resort.', ''),
('machrie', 'The Machrie', 'https://book.rguest.eu/onecart/golf/courses/10278/TheMachrie', 'https://book.rguest.eu/onecart/golf/courses/10278/TheMachrie', 'Yes', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'islands', 'No', 55.664637, -6.256074, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000726c3d43380619c0145b41d312d54b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Machrie, located on the Isle of Islay, is a legendary links that sits among the upper echelons of world golf. Originally designed in 1891 by Willie Campbell, the course underwent a total transformation in 2018 by architect David J. Russell. The redesign modernized the layout while preserving the soul of its ancient, towering dunes. It is a pure links experience, characterized by massive elevation changes, hidden hollows, and panoramic views of the Atlantic Ocean and the Big Strand beach.\r\n\r\nThe course has a storied history, once hosting an exhibition match in 1901 with a prize fund that rivaled the Open Championship. Notable visitors include every serious student of links golf, drawn by its reputation for raw beauty and tactical complexity. The turf is firm and fast-running, and the wind is a constant, shifting factor. The modern hotel and clubhouse have turned The Machrie into a world-class destination. To play here is to experience golf in its most elemental form-a wild, spectacular, and deeply moving journey across one of the most historic pieces of links land in existence.', ''),
('machriebay', 'Machrie Bay', 'https://www.machriebay.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.machriebay.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.555053, -5.341588, 0, 2428, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000fed2a23ec95d15c0fa4509fa0bc74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'On the opposite side of the island from its world-famous namesake, Machrie Bay on the Isle of Arran is a delightful 9-hole course that offers a completely different experience. Established in 1900, the course is a traditional, family-run links that sits right on the shoreline. It is a flat, easy-to-walk course that emphasizes fun and accessibility. The layout is natural and unpretentious, with the sea coming into play on several holes and the dramatic peaks of Arran providing a stunning backdrop.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its relaxed atmosphere and its excellent tearoom, which is a destination in its own right for locals and visitors alike. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the course has a unique charm, featuring small greens and narrow fairways that require a steady hand. It is a favorite for families and for those looking for a quick, scenic round before heading to the nearby distillery. Machrie Bay represents the \"joy of the game\"a place where the focus is on the beauty of the surroundings and the companionship of the round. It is a quintessential Scottish island course that leaves every visitor with a smile.', ''),
('machrihanish', 'Machrihanish', 'https://machrihanish.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://machrihanish.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.433016, -5.716739, 0, 0, '', '', 'machrihanish', 7910, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000002b1213d4f0dd16c087527b116db74b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Machrihanish Golf Club is a titan of the game, home to what is widely considered the greatest opening hole in world golf. Designed by the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" Old Tom Morris, in 1876, the course is a pure links situated on the remote Kintyre Peninsula. The 1st hole, \"Battery\" requires a heroic drive over the Atlantic beach to find the fairway-a shot that has challenged every great player from Babe Zaharias to Jack Nicklaus. It is an uncompromising and atmospheric test of links golf.\r\n\r\nThe course is a sanctuary of natural dunes, hidden hollows, and lightning-fast greens. It has a prestigious tournament history, frequently hosting the Scottish Ladies\' Championship and regional qualifying for major events. Notable for its \"out and back\" routing, the course takes players deep into the wild dunes of Machrihanish Bay. The sense of isolation and the raw power of the sea make playing here a spiritual experience for many. It is a course that rewards creativity and a low ball flight. For any serious golfer, a trip to Machrihanish is a pilgrimage to one of the most hallowed and beautiful sites in the history of the sport.', ''),
('machrihanishdunes', 'Machrihanish Dunes', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/machrihanishdunes', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/machrihanishdunes#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.451633, -5.710137, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'machrihanishdunes', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000dcb75a272ed716c0ae65321ccfb94b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Machrihanish Dunes is a revolutionary modern links that sits adjacent to the historic Old Tom Morris course. Opened in 2009 and designed by David McLay Kidd (the architect behind Bandon Dunes), it is the first course ever built on a site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI). As such, the design was \"found\" rather than built; no heavy machinery was used to shape the fairways, and the layout follows the natural, rugged contours of the dunes exactly as they have sat for centuries.\r\n\r\nThe course is a wild, adventurous experience, featuring massive, undulating greens and deep natural blow-outs. It is notoriously difficult, especially when the wind whips off the Atlantic, requiring a huge variety of shots and a high degree of patience. Notable visitors include modern stars of the game who appreciate the \"raw\" and ecological approach to design. The Dunes offers a fascinating contrast to its neighbor, providing a much more rugged and unpredictable round. It is a testament to sustainable design and a \"must-play\" for those who want to see how the origins of links golf are being reimagined for the 21st century.', ''),
('MainsofTaymouth', 'Mains of Taymouth', 'https://www.taymouth.co.uk/on-site-facilities/kenmore-golf-course.php', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.588849, -4.002008, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004c5299620e0210c023a46e675f4b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Mains of Taymouth, located in the heart of Kenmore at the tip of Loch Tay, is often described as the \"finest 9-hole course in Perthshire.\" Opened in 1992, the course was designed to complement the luxury holiday estate and offers a high-quality parkland experience. The layout is set on a hillside, providing spectacular views over the loch and the surrounding mountains of the Tay Valley. It is characterized by its large, undulating greens and several significant water hazards that require strategic navigation.\r\n\r\nThe course has a modern, resort-style feel and is maintained to an impeccable standard. While it is a shorter course, the elevation changes and the narrow, tree-lined fairways provide a stern test of accuracy. It is a popular venue for visitors staying in the estate\'s luxury cottages and has built a strong reputation for its friendly, professional atmosphere. The signature 9th hole requires an approach over a pond to a green overlooked by the clubhouse balcony. Mains of Taymouth is a perfect example of a high-end \"boutique\" golf course, offering a peaceful and scenic round in one of Scotland\'s most beautiful lochside settings.', ''),
('MarHall', 'Mar Hall', 'https://www.marhall.com/golf/the-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.921013, -4.478013, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005b40683d7ce911c06e1805c1e3f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Mar Hall Golf & Spa Resort is home to the Earl of Mar course, a five-star championship parkland layout that graces the banks of the River Clyde. Designed by the renowned architect Dave Thomasthe man behind the Brabazon at The Belfrythe course was carved out of 240 acres of ancient wooded estate in 2010. Thomas skillfully incorporated the estate\'s 250-year-old chestnut and beech trees into the routing, creating a course that feels far older than its years.\r\n\r\nThe resort has a high-society pedigree, with the 19th-century gothic mansion (designed by Sir Robert Smirke) serving as one of Scotland\'s most luxurious clubhouses. Famous guests have included A-list celebrities and world-class athletes, from Lionel Messi to Kylie Minogue, who have sought the privacy and elegance of the estate. While the course provides a stern test for the low-handicapper with its strategic bunkering and water hazards, it remains accessible for guests looking for a relaxed round. Notable tournaments often include high-end corporate events and regional PGA outings, all held against the dramatic backdrop of the Kilpatrick Hills and the Erskine Bridge.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('maverston', 'Maverston', 'https://maverston.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://maverston.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.655114, -3.170532, 17067, 0, '', '', 'maverston', 4151, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002d5f97e13f5d09c06c938ac6dad34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Maverston Golf Club, located near Urquhart in Moray, is a tranquil Highland retreat that offers a \"hidden gem\" experience. The 18-hole Maverston Course was designed by Euan McIntosh, a former Scottish Internationalist and a formidable name in the amateur game. Opened in 2014, the course takes advantage of the gently undulating landscape of the Maverston Highland Estate. It is a modern parkland layout characterized by its wide-open vistas, offering views of the Garmouth hills to the south and the Moray Firth to the north.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its inclusive and welcoming atmosphere, breaking away from some of the more rigid traditions of older Scottish institutions. While it is a young course, it has quickly gained a reputation for its conditioning and the trueness of its greens. It frequently hosts regional Texas Scramble Opens and Seniors events, drawing players from across the North East. For those seeking a peaceful, scenic round where the air is fresh and the pace of play is unhurried, Maverston provides a high-quality alternative to the crowded coastal links of the region.', ''),
('maverston9', 'Maverston - Kempston', 'https://maverston.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://maverston.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.655114, -3.170532, 18684, 0, '', '', 'maverston', 4151, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002d5f97e13f5d09c06c938ac6dad34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Kempston Course at Maverston is the club\'s delightful 9-hole sibling, providing a shorter but no less engaging challenge. Also designed by Euan McIntosh, the Kempston is a par-three course that serves as the perfect training ground for juniors and beginners, or a high-speed \"short game\" sharpen-up for experienced players. Despite its shorter yardage, the course is maintained to the same exacting standards as the main championship track, featuring manicured greens and clever bunkering.\r\n\r\nThe Kempston is a vital part of the club\'s community-first philosophy, often serving as the gateway for local families and new golfers to enter the sport. It offers a relaxed environment where the technicalities of iron play are the primary focus. Many members use the Kempston for a quick evening round when time is short, enjoying the same spectacular Highland scenery that defines the estate. It is a masterclass in how a modern facility can cater to all levels of the game, ensuring that the \"home of golf\" remains accessible to the next generation.', ''),
('maybole', 'Maybole', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gsacarrick#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.350507, -4.691757, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gsacarrick', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c51d6ff25bc412c07102d369ddac4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Maybole Golf Course is a charming 9-hole parkland course situated in the \"Kingdom of Carrick\" in South Ayrshire. Set within the town\'s Memorial Park, the course offers uninterrupted views of the southern uplands and the Carrick Hills. While many Ayrshire courses are defined by their brutal links land, Maybole is a more sheltered and welcoming experience. It is part of the Golf South Ayrshire stable, which includes the legendary James Braid-designed courses, and it maintains a high standard of public-sector conditioning.\r\n\r\nThe layout is notoriously \"friendly\" with fewer hazards and more generous fairways than its coastal neighbors, making it a favorite for beginners and senior golfers. However, the gentle rolling terrain requires a bit of local knowledge to master the slopes. The club is a pillar of the local community, and its professional staff are often involved in regional development programs. For those following the \"Braid Trail\" or exploring the historic heart of Ayrshire, Maybole provides a tranquil and affordable \"stroll in the park\" that captures the unpretentious spirit of Scottish municipal golf.', ''),
('mcdonald', 'McDonald', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/mcdonald#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/mcdonald#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.370918, -2.081655, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'mcdonald', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000657094bc3aa700c0b6bfb33d7aaf4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'McDonald Golf Club in Ellon is one of Aberdeenshire\'s most beloved parkland treasures. Established in 1926, the course was gifted to the people of Ellon by the local benefactor Sir James McDonald. The original 9-hole layout was carved out of ancient woodland, and the course was eventually expanded to a full 18 holes that wind through majestic forests of rhododendrons and towering hardwoods. The front nine is famously defined by a meandering burn that twists across the fairways and comes into play on nearly every hole.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history in the North East and has produced several notable amateur champions. One of its most famous features is the \"red squirrel sanctuary\" status of the woods; a quiet golfer is often treated to a sighting of the native wildlife during their round. Notable tournaments held here include the Aberdeenshire County Championships. The back nine, in particular, is often cited by locals as one of the most stunning stretches of parkland golf in the country. It is a social, vibrant club that prides itself on maintaining a \"private estate\" feel while remaining a warm and inclusive community hub.', ''),
('mearnscastle', 'Mearns Castle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/mearnscastle#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/mearnscastle#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.772349, -4.289322, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'mearnscastle', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a20dc006442811c0950c0055dce24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Mearns Castle Golf Academy, located just south of Glasgow, is a premier 9-hole parkland course and training facility that has redefined the \"academy\" experience in Scotland. The course is built around the ruins of the 15th-century Mearns Castle, providing a dramatic historical backdrop to the first few holes. In 2015, the routing was modernized to create a more challenging and strategic finish, breaking up the par-threes to ensure a varied test of golf.\r\n\r\nThe facility is perhaps most famous for its world-class practice amenities, including a state-of-the-art Toptracer driving range and short-game area. It is a frequent haunt for local PGA professionals and has been a nursery for several of the West of Scotland\'s rising amateur stars. While the course is public, it maintains a highly competitive membership and hosts regular medals. The signature views across the city toward the Campsies make it a scenic escape. Mearns Castle is the ideal destination for the \"busy\" modern golfer who wants a high-quality, high-tech experience that doesn\'t sacrifice the beauty and challenge of traditional parkland play.', ''),
('meldrumhouse', 'Meldrum House', 'https://www.meldrumhouse.com/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'aberdeen', '', 57.351892, -2.311492, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009db98784ef7d02c0addc0bcc0aad4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Meldrum House Country House & Golf Club is the epitome of Scottish parkland luxury. Designed by the esteemed architect Graeme Webster and opened in 1998, the course sits within a private 240-acre estate in Aberdeenshire. It is one of the few courses in Scotland that can be stretched to over 7,000 yards from the back tees, making it a formidable \"championship\" test. The layout features USGA-spec greens, allowing for world-class playing surfaces twelve months of the year.\r\n\r\nThe club is famously exclusive but offers a refined welcome to visitors staying at the 800-year-old manor house hotel. Notable features include the \"18 bunkers\" that guard the green at the par-five 11th holea sight that has intimidated even the best professional players. Famous guests and members have included international businessmen and sports stars who appreciate the club\'s privacy and high-end service. With its cross-cut fairways, luxury dining domes, and world-class practice facilities, Meldrum House offers a polished, high-gloss golfing experience that rivals the finest resorts in the world.', ''),
('melrose', 'Melrose', 'https://melrosegolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'borders', '', 55.590190, -2.724683, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c3bcc79926cc05c08f368e588bcb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Melrose Golf Club is a rugged and scenic 9-hole course that clings to the base of the iconic Eildon Hills in the Scottish Borders. Founded in 1880, the course is a \"mountain goat\" experience that requires as much fitness as it does finesse. The original layout was significantly improved in the early 20th century, utilizing the steep natural slopes to create a variety of blind shots and dramatic elevation changes. From the highest point of the course, players are treated to a cinematic view of the historic Melrose Abbey and the Tweed Valley.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community, especially during the famous Melrose Sevens rugby weekend, when the clubhouse becomes a hub of activity. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, it is a regular venue for the Borders Golfers\' Association championships. The course is known for its firm, moorland turf and its remarkably small, sloping greens. It is a place where local knowledge is king; knowing which side of the hill to land your ball is more important than how far you can hit it. For the adventurous golfer, Melrose offers a traditional, physical, and intensely beautiful round of golf.', ''),
('Melville', 'Melville', 'https://melvillegolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.886776, -3.098707, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000161747e526ca08c058703fe081f14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Melville Golf Centre, located on the outskirts of Edinburgh, is a modern and highly accessible 9-hole parkland course that caters to the city\'s growing golfing population. Opened in the 1990s, the facility was designed by Graeme Webster to provide a high-quality \"pay as you play\" experience. The course is relatively flat and easy to walk, featuring wide fairways and large greens, making it perfect for beginners or those looking for a stress-free afternoon round.\r\n\r\nThe centre is particularly renowned for its world-class practice facilities, including a floodlit, heated driving range that is one of the busiest in the Lothians. It has served as a vital entry point for thousands of Edinburgh residents into the sport. While it lacks the ancient pedigree of the city\'s private clubs, it has become a staple for regional junior events and corporate golf days. The signature hole requires a precise approach over a pond to a well-guarded green. Melville represents the \"friendly face\" of modern golfefficient, professional, and entirely focused on making the game as enjoyable as possible for everyone.', ''),
('merchantsofedinburgh', 'Merchants of Edinburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/merchantsofedinburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/merchantsofedinburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.918687, -3.232111, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'merchantsofedinburgh', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b95510035ddb09c053211e8997f54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Merchants of Edinburgh Golf Club is a historic and tactical masterpiece situated in the Morningside area of the capital. Originally designed by the famous Ben Sayers in 1907 and later remodelled in 1936 by the legendary James Braid, the course is a model of strategic design on a compact site. Despite its shorter yardage, it is a formidable test of accuracy, featuring steep hills and what is famously one of the few \"square\" greens in the world.\r\n\r\nThe club offers unparalleled views across the city, from the Forth Bridges to Edinburgh Castle and the Pentland Hills. Notable members have historically included many of the city\'s prominent \"merchants\" and professional elite. Because the course is built on a high ridge, the wind is a constant factor that requires a creative, low ball flight. The clubhouse, rebuilt in 2001, is a modern sanctuary that retains the club\'s traditional, welcoming character. For those looking for a historic, high-quality, and physically challenging round of golf in the heart of Edinburgh, \"The Merchants\" is a prestigious and essential stop.', ''),
('millport', 'Millport', 'https://millport.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.759399, -4.939409, 0, 2444, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b345d26ef4c113c0bcce86fc33e14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Millport Golf Club, situated on the charming Isle of Cumbrae, offers a classic moorland experience with some of the most panoramic views in the West of Scotland. Founded in 1888, the course was redesigned in 1913 by the legendary James Braid, who capitalized on the island\'s natural undulations to create a layout that tests every club in the bag. The course sits high above the town, providing a 360-degree vista that includes the peaks of Arran, the mountains of Argyll, and the Ayrshire coast.\r\n\r\nThe club has a fiercely loyal membership and a reputation for providing a warm island welcome. While the yardage is modest by modern standards, Braid\'s strategic bunkering and the ever-present Firth of Clyde breeze ensure that \"mastering\" Millport is no easy feat. Notable tournaments include the Cumbrae Open, which draws players from the mainland for a day of competitive golf and ferry-hop adventure. The turf is firm and springy, typical of the best moorland tracks. For those seeking a tranquil escape, the short ferry crossing from Largs leads to a course where the scenery is as much a part of the score as the putting.', ''),
('milnathortgolfclub', 'Milnathort', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/milnathortgolfclub#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/milnathortgolfclub#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.226078, -3.418561, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'milnathortgolfclub', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000670c738236590bc02c2cb81ff01c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Milnathort Golf Club is a beautiful 9-hole parkland gem in the heart of Kinross-shire. Established in 1910, the course was originally a modest affair before being significantly refined in the 1920s with input from the esteemed James Braid. The layout is characterized by its lush, mature trees and the North Queich burn, which meanders through the property and provides a natural hazard on several of the most challenging holes. Despite being a 9-hole course, it features 18 distinct tee positions that create a varied and engaging full-round experience.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its impeccably fast greens and its family-friendly atmosphere. While it hasn\'t hosted international professional tours, it is a staple for regional Perth & Kinross county events. The course is relatively flat, making it an enjoyable walk for golfers of all ages, but Braid\'s clever positioning of hazards ensures that low-handicappers must still show respect. Notable for its \"hidden\" challenges and excellent conditioning, Milnathort offers a traditional Scottish parkland round in a peaceful, rural setting that feels entirely secluded from the nearby motorway.', ''),
('milngavie', 'Milngavie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/milngavie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/milngavie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.959059, -4.340342, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'milngavie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000028d2fd9c825c11c09df7ff71c2fa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Milngavie Golf Club is a premier moorland course located on the edge of the Mugdock Country Park, just north of Glasgow. Founded in 1895, the course was redesigned in 1923 by the great James Braid and later refined by Willie Fernie. The layout is set against the dramatic backdrop of the Campsie Fells and is characterized by its heather-lined fairways and natural rock outcrops. It is a tactical course where accuracy is far more important than length, as Braid utilized the local terrain to punish the overly aggressive player.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine amateur players who have represented Dunbartonshire at the highest levels. Notable for its \"hidden\" holes and blind shots, Milngavie provides a sense of adventure that is rare in modern parkland golf. The signature 14th hole offers spectacular views across the city toward the distant mountains. The clubhouse is a welcoming sanctuary after a round on the rugged, springy turf. It is a \"pure\" golf club that has maintained its traditional values while ensuring its course remains a high-quality, championship-standard test.', ''),
('minto', 'Minto', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/minto#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/minto#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.947673, -3.189284, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'minto', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009e3f6d54a78309c0af264f594df94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Minto Golf Club is a scenic and challenging parkland course situated on the slopes of Minto Hill in the heart of the Scottish Borders. Established in 1928, the course was designed by the local professional Tom Fernie, who created a layout that rewards accuracy and stamina. The course is characterized by its dramatic elevation changes and panoramic views across the Teviot Valley toward the Cheviot Hills. The mature woodland and vibrant gorse provide a colorful and natural environment for a round of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm Borders hospitality and its remarkably well-conditioned greens. While it lacks the \"famous name\" architects of the coast, the layout is highly respected for its strategic depth; several holes require shots over natural ravines and through narrow corridors of trees. Notable for its \"quiet\" beauty, Minto is a regular venue for Borders Golfers\' Association tournaments. The 12th hole, \"The Pulpit\" offers a view from the tee that is worth the green fee alone. It is a traditional, unpretentious club that offers a tranquil and engaging round of golf in one of the most beautiful corners of the south.', ''),
('moffat', 'Moffat', 'https://www.moffatgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.moffatgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.328152, -3.460673, 0, 2448, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a033695375af0bc0fa0e7ee200aa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Moffat Golf Club is a rugged and atmospheric moorland course that offers a truly unique \"highland\" experience in the Southern Uplands. Founded in 1884, the course was redesigned in 1904 by the legendary Ben Sayers, who utilized the steep hillsides to create a layout that is both physically and mentally demanding. The course sits 800 feet above sea level, providing spectacular views over the Annan Valley and the historic spa town of Moffat.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its \"volcanic\" greenssmall, plateau surfaces that require surgical precision with the short irons. Notable for its lack of artificial bunkers, the course relies on the natural terrain, heather, and wind to defend its par. It is a place where local knowledge is essential, as the slopes can turn a good drive into a difficult lie. The club has a rich social history and was a favorite of the Victorian elite who visited the town for its mineral springs. For those who enjoy the \"raw\" side of the game, Moffat provides a spirited and historic round of golf in a wild, stunning landscape.', ''),
('monifieth', 'Monifieth - Medal', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.485781, -2.797341, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'monifieth', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000059147651f46006c0540262122e3e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Medal Course at Monifieth Links is a titan of Angus golf and a frequent Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship. This traditional links land has a history of golf dating back to at least 1639. The course was originally designed by Old Tom Morris and later refined by James Braid, creating a layout that is both historic and uncompromising. It is famously the place where Tom Watson played his first-ever round of links golf before going on to win the Open at nearby Carnoustie in 1975.\r\n\r\nThe course is characterized by its deep bunkers, firm fairways, and the railway line that runs parallel to the early holes. Notable for its difficulty when the wind blows off the Tay Estuary, the Medal Course requires a wide variety of shot-making. It has hosted every major amateur championship in Scotland and remains a favorite for low-handicappers seeking a pure links test. The turf is of the highest quality, and the sense of history is palpable from the first tee to the final green. Monifieth Medal is an essential stop for any serious golfer visiting the Dundee area.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/km4AgpynF18?si=J5ynCGz-4LmZZZYq'),
('monifiethashludie', 'Monifieth - Ashludie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/monifieth#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.485781, -2.797341, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'monifieth', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000059147651f46006c0540262122e3e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Ashludie Course is the Medal\'s shorter, quirkier, and arguably more fun younger sibling at Monifieth Links. While it measures just over 5,000 yards, it is no \"pushover\"; the small, undulating greens and tight fairways require a high degree of precision and a sharp short game. It was designed to provide a more accessible alternative to the championship course, but it has become a favorite in its own right for those looking for a fast, engaging round of links golf.\r\n\r\nThe Ashludie is often used for junior development and senior tournaments, but it also serves as a tactical warm-up for those heading to the Medal. It shares the same sandy, free-draining soil that makes Monifieth a year-round destination. Notable for its many par-threes and narrow corridors through the gorse, the course rewards the \"thinking\" golfer over the long hitter. It is a beautifully maintained track that offers all the traditional links challenges on a more compact scale. For many visitors, a day at Monifieth isn\'t complete without \"taking on the Ashludie\" after lunch.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZTUJzwSMtbo?si=moQFs5MMMAGYn18p'),
('montrosegolflinks', 'Montrose - 1562', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.709265, -2.462915, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'montrosegolflinks', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000006b9f8ec70cb403c046990d32c95a4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Montrose Golf Links is the fifth oldest golf course in the world, with the game having been played on this site since 1562. The \"Medal\" course was originally laid out by Willie Park Jr. and later refined by James Braid, creating a masterpiece of traditional links design. It is unique for its \"T-shaped\" routing, which ensures that the wind affects the golfer from every possible angle during the round. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and remains one of the most respected links in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its proximity to the North Sea, with several holes hugging the cliff edge. This beauty comes with a challenge, as coastal erosion is a constant battle for the club. Notable members have included legends of the local community and figures from Scotland\'s early golfing history. The 1562 course is a sanctuary of deep bunkers, natural dunes, and fast-running turf. To play here is to walk in the footsteps of over four centuries of golfers, offering a historic and spiritually moving connection to the origins of the game.', ''),
('montrosegolflinksbroomfield', 'Montrose - Broomfield', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/montrosegolflinks#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.709265, -2.462915, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'montrosegolflinks', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006b9f8ec70cb403c046990d32c95a4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Broomfield Course at Montrose offers a flatter, more open links experience that is the perfect complement to its historic 1562 neighbor. Originally used as a practice ground for the local militia, the land was developed into a full 18-hole course to meet the growing demand for golf in the town. While it lacks the dramatic elevation changes of the Medal course, it features the same firm, sandy turf and fast greens that characterize the best Scottish links.\r\n\r\nBroomfield is particularly popular with families, beginners, and those looking for a walking-friendly round that still provides an authentic links challenge. The wind remains the primary defender of par, and the gorse-lined fairways require accuracy off the tee. It is a municipal-style course in spirit, offering a high-quality playing surface at a very accessible price. Notable for its friendly, relaxed atmosphere, Broomfield ensures that the vast links land of Montrose remains a playground for everyone, from the casual visitor to the scratch amateur looking for a quick, competitive game.', ''),
('moray', 'Moray - Old', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/moray/visitor_home.php', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/moray/visitor_home.php', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.719109, -3.315948, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'moray', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000093e4b9be0f870ac030a182c30bdc4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Old Course at Moray Golf Club in Lossiemouth is a legendary links designed in 1889 by the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" Old Tom Morris. It is a pure, traditional layout that starts and finishes within the town, much like the Old Course at St Andrews. The course is famous for its deep, revetted bunkers, gorse-lined fairways, and its signature finishing hole-a par-four that requires an approach over a steep bank to a green overlooked by the magnificent clubhouse.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has hosted many of the game\'s greats, including Sir Henry Cotton, who reportedly loved the challenge of the Moray turf. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and regularly hosts the Scottish Amateur Championship. One of its most unique features is the proximity to the RAF Lossiemouth airbase; the sight and sound of fighter jets soaring overhead provides a dramatic and modern contrast to the ancient links. Moray Old is a masterclass in classic design, offering a rugged, honest, and intensely atmospheric round of golf.', ''),
('moraynew', 'Moray - New', 'https://www.moraygolf.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.719109, -3.315948, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'moray', 3, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000093e4b9be0f870ac030a182c30bdc4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The New Course at Moray Golf Club is far from a secondary consideration; it is a championship-standard links in its own right. Designed by the legendary Henry Cotton and opened in 1970, it offers a distinct contrast to the Old Tom Morris layout next door. While the Old Course is wide and grand, Cotton\'s \"New\" is tighter, more intricate, and arguably more punishing for the wayward driver. It winds through the dense gorse of the Lossiemouth dunes, requiring a strategic \"iron-off-the-tee\" approach on several holes.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its par-threes, which are often cited as some of the most difficult in the North East, especially when the wind whips off the Moray Firth. Notable for its impeccably fast greens, the New Course frequently hosts the Scottish Ladies\' Championship and regional pro-ams. It shares the same dramatic backdrop of RAF Lossiemouth, where the roar of Typhoon jets provides a modern soundtrack to a very traditional links challenge. For many members, the New is the preferred \"daily\" test because of its relentless demand for accuracy and its beautifully secluded atmosphere within the gorse.', ''),
('mortonhall', 'Mortonhall', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/mortonhall#/course/1', 'https://www.howdidido.com/Directory/OpenCompetitions/3007', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.911577, -3.209648, 0, 0, '', '', '', 3007, 'mortonhall', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000dd5f3dee5bad09c095641d8eaef44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While many of Edinburgh\'s famous courses cling to the coastline, Mortonhall Golf Club offers a refined, inland escape just four miles from the city center. Founded in 1892, it holds the prestigious title of the oldest course in the City of Edinburgh over which golf is still played. The land itself is steeped in history; once part of the St Clair of Rosslyn estate granted by Robert the Bruce, it eventually became the private parkland of the Trotter family. The course captures this grand estate feeling, weaving through mature silver birches, firs, and pines that frame views of the Pentland Hills and the Firth of Forth.\r\n\r\nThe course\'s architectural pedigree is a \"who\'s who\" of Scottish golf. Its early layout was shaped by the legendary Willie Park Jr. and J.H. Taylor, before being further refined by the great James Braid. In the 1970s, Fred W. Hawtree added modern flourishes, ensuring the par-72 championship layout remained a robust test for contemporary equipment. This evolution has made Mortonhall a frequent host for elite competitions, including the Scottish Amateur Stroke Play Championship and various national youth tournaments.\r\n\r\nBeyond its competitive record, Mortonhall is famous for its storied membership and unique connections. During the First World War, it is believed that the celebrated war poets Siegfried Sassoon and Wilfred Owen played rounds here while recovering at nearby Craiglockhart. Today, the club is known for its vibrant social atmosphere and its historic clubhouse, which provides a stately finish to one of Scotland\'s most meticulously conditioned parkland experiences.', ''),
('muckhart', 'Muckhart', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/muckhart#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/muckhart#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.182322, -3.603839, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'muckhart', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000000e65a88aa9d40cc0b0abc95356174c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Muckhart Golf Club is a spectacular 27-hole complex situated at the base of the Ochil Hills in Perthshire. The three 9-hole loopsCowden, Arndean, and Naemooreach offer a distinct character, ranging from parkland to moorland. Established in 1908, the club has grown from a modest village course into a premier destination for regional golf. The elevation changes are dramatic, providing views across the Forth Valley to the Wallace Monument and Stirling Castle.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its junior development program, which is widely regarded as one of the best in Scotland. Notable members have included several Scottish internationalists who honed their skills on these tricky, sloping fairways. Because of the three loops, Muckhart offers incredible variety; you can play a different combination of 18 holes every time you visit. The greens are notoriously undulating and fast, requiring a delicate touch. It is a vibrant, modern club that maintains a deep respect for its Highland roots, offering some of the most scenic and engaging golf in the central belt.', ''),
('muirfield', 'Muirfield', 'https://www.muirfield.org.uk/visitors-new/', 'https://www.muirfield.org.uk/visitors-new/', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'tue,thu', 'eastlothian', '', 56.045209, -2.822420, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000004e9cdcef509406c0103e9468c9054c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Muirfield, the home of The Honourable Company of Edinburgh Golfers, is arguably the most respected and strategically perfect links in the world. Founded in 1744 (though moving to Muirfield in 1891), the course was designed by Old Tom Morris and later refined by Harry Colt. It is unique for its \"two-loop\" design: the front nine travels clockwise around the perimeter, while the back nine travels counter-clockwise in the center. This ensures the wind attacks the golfer from every possible direction.\r\n\r\nMuirfield has hosted The Open Championship 16 times, with winners including Jack Nicklaus (who named his own course, Muirfield Village, after it), Gary Player, Tom Watson, and Phil Mickelson. It is a sanctuary of deep, revetted bunkers and perfectly manicured fairways. The clubhouse is a cathedral of golfing history, and the legendary \"Muirfield Lunch\" is as famous as the course itself. While it is a private and traditional club, a round at Muirfield is the ultimate bucket-list item for any serious golfer-a masterclass in design, history, and the highest standards of the game.', ''),
('Muirkirk', 'Muirkirk', 'https://www.muirkirk.org.uk/muirkirk-community-information/muirkirk-golf-club/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.514072, -4.066944, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000059a7caf78c4410c008e57d1ccdc14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Muirkirk Golf Club is a rugged and scenic 9-hole moorland course tucked away in the East Ayrshire hills. Established in 1905, the course is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense, offering a raw and authentic Scottish golfing experience. The layout is set on the slopes of the Garpel Valley, providing panoramic views of the surrounding countryside. It is a natural course where the fairways follow the undulating contours of the land, and the hazards are largely provided by the heather, gorse, and the local burn.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, unpretentious welcome and its resilient community spirit. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the clever routing makes excellent use of the natural slopes to create a variety of challenging shots. It is a place where the elementsspecifically the winddictate the strategy of the day. The course is famously well-maintained by a small, dedicated team, and the greens are often surprisingly true for such an exposed site. For those seeking a quiet, traditional round of golf away from the crowds, Muirkirk offers a peaceful and honest connection to the game\'s roots.', ''),
('muiroford', 'Muir of Ord', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/muiroford#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/muiroford#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.511010, -4.459639, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'muiroford', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000055dd239babd611c0e8f692c668c14c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Muir of Ord Golf Club is a fascinating Highland gem that spans the main Inverness-to-Wick railway line. Originally established as a 9-hole course in 1875, it was extended to 18 holes in the 1920s with input from the legendary James Braid. The course is a moorland-heathland hybrid, characterized by its springy turf, purple heather, and silver birch trees. The railway line comes into play on several holes, requiring a steady nerve as the Highland trains rumble past just yards from the fairway.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has hosted the Northern Open and various North District championships. One of its most distinctive features is the 18th hole, a par-three that finishes right in front of the clubhouse, providing a dramatic end to the round. The greens at Muir of Ord are famously true and are often cited as some of the best in the Highlands. It is a friendly, community-focused club that offers a historic Braid layout with a unique industrial twist. For any golfer touring the North, the \"Muir\" provides a charming and strategically rewarding challenge.', ''),
('murcarlinks', 'Murcar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/murcarlinks', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/murcarlinks#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.206424, -2.068247, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'murcarlinks', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000a1664815c58b00c0048e041a6c9a4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Murcar Links is a world-class championship course that sits adjacent to the famous Royal Aberdeen links. Established in 1909 and designed by Archie Simpson, it was later refined by James Braid. It is a rugged, spectacular links characterized by massive sand dunes, deep hollows, and blind shots. Murcar has a significant tournament pedigree, having hosted the European Tour\'s Saltire Energy Paul Lawrie Matchplay and the Scottish Challenge Tour.\r\n\r\nThe course is famously difficult, especially when the North Sea gales blow across the exposed dunes. Notable members have included many of the North East\'s top amateurs. The signature 7th hole, \"Serpentine\" is a par-four that requires a nerve-wracking drive between towering dunes to a narrowing fairway. Murcar is a \"pure\" links in every sense-raw, uncompromising, and visually stunning. It offers a more rugged and wild experience than some of its more manicured neighbors, making it a favorite for those who want to experience the true, untamed nature of Scottish coastal golf.', ''),
('murcarstrathabie', 'Murcar - Strabathie', 'https://murcarlinks.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'aberdeen', '', 57.201434, -2.072262, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000cbf27519fe9300c0b726dd96c8994c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Strabathie Course at Murcar is the 9-hole sibling to the championship links, but it should not be underestimated. Originally intended as a training ground for the main course, it has evolved into a high-quality links-parkland hybrid that offers a quicker but still testing round of golf. The layout features many of the same natural hazards as the main course, including deep bunkers and thick gorse, but on a slightly more compact and accessible scale.\r\n\r\nStrabathie is particularly popular with juniors, beginners, and those looking for a fast \"nine\" after work. It is maintained to the same exacting standards as the championship links, ensuring a world-class playing surface throughout the year. While it lacks the international spotlight of the main course, it provides a vital entry point for new golfers in the Aberdeen area. It is a delightful, walking-friendly track that allows players to experience the unique turf and sea breezes of Murcar without the punishing length of the full championship experience.', ''),
('murrayfield', 'Murrayfield', 'https://www.murrayfieldgolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.949961, -3.250521, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.murrayfieldgolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000092b06f2711010ac0dcbc715298f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Murrayfield Golf Club is a prestigious parkland course located in the heart of Edinburgh, offering spectacular views of the city, the Firth of Forth, and the distant mountains of Fife. Established in 1896, the course was significantly improved by the legendary James Braid. Despite its urban location, the course feels remarkably secluded, with its fairways lined by mature trees and lush vegetation. Its most famous feature is the view of Edinburgh Castle from the higher holes on the back nine.\r\n\r\nThe club has a high-society reputation and has counted many prominent Edinburgh families among its members for generations. It is a tactical course where the elevation changes require careful club selection and a steady hand. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and strategic bunkering, Murrayfield is a regular host for the Lothians County Championships. The clubhouse is a hub of traditional elegance, providing a warm welcome in one of the city\'s most affluent suburbs. For those looking for a historic, high-quality round within minutes of the city center, Murrayfield is a premier choice.', ''),
('murrayshall', 'Murrayshall', 'https://www.murrayshall.co.uk/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.419170, -3.368315, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008a027d224ff20ac06fbbd05ca7354c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Murrayshall Course is the flagship championship layout at the Murrayshall Country Estate near Perth. Designed by Hamilton J. Stutt and opened in 1981, it is a grand, expansive parkland course that winds through the estate\'s 365 acres of mature woodland and rolling hills. It is a \"resort\" course of the highest order, featuring wide fairways, large bunkers, and impeccably maintained greens. The course offers spectacular views across the Vale of Strathmore toward the Grampian Mountains.\r\n\r\nThe course has a strong tournament history, having hosted several PGA Scotland events and the Scottish Schoolboys\' Championship. Notable for its \"American-style\" scale, Murrayshall requires power off the tee but rewards precision on the large, undulating greens. The signature 18th hole, finishing in front of the historic 17th-century manor house, provides a dramatic and luxurious conclusion to the round. It is a polished, professional, and intensely scenic course that offers a five-star golfing experience in the heart of Scotland\'s most beautiful parkland.', ''),
('musselburgh', 'Musselburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/musselburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/musselburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.929934, -3.054277, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'musselburgh', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000062669fc7286f08c020b8ca1308f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Musselburgh Golf Club, also known as Monktonhall, is a prestigious parkland course designed in 1938 by the legendary James Braid. While it is often confused with the historic Old Links nearby, Monktonhall is a distinct championship-standard layout that serves as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship. Braid utilized the naturally undulating terrain to create a course that emphasizes strategic positioning, featuring his signature deep bunkers and well-protected greens.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine amateur players, often featuring in the top tiers of the Lothians County circuit. Famous visitors have included numerous pros during Open qualifying weeks who have praised the course for its consistency and \"fair\" but firm challenge. The layout is beautifully tree-lined, providing a sense of seclusion despite its proximity to Edinburgh. The signature 18th hole, requiring a precise approach to a green nestled near the clubhouse, is one of the finest finishing holes in the region. It remains a \"pure\" golf club that prioritizes the quality of its turf and the traditions of the game.', ''),
('musselburgholdlinks', 'Musselburgh Old Links', 'http://www.musselburgholdlinks.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.947085, -3.034735, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006536c824234708c01ec4ce143af94b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Old Links at Musselburgh is one of the most significant sites in the history of the sport. It is the oldest continuously played golf course in the world, with records dating back to 1672. Situated inside the Musselburgh Racecourse, it served as a venue for The Open Championship six times between 1874 and 1889. It is the birthplace of the standard 4.25-inch golf hole, which was first established here using a piece of drainage pipe as a hole-cutter.\r\n\r\nThe course is a living museum, and many visitors choose to rent hickory clubs to play the nine holes as the early pioneers did. Notable Open winners here include Mungo Park and Jamie Anderson. The layout is flat and exposed, with historic hazards like \"The Grave\" bunker providing a stern test of nerves. Playing Musselburgh Old is a spiritual experience for any golfer, offering a direct connection to the 19th-century \"Great Triumvirate\" era. It is an unpretentious, historic treasure that remains a mandatory pilgrimage for anyone interested in the roots of Scottish golf.', ''),
('muthill', 'Muthill', 'https://muthillgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.330678, -3.844746, 0, 2466, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001f6adb300ac20ec0dbc01da8532a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Muthill Golf Club is a charming and scenic 9-hole parkland course located near Crieff in Perthshire. Established in 1946, the course is perched on a hillside, offering panoramic views over the Strathearn Valley toward the Grampian Mountains. While it is a shorter course, Muthill is notorious for its sloping fairways and small, tricky greens that require a delicate touch and precise club selection. It is a \"mountain-lite\" experience that tests your fitness as much as your finesse.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, community-focused atmosphere and is a favorite for local society outings. Although it doesn\'t host professional tours, it has a reputation for being one of the best-maintained 9-hole tracks in the county. The 2nd hole, \"The Whinny\" is a highlight, requiring a blind shot over a ridge to a hidden green. Muthill represents the quintessential Scottish village clubfriendly, unpretentious, and deeply integrated into the local landscape. For those looking for a quick, scenic, and technically demanding round, it offers high-value golf in a truly tranquil setting.', ''),
('nairndunbargolf', 'Nairn Dunbar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/nairndunbargolf#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/nairndunbargolf#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.586222, -3.859008, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'nairndunbargolf', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000da0418963fdf0ec00d198f5209cb4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Nairn Dunbar Golf Links is a heavyweight of Northern golf, frequently overshadowed by its neighbor but a formidable championship test in its own right. Founded in 1899, the course has evolved into a rugged links-heathland hybrid. In recent years, a major restoration project returned the course to its \"pure\" links roots by removing gorse to reveal natural sand dunes. It has a high tournament pedigree, having hosted the British Amateur Championship and the Scottish Boys\' Championship.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its brutal opening stretch and its remarkably fast, true greens. Notable members have included several Walker Cup players, and the club prides itself on a competitive yet welcoming environment. Unlike some traditional links, Nairn Dunbar offers a variety of holes that wind through both dunes and more sheltered, tree-lined areas. The wind off the Moray Firth is a constant defender of par, making a low-ball flight essential. It is a polished, professional club that offers a world-class links experience with a slightly more modern and relaxed feel than the ancient coastal giants.', ''),
('nairngc', 'Nairn', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/nairngc#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/nairngc#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.585206, -3.909676, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'nairngc', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe6100000010100000016a6ef3504470fc024b6bb07e8ca4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Nairn Golf Club is a global masterpiece and a jewel of the Moray Firth. Established in 1887 and refined by legends including Old Tom Morris, James Braid, and Ben Sayers, it is a pure links of the highest order. It is one of the few courses in the world where the sea is visible from every single hole. Nairn has an immense international reputation, famously hosting the 1999 Walker Cup and the 2012 Curtis Cup, where the quality of its firm, fast fairways drew worldwide acclaim.\r\n\r\nThe course is renowned for having some of the best greens in Scotland-lightning-fast and remarkably smooth. Famous members and visitors include royalty and major champions who seek out its technical complexity. The first seven holes hug the shoreline so closely that a stray hook will literally land in the North Sea. It is a traditional, aristocratic club where the standards of play and etiquette are held in the highest regard. To play Nairn is to experience the absolute pinnacle of links architecture-a beautiful, unforgiving, and spiritually uplifting journey across the Highland coastline.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('nairngc9', 'Nairn - Cameron', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/nairngc#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.585206, -3.909676, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'nairngc', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000016a6ef3504470fc024b6bb07e8ca4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Cameron Course at Nairn is the 9-hole sibling to the famous championship links, offering a high-quality \"warm-up\" or a more relaxed alternative for families and beginners. Despite its shorter length, the Cameron is maintained by the same world-class greenkeeping team as the main course, ensuring the same fast-running turf and immaculate greens. It consists of a mix of par-threes and par-fours that provide a tactical challenge without the intimidating length of the championship track.\r\n\r\nThe Cameron is particularly popular for junior development and for members looking for a quick \"nine\" after work. It offers a wonderful view of the Moray Firth and allows players to sample the unique Nairn microclimate and turf. While it lacks the international accolades of its elder brother, it is a vital part of the club\'s identity, providing an accessible gateway to one of the world\'s great golfing venues. It is the perfect example of how a premier club can cater to all levels of the game while maintaining an uncompromising standard of quality.', ''),
('newbattle', 'Newbattle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newbattle#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newbattle#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.885138, -3.061040, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'newbattle', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000094fb1d8a027d08c03239b5334cf14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Newbattle Golf Club is a hidden parkland gem located on the outskirts of Dalkeith, just south of Edinburgh. Founded in 1933, the course is set within the historic estate of Newbattle Abbey, and its fairways wind through ancient woodland and along the banks of the River Esk. The layout is characterized by its lush, mature trees and several significant elevation changes, providing a peaceful and sheltered environment that feels miles away from the nearby capital.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history in the Lothians and is known for its competitive amateur teams. The course is a tactical test where the river comes into play on several of the most challenging holes, requiring a steady nerve on the approach shots. Notable for its fast, sloping greens, Newbattle is a regular host for regional county events. The 13th hole, \"The Maiden\" is a scenic par-three that requires a precise shot over a valley. It is a friendly, traditional club that offers a refined and atmospheric round of golf, where the history of the abbey estate adds a touch of grandeur to every shot.', ''),
('newburghonythan', 'Newburgh on Ythan', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newburghonythan#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newburghonythan#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.313270, -2.001010, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'newburghonythan', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000004da3c9c5189806c002bc051214974b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Newburgh on Ythan Golf Club is a spectacular links course situated at the mouth of the River Ythan in Aberdeenshire. Originally a 9-hole course founded in 1888, it was extended to a full 18 holes in the 1990s. The course is a \"tale of two halves\": the front nine offers a more modern, hilly links feel with expansive views, while the back nine winds through massive, ancient dunes that are among the most dramatic in the country. It sits adjacent to the Forvie National Nature Reserve, making it a haven for wildlife.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its demanding elevation changes and the blind shots required through the dunes. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the natural routing is a masterclass in links design. Notable for its firm turf and punishing rough, Newburgh is a favorite for those who enjoy the \"raw\" and unadulterated side of links golf. The views from the 4th tee, overlooking the estuary and the North Sea, are worth the green fee alone. It is a welcoming, community-led club that offers a wild and memorable challenge that rivals the more famous links of the North East.', ''),
('newcastleton', 'Newcastleton', 'https://www.visitnewcastleton.com/things-to-do-in-newcastleton/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.180300, -2.824266, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004da3c9c5189806c002bc051214974b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Newcastleton Golf Club is a rugged and charming 9-hole moorland course situated in the heart of the Liddesdale Valley in the Scottish Borders. Established in 1910, the course is perched on the slopes of Holm Hill, offering panoramic views over the village and the surrounding border hills. It is a \"natural\" course in the truest sense, where the fairways follow the steep contours of the land and the primary hazards are provided by the heather, gorse, and the local topography.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility, maintained with immense pride by a small group of local volunteers. While it doesn\'t host professional tournaments, it is a beloved part of the local community and offers a peaceful, solitary experience for visiting golfers. The layout requires a good level of fitness due to the steep climbs, but the reward is a series of exhilarating elevated tee shots. Newcastleton is a place where you can escape the pressures of modern life and experience the game as it was played over a century ago-simple, beautiful, and deeply connected to the landscape.', ''),
('NewCumnock', 'New Cumnock', 'https://members.tripod.com/bob_newcumnock/golf/welcomex.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.406216, -4.197561, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000038dc476e4dca10c0548ec9e2feb34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'New Cumnock Golf Club is a scenic 9-hole parkland course located at the foot of the Afton Hills in East Ayrshire. Founded in 1902, the course is situated on the banks of the River Nith, which provides a natural and often treacherous hazard on several holes. The layout is relatively flat, making it an enjoyable walk, but the narrow fairways and well-placed trees require a high degree of accuracy. The backdrop of the hills and the tranquility of the river make it one of the most peaceful spots in the county.\r\n\r\nThe club is a pillar of the local community and is known for its warm, unpretentious hospitality. While it lacks a \"famous name\" architect, the course is highly regarded for its conditioning and the quality of its greens. It is a regular venue for Ayrshire regional amateur events and has a reputation for being a \"friendly\" course that still offers a stiff challenge to low-handicappers. The signature 5th hole, playing right along the riverbank, is a highlight of the round. New Cumnock offers an authentic and high-value taste of Ayrshire parkland golf in a stunning rural setting.', ''),
('NewGalloway', 'New Galloway', 'https://newgallowaygolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.070316, -4.140687, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b0e3bf40109010c059315c1d00894b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'New Galloway Golf Club is a captivating 9-hole gem located in the heart of the Galloway Forest Park. Established in 1902, the course is a rugged moorland layout that offers some of the most stunning views in the South West. It is famously undulatingmany locals joke that there isn\'t a flat lie on the entire propertyforcing players to adapt their stance and shot-making constantly. The course is surrounded by ancient woodland and is a haven for red kites and deer.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of Scotland\'s smallest royal burgh and is known for its incredibly warm, inclusive atmosphere. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the routing is a masterpiece of natural design, utilizing rocky outcrops and heather as organic hazards. The signature 6th hole, \"The Lairig\" requires a nerve-wracking shot over a valley to a green perched on a hillside. New Galloway offers a peaceful, \"slow-golf\" experience where the beauty of the landscape is just as important as the score on the card.', ''),
('newmachar', 'Newmachar - Hawkshill', 'https://newmachar.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.242754, -2.199690, 7850, 0, '', '', 'newmachar', 1357, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b7b41a12f79801c0917c2590129f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'The Hawkshill Course at Newmachar is a titan of North East golf. Designed by the renowned Dave Thomas and opened in 1990, it was built to be a premier championship test. It is a dense, tree-lined parkland course that demands total precision; many holes are framed by tight corridors of Scots pine and silver birch. Hawkshill has a serious tournament pedigree, having hosted the European Challenge Tour and various prestigious PGA Scotland events.\r\n\r\nThe course is notorious for its difficult par-fives and its slick, subtly undulating greens. Notable members include several of Aberdeen\'s top professional and amateur players who use Hawkshill\'s unforgiving layout to hone their skills. The signature 18th hole, with water guarding the green right in front of the clubhouse, has seen many dramatic finishes in professional competition. It is a polished, professional, and physically demanding course that offers a \"Tour-level\" experience for those who think they can handle the heat.', ''),
('newmacharswailend', 'Newmachar - Swailend', 'https://newmachar.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'clubv1', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.243891, -2.197891, 7852, 0, '', '', 'newmachar', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c36169e0479501c0f564fed1379f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Swailend Course is Newmachar\'s slightly more \"user-friendly\" sibling, but it is a formidable challenge in its own right. Also designed by Dave Thomas and opened in 1997, Swailend is more open than the Hawkshill, allowing for a bit more freedom off the tee. However, the greens are arguably more difficult, featuring significant tiers and slopes that require a master\'s touch with the putter. It offers a more rolling, traditional parkland feel compared to the dense forest of its neighbor.\r\n\r\nSwailend is a favorite for local club medals and society outings because it offers a high-quality playing surface without being quite as \"penal\" as the Hawkshill. It is meticulously maintained by the same world-class greenkeeping team, ensuring year-round conditioning that is among the best in the region. Notable for its scenic views over the Aberdeenshire countryside, Swailend provides a perfect balance of challenge and enjoyment, making the Newmachar complex one of the most comprehensive golfing destinations in the country.', ''),
('newtonmore', 'Newtonmore', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newtonmore#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/newtonmore#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.065147, -4.119599, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'newtonmore', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000087890629787a10c05d37a5bc56884c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Newtonmore Golf Club is a spectacular Highland course that sits on the banks of the River Spey within the Cairngorms National Park. Established in 1893, the course is mostly flata rarity for a Highland trackmaking it an easy and enjoyable walk. It is a parkland-moorland hybrid that follows the meandering path of the river, which acts as a beautiful but deadly hazard on several holes. The mountain scenery surrounding the course is truly breathtaking.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its connection to the local community and its long-standing friendly rivalry with neighboring Kingussie. While it lacks a \"famous\" architect, the layout is highly regarded for its logical flow and the trueness of its greens. It has hosted various North District events and is a regular favorite for visiting golfers touring the Spey Valley. The 18th hole, \"The Home Hole\" requires an approach over a burn to a green overlooked by the traditional clubhouse. Newtonmore offers a tranquil and authentically Highland round of golf that emphasizes the natural beauty of the Spey.', ''),
('newtonstewart', 'Newton Stewart', 'https://www.newtonstewartgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.newtonstewartgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.964662, -4.473873, 0, 2477, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000063d4b5f63ee511c0d3d85e0b7a7b4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Newton Stewart Golf Club is a scenic parkland beauty located on the edge of the Galloway Hills. Founded in 1896, the course offers panoramic views of the \"Cairnsmore of Fleet\" and the surrounding countryside. The layout is characterized by its varied terrain, ranging from gentle slopes to significant elevation changes that require a creative approach. It is a beautifully wooded course, with mature trees framing the fairways and providing shelter from the Dumfries and Galloway breezes.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm hospitality and its well-conditioned greens. While it may not have hosted the professional majors, it is a stalwart of the South of Scotland amateur circuit. The signature 9th hole, \"The Monument\" is a highlight, played toward the local memorial landmark on the hill. Newton Stewart is a traditional, unpretentious club that rewards accuracy over power. It is an ideal stop for those exploring the South West, offering a peaceful and engaging round of golf in a setting that captures the lush, green essence of the Galloway landscape.', ''),
('niddrycastle', 'Niddry Castle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/niddrycastle#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/niddrycastle#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.953689, -3.448189, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'niddrycastle', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000626a4b1de4950bc008c72c7b12fa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Niddry Castle Golf Club is a unique parkland course located in Winchburgh, West Lothian. The course is built around the historic 15th-century Niddry Castle, where Mary, Queen of Scots once sought refuge. Opened in the 1980s, the layout was designed to incorporate the castle as a dramatic focal point. It is a challenging course characterized by its significant elevation changes, water hazards, and tight, tree-lined fairways that require careful strategic planning.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vibrant community hub and is known for its friendly, modern atmosphere. While it is a relatively young course, it has matured quickly and is a regular host for West Lothian County events. The signature hole is the par-three over the pond toward the castle, providing one of the most iconic views in Lothian golf. Niddry Castle is a \"thinking man\'s\" course where the driver is often left in the bag in favor of accuracy. It offers a memorable blend of historic grandeur and modern parkland challenges, making it a standout in the central belt.', ''),
('northberwick', 'North Berwick', 'https://www.northberwickgolfclub.com/tee_booking_request_form', 'https://www.northberwickgolfclub.com/tee_booking_request_form', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,sun', 'eastlothian', '', 56.056085, -2.727239, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe6100000010100000086014bae62d105c0e96514cb2d074c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The West Links at North Berwick is a global icon and a masterpiece of traditional links design. Founded in 1832, the course is a pure links that starts and finishes in the heart of the town. It is home to some of the most copied holes in the world, most notably the 15th, \"Redan\" which has been replicated on nearly every continent. Unlike many modern courses, North Berwick is famous for its quirks-including stone walls that must be lofted over and ancient, deep-seated bunkers.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted every major amateur event and served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship for decades. Notable members have included legends of the game and icons of the Scottish establishment. The 13th hole, \"Pit\" requires an approach over a historic stone wall to a green nestled on the other side. North Berwick is a \"fun\" links in the truest sense; it is a creative, unpredictable, and spiritually uplifting journey along the Firth of Forth. To play here is to experience the very soul of Scottish golf architecture.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/QED9z5mRzEI?si=JGvKhbP-xGLN85Gb'),
('northinch', 'North Inch', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/northinch#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/northinch#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.404420, -3.432090, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'northinch', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000db6d179aeb740bc096ecd808c4334c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The North Inch Golf Course in Perth is a site of immense historical significance, with records of golf being played on this common land as far back as 1512. It is one of the oldest places in the world where the game has been enjoyed. The current layout was designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris, providing a classic parkland-links hybrid experience right in the center of Perth. Because it is built on a flood plain of the River Tay, the turf is remarkably springy and fast-draining.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal course, the North Inch has been a training ground for generations of Perthshire golfers. It is an open, walking-friendly course that offers views of the historic Scone Palace across the river. While it is a public facility, it is maintained to a high standard and has hosted numerous regional amateur championships. The 18th hole, playing back toward the city\'s historic spires, is a classic finish. North Inch represents the \"people\'s game\"historic, accessible, and deeply rooted in the origins of the sport.', ''),
('oatridge', 'Oatridge and Binny', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oatridge#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oatridge#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.941530, -3.523580, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'oatridge', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000aab706b64a300cc0f819170e84f84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Oatridge and Binny Golf Club, located near Broxburn, is a unique and high-quality parkland course that serves as a teaching facility for the Scottish Agricultural College. Opened in the late 1990s, the 9-hole course (played twice for an 18-hole round) was designed by Graeme Webster. It is characterized by its rolling terrain, clever water hazards, and its commitment to ecological diversity. The course is famously well-manicured, as it serves as a \"living classroom\" for greenkeeping students.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its relaxed and welcoming atmosphere, making it a favorite for beginners and those looking for a stress-free round. While it lacks the ancient history of other Lothian clubs, it offers a modern, scientifically-managed playing surface that is often superior to many private tracks. The signature hole requires a precise shot over a large pond to a well-guarded green. Oatridge and Binny is a testament to the future of the gamesustainable, accessible, and professionally maintainedoffering a high-value and educational round of golf.', ''),
('oldmeldrum', 'Old Meldrum', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oldmeldrum#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oldmeldrum#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.335236, -2.319573, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'oldmeldrum', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000147afd497c8e02c08f386403e9aa4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Old Meldrum Golf Club is a historic Aberdeenshire parkland course with roots dating back to 1885. The course sits on a high ridge overlooking the \"Garioch\" countryside, providing expansive views of the peak of Bennachie. The layout is a varied and engaging mix of holes, featuring significant elevation changes and mature woodland. It is a tactical course where the prevailing wind is a major factor, often requiring a creative, low-ball flight.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its competitive amateur teams. While it hasn\'t hosted the professional majors, it is a regular venue for Aberdeenshire County events and is highly regarded for its consistent conditioning. The signature 13th hole, \"The Binn\" offers a dramatic tee shot and views that are among the best in the county. Old Meldrum is a traditional, friendly club that provides an authentic \"North East\" parkland experience, where the quality of the greens and the warmth of the clubhouse are the primary attractions.', ''),
('oldranfurly', 'Old Ranfurly', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oldranfurly#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/oldranfurly#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.852670, -4.579640, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'oldranfurly', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000053d0ed258d5112c0e223624a24ed4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Old Ranfurly Golf Club, located in the village of Bridge of Weir, is a classic Scottish moorland course that has been a staple of Renfrewshire golf since 1898. The course was originally laid out by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie and later refined by the legendary James Braid. It is perched on a high plateau, providing some of the most spectacular panoramic views in the West of Scotland, stretching from the Ben Lomond peaks to the Gleniffer Braes.\r\n\r\nThe club is renowned for its firm, springy turf and its challenging, fast-running greens. Notable members over the years have included various titans of Glasgow\'s industrial past, and the club remains a prestigious venue for the Renfrewshire County Championships. The layout is notoriously tricky when the wind blows across the exposed moorland, requiring a creative array of \"bump and run\" shots. It is a traditional, aristocratic club that maintains an impeccably conditioned course, offering a \"pure\" golfing experience that feels far removed from the urban bustle of nearby Glasgow.', ''),
('Orkney', 'Orkney', 'https://orkneygolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 58.987713, -2.982313, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000357c0bebc6db07c0c26a2c616d7e4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Orkney Golf Club, situated just outside Kirkwall, is a rugged and atmospheric parkland-moorland hybrid that offers a truly unique island experience. Established in 1889, the course is one of the most northerly in the UK. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and its exposure to the fierce Atlantic winds, which act as the course\'s primary defender. From the higher holes, players are treated to cinematic views of the northern islands and the historic St. Magnus Cathedral.\r\n\r\nThe club is the heart of the Orcadian golfing community and is known for its incredibly warm and unpretentious welcome. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the natural routing is genius, using the undulating landscape to create several blind shots and challenging carries over heather and gorse. The greens are remarkably true despite the harsh climate. Notable for its \"Midnight Sun\" tournaments held during the summer solstice, Orkney Golf Club offers a raw, elemental connection to the game that every adventurous golfer should experience at least once.', ''),
('paisley', 'Paisley', 'https://paisley.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.812064, -4.444690, 0, 0, '', '', 'paisley', 164, '', 0, 0, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000d66ebbd05cc711c0252191b6f1e74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Paisley Golf Club, often referred to locally as \"Bushes\" is a magnificent moorland course located within the Gleniffer Braes Country Park. Founded in 1894, the course was redesigned in the 1950s by Philip Mackenzie Ross, the architect responsible for the post-war restoration of the Ailsa course at Turnberry. The layout is perched high above the town of Paisley, offering views that, on a clear day, extend all the way to the southern Highlands and the Cumbrae Isles.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong competitive pedigree and has hosted the Scottish Youths\' Championship and numerous PGA Scotland regional events. It is characterized by its narrow fairways, thick heather, and strategic bunkering that punishes the wayward driver. Notable for its lush conditioning and challenging par-threes, Paisley is a \"thinking man\'s\" course where local knowledge is key to navigating the rolling terrain. It is a friendly, vibrant club that provides a high-quality, championship-standard test of golf in a stunningly scenic and elevated setting.', ''),
('Palacerigg', 'Palacerigg', 'http://palacerigggolfclub.co.uk/index.html', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.936273, -3.942072, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000089d1730b5d890fc05c902dcbd7f74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Palacerigg Golf Course is a rugged and rewarding moorland layout located within the Palacerigg Country Park in Cumbernauld. Designed by the three-time Open Champion Henry Cotton and opened in the 1970s, the course was built to provide a high-quality public-sector challenge. Cotton utilized the natural peat and heather of the moorland to create a course that feels wild and isolated. It is a relatively long course that requires both power and precision, especially on the exposed holes where the wind is a major factor.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal facility, Palacerigg has a reputation for being one of the best-value rounds in the central belt. The layout features several significant water hazards and tight fairways lined with young woodland. While it doesn\'t host the professional majors, it is a staple of the Lanarkshire amateur circuit and is praised for its year-round playability. The signature holes along the ridge offer spectacular views over the Forth Valley. It is an honest, unpretentious course that represents the \"Cotton\" philosophy of accessible but rigorous golf, providing a peaceful escape for the region\'s golfers.', ''),
('panmure', 'Panmure', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/panmure#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/panmure#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.490343, -2.772167, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'panmure', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe61000000101000000496760e4652d06c04969368fc33e4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Panmure Golf Club is a world-class links located in Carnoustie, often cited as one of the most underrated courses in Scotland. Established in 1845, the current layout at Barry Links was designed with input from Old Tom Morris and James Braid. It is famously the place where Ben Hogan spent two weeks practicing before his legendary 1953 Open victory at Carnoustie. Hogan suggested several changes to the 6th hole, which the club adopted and still carries his name today.\r\n\r\nThe course is a \"hidden\" links, with many holes winding through dunes and corridors of Scots pine, giving it a unique character compared to the more exposed local tracks. It has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship and is a regular host for the Scottish Amateur Championship. The greens are notoriously firm and fast, and the bunkering is among the most strategic in the country. Panmure is a refined, private club that offers a pure and historic links experience, where the ghost of Hogan seems to linger on every fairway.', ''),
('peebles', 'Peebles', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/peebles#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/peebles#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.656294, -3.208581, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'peebles', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002b89ec832cab09c0d047197101d44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Peebles Golf Club is a spectacular parkland-moorland hybrid situated on the slopes of the Southern Uplands. Established in 1892, the course was significantly redesigned by Harry Colt, one of the giants of golf architecture. The layout is characterized by its dramatic elevation changes and panoramic views over the Tweed Valley. It is a tactical course where the driver is often best left in the bag in favor of accuracy, as the fairways are lined with mature trees and punishing gorse.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local Borders community and has a history of producing elite amateur talent, including former Scottish champions. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and its warm, welcoming clubhouse, Peebles is a regular host for the Borders Golfers\' Association championships. The signature 13th hole, \"The Neidpath\" offers a scenic view that is worth the walk alone. It is a traditional, well-maintained club that provides a refined and physically engaging round of golf, capturing the lush, rolling beauty of the Scottish Borders.', ''),
('peterculter', 'Peterculter', 'https://www.petercultergolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.petercultergolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.084650, -2.268677, 0, 2508, '', '', '', 1038, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c77f8120402602c09fcdaacfd58a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Peterculter Golf Club is a beautiful parkland course located on the banks of the River Dee, just south of Aberdeen. Established in 1989, the course was designed by Graeme Webster to take full advantage of the dramatic riverside setting and the surrounding valley. The layout is a \"tale of two halves\": the lower holes follow the meandering path of the Dee, while the upper holes climb the hillside, offering expansive views across the Aberdeenshire countryside.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its modern, friendly atmosphere and its commitment to high-quality conditioning. While it is a relatively young course, it has quickly established itself as a premier venue for regional PGA Scotland events. The signature par-three 13th, played from a high tee to a green nestled near the riverbank, is one of the most photographed holes in the region. Peterculter is a \"resort-style\" club in terms of its amenities but remains a community hub at heart. It offers a scenic, varied, and technically demanding round of golf that highlights the natural beauty of the Dee Valley.', ''),
('peterhead', 'Peterhead - Old', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/peterhead', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/peterhead#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.518085, -1.801164, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'peterhead', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000080b8ab5791d1fcbf2ac6f99b50c24c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Peterhead Old Course is a rugged and authentic links that holds the distinction of being the 18th oldest golf club in the world. Established in 1841 and refined over the years by various hands, the course is situated among some of the most dramatic sand dunes in the North East. It is a pure links experience where the wind off the North Sea is a constant and shifting factor. The layout is characterized by its narrow fairways, deep bunkers, and fast-running turf.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has hosted various regional amateur championships, known for being a \"true\" test of links skill. Notable for its isolation and its connection to the local fishing community, Peterhead Old offers a sense of total immersion in the elements. The signature holes through the massive dunes require both power and a delicate touch on the firm greens. It is a traditional, unpretentious club that prides itself on maintaining the integrity of its ancient links land. For those who enjoy the raw, unadulterated side of the game, Peterhead Old is an essential and historic stop.', ''),
('peterheadnew', 'Peterhead - New', 'https://www.peterheadgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.518054, -1.800660, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'peterhead', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000001d7233dc80cffcbfefc7ed974fc24c40, 'links', 'No', 'The New Course at Peterhead is the club\'s delightful 9-hole sibling, offering a quicker but equally scenic links experience. While it is shorter than the Old Course, it shares the same high-quality turf and stunning coastal views. The layout is designed to be more accessible for juniors, beginners, and those looking for a fast \"nine\" after work, but it still features several tricky holes that require respect.\r\n\r\nThe New Course is maintained by the same dedicated greenkeeping team as the Old, ensuring that the playing surfaces are of a championship standard. It serves as a vital entry point for the local community into the sport and offers a more relaxed environment for casual play. Despite its name, the course has a mature feel and blends seamlessly into the rugged coastal landscape. It is the perfect example of how a historic club can provide a comprehensive golfing experience, catering to all levels of ability while honoring its links heritage.', ''),
('piperdamnewcourse', 'Piperdam', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/piperdamnewcourse#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/piperdamnewcourse#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'angus', 'Yes', 56.499462, -3.136828, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'piperdamnewcourse', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ad6a4947391809c021cced5eee3f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Piperdam Golf & Leisure Resort is home to the Newtyle course, a premier 18-hole parkland layout situated near Dundee. Opened in the mid-1990s, the course was designed to be a centerpiece for the surrounding holiday resort. It is a modern \"target-style\" course characterized by its significant water hazardsincluding a massive central lochand its large, undulating greens. The layout is relatively flat but is punctuated by strategic bunkering and mature woodland.\r\n\r\nThe resort has a high-energy, modern atmosphere and is a favorite for corporate golf days and society outings. While it may not have the ancient history of the nearby links, it offers a professional-standard parkland experience with world-class facilities. Notable for its impeccable conditioning and its \"amen corner\" around the loch, Piperdam is a regular host for regional PGA Scotland pro-ams. The signature 18th hole, requiring a carry over water to a green overlooked by the lodge balcony, provides a theatrical finish. It is a high-value destination for those seeking a modern and visually stunning round of golf in the heart of Angus.', ''),
('pitlochry', 'Pitlochry', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pitlochry', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pitlochry#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.712522, -3.744936, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'pitlochry', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008ae76c01a1f50dc01bd7bfeb335b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Pitlochry Golf Club is frequently described as the \"Switzerland of Scotland.\" Established in 1908 and refined by the legendary Willie Fernie, this 18-hole course offers a unique \"inland links\" experience perched on the edge of the Highlands. It is famous for its steep elevation changes, particularly the climb on the opening holes which is rewarded with breathtaking views over the Tummel Valley. The course is characterized by springy, moorland turf and fairways lined with heather and silver birch.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant, modern atmosphere and has hosted the Highland Open since 1921, drawing competitors from across the globe. Notable for its friendly \"pro-shop\" culture, the course is often cited as one of the best-conditioned in Perthshire. The signature 4th hole, \"The Brae\" requires a heroic drive up a steep incline, while the closing stretch offers a series of thrilling downhill holes where the ball seems to travel forever in the crisp Highland air. It is a scenic masterpiece that proves you don\'t need a coastline to have a world-class golfing adventure.', ''),
('pitreavie', 'Pitreavie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pitreavie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pitreavie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.054392, -3.425851, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'pitreavie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004dc0af9124680bc0ff942a51f6064c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Pitreavie Golf Club in Dunfermline is a site of immense architectural interest, having been designed by the legendary Dr. Alister MacKenzie in 1922. MacKenzie, who later designed Augusta National and Cypress Point, brought his revolutionary \"multi-tier\" green design to the Fife countryside. The course is a polished parkland layout that features many of MacKenzie\'s signature trademarks, including strategic bunkering that uses shadows to deceive the eye and greens that require masterclass-level reading.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong competitive history and frequently hosts the Fife County Championships. It is a regular stop for serious students of golf architecture who come to see the early work of the \"Calamity Jane\" designer. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and its lush, mature tree-line, Pitreavie offers a refined and intellectual round of golf. The 18th hole provides a dramatic finish in front of the traditional clubhouse, requiring a precise approach to one of the most complex greens on the course. It is a high-quality, historic track that offers a taste of \"Master\'s\" style strategy in the heart of Scotland.', ''),
('plgc', 'Paul Lawrie Golf Centre', 'https://paullawriecentre.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.111208, -2.168659, 0, 2499, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009468c9e3695901c0db8651103c8e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Paul Lawrie Golf Centre, located just outside Aberdeen, is a state-of-the-art facility founded by the 1999 Open Champion, Paul Lawrie. The 9-hole course at the centre is designed to Lawrie\'s exacting standards, providing a world-class \"short course\" experience that emphasizes iron play and short-game precision. Despite its shorter yardage, the course features tour-quality greens and strategic bunkering, making it a favorite practice ground for local professionals and elite amateurs.\r\n\r\nThe centre is a hub for the Paul Lawrie Foundation, which has been instrumental in developing the next generation of Scottish golfers. It features a world-class driving range and teaching academy, reflecting Lawrie\'s commitment to the growth of the game. While it is a public-access facility, the conditioning is of a championship standard. For those looking to sharpen their skills or enjoy a quick, high-quality round, the centre provides a modern and professional environment. It is a testament to Lawrie\'s legacy, offering an accessible gateway to elite-level training and play.', ''),
('Polkemmet', 'Polkemmet', 'https://www.westlothianleisure.com/venues/polkemmet-golf-course-driving-range/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.865964, -3.721057, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003c6a4c88b9c40dc0b5c189e8d7ee4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Polkemmet Golf Course is a delightful 9-hole parkland layout situated within the Polkemmet Country Park in West Lothian. Developed on the site of a former private estate, the course was opened in the 1980s and has matured into a scenic and testing facility. The layout winds through mature woodland and features several significant water hazards, including the River Almond which comes into play on the early holes.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal facility, Polkemmet is known for its inclusive and friendly atmosphere. While it is a shorter course, it requires a high degree of accuracy off the tee to navigate the narrow, tree-lined corridors. It is a favorite for local families and seniors, offering a tranquil and affordable \"stroll in the park\" that still provides enough challenge to keep experienced players on their toes. Notable for its excellent drainage and year-round playability, Polkemmet represents the best of community golfoffering a peaceful escape and high-quality turf in a historic estate setting.', ''),
('pollok', 'Pollok', 'https://pollok.intelligentgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.822755, -4.308673, 0, 0, '', 'https://pollok.intelligentgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000001a260c6143c11c06ccf2c0950e94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Pollok Golf Club is one of Glasgow\'s most prestigious and refined parkland sanctuaries. Established in 1892 and redesigned in the 1920s by Dr. Alister MacKenzie, the course is situated within the magnificent Pollok Country Park. It is a \"pure\" golf club in the traditional sense, maintaining an atmosphere of quiet elegance and impeccable standards. The layout is characterized by its lush, manicured fairways and greens that are widely considered to be among the finest in the West of Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe club has a storied history and has hosted many prestigious amateur and professional events, including the Scottish Amateur Championship. Notable members have historically included leaders of Glasgow\'s merchant and professional classes. The course is beautifully secluded, with the White Cart Water meandering through the property and providing a natural hazard on several holes. Pollok is a sanctuary of traditional values, offering an uncompromising parkland test where the quality of the conditioning is matched only by the warmth of the clubhouse hospitality.', ''),
('PortBannatyne', 'Port Bannatyne', 'https://portbannatynegolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.858327, -5.085636, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e770adf6b05714c00c23bda8dded4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Port Bannatyne Golf Club, located on the Isle of Bute, is a unique and quirky 13-hole course that offers a truly memorable island experience. Founded in 1912, the course is perched on a hillside overlooking the Kyles of Bute and Loch Striven. Because it consists of 13 holes, a \"full\" round involves playing five of the holes twice, creating a varied and interesting 18-hole loop. The layout is a rugged moorland hybrid, featuring natural hazards like gorse and heather.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its incredible panoramic views and its relaxed, \"honesty box\" atmosphere. While it lacks a famous architect, the course is a masterclass in utilizing the natural landscape to create a fun and engaging challenge. It is a favorite for visitors who enjoy the \"undiscovered\" side of Scottish golf. Notable for its springy turf and small, tricky greens, Port Bannatyne rewards the creative player over the long hitter. It is a quintessential island clubpeaceful, scenic, and deeply traditionaloffering a round of golf that feels like a step back in time.', ''),
('portglasgow', 'Port Glasgow', 'https://www.portglasgowgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.portglasgowgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.924562, -4.663735, 0, 2518, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009dd7d825aaa712c0eb8f300c58f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Port Glasgow Golf Club is a rugged and rewarding moorland course situated high above the Firth of Clyde. Established in 1895, the course offers some of the most dramatic views in the region, stretching from the Erskine Bridge to the Argyll hills. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and its exposure to the sea breezes, which act as a constant defender of par. It is a tactical course where local knowledge is key to navigating the various blind shots and sloping fairways.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its unpretentious and welcoming membership. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, it is a stalwart of the Renfrewshire amateur circuit and has produced many fine local champions. The greens are remarkably true and often quite fast in the summer months. Notable for its peaceful, elevated setting, Port Glasgow provides a spirited and challenging round of golf that captures the rugged beauty of the Clyde coastline. It is an honest, traditional club that offers high-value golf with a view that is hard to beat.', ''),
('portlethen', 'Portlethen', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/portlethen#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/portlethen#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.066385, -2.144768, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'portlethen', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000020f0c207c2801c0f4f8bd4d7f884c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Portlethen Golf Club, located just south of Aberdeen, is a modern and highly-regarded parkland course that was founded in 1981. Designed by Donald Steel, one of the most respected modern golf architects, the course was built to provide a championship-standard test for the growing local community. The layout features wide, rolling fairways, strategic water hazards, and large, subtly undulating greens. It is a course that rewards both length and precision, making it a fair but formidable test.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant and professional atmosphere, frequently hosting regional PGA Scotland events and the Aberdeenshire County Championships. Notable for its impeccable conditioning and its \"Tour-standard\" practice facilities, Portlethen has quickly become one of the premier inland courses in the North East. The signature 15th hole, a par-three played over water to a well-guarded green, is a highlight of the round. It is a polished, high-gloss club that offers a modern and engaging golfing experience, perfect for those who appreciate contemporary design and world-class maintenance.', ''),
('portmahomack', 'Portmahomack', 'https://portmahomack.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 57.835400, -3.823559, 0, 2521, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000999cda19a6960ec0098a1f63eeea4c40, 'links', 'No', 'Portmahomack (Tarbat) Golf Club is a beautiful 9-hole links course situated on the shores of the Dornoch Firth. Established in 1909, the course is a traditional, natural links that offers spectacular sea views from every hole. The layout is characterized by its firm, sandy turf, deep bunkers, and gorse-lined fairways. It is a \"pure\" links experience where the wind off the Moray Firth is a constant and shifting factor, requiring a creative array of low-ball flight shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility and is maintained with immense pride by the local community. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the routing is genius, utilizing the natural dunes and shoreline to create a varied and engaging challenge. It is a favorite for those traveling the North Coast 500 who want to experience an authentic Highland links without the crowds. Notable for its peace and seclusion, Portmahomack offers a raw, elemental connection to the origins of the game. It is a hidden gem that rewards the adventurous golfer with a truly memorable and scenic round.', ''),
('Portobello', 'Portobello', 'https://www.edinburghleisure.co.uk/venues/portobello-golf-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.946560, -3.113256, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000309b00c3f2e708c0d3d9c9e028f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Portobello Golf Course is a charming 9-hole parkland course located in the heart of Edinburgh\'s seaside suburb. As a municipal facility, it has served as a vital nursery for the game in the capital for over a century. The course is relatively short and flat, making it an ideal venue for beginners, juniors, and seniors. Despite its modest length, the layout features several well-placed trees and small greens that require a steady hand and precise club selection.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its relaxed and inclusive atmosphere, providing an accessible gateway for the local community into the sport. While it doesn\'t boast a famous architect or championship pedigree, it is a beloved local asset that is maintained to a good standard. Its proximity to the city center and the Portobello beach makes it a popular choice for a quick \"nine\" after work or on the weekend. Portobello represents the \"social\" side of the gameunpretentious, affordable, and focused on the enjoyment of the sport in a friendly and urban setting.', ''),
('portpatrick', 'Portpatrick Dunskey', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/portpatrick#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/portpatrick#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.846540, -5.114910, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'portpatrick', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f6ee8ff7aa7514c0bf60376c5b6c4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Portpatrick Dunskey Golf Club is a spectacular cliff-top links-style course located on the rugged coast of Wigtownshire. Established in 1903, the course was refined in the early 20th century by the legendary James Braid, who took full advantage of the dramatic elevation changes. The layout is perched high above the Irish Sea, and on a clear day, the views stretch all the way to the coast of Northern Ireland. It is a scenic masterpiece where the sound of the waves crashing against the cliffs is a constant companion.\r\n\r\nThe club has a friendly and welcoming atmosphere, frequently hosting regional South of Scotland amateur championships. Notable for its firm, springy turf and its exposure to the \"Portpatrick breeze\" the course requires a creative array of shots. The signature holes along the cliff edge are among the most photographed in the country, requiring nerve as well as skill to avoid the rocky drops. It is a traditional club that offers a wild, exhilarating, and visually stunning round of golf, making it a \"must-play\" for anyone touring the South West.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('PortpatrickDinvinCourse', 'Portpatrick Dinvin Course', 'https://www.portpatrickgolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 54.846544, -5.114903, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000062d9cc21a97514c00150c58d5b6c4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Dinvin Course at Portpatrick is the club\'s delightful 9-hole sibling, providing a shorter but equally scenic challenge. While it measures significantly less than the main Dunskey course, it is no simple \"warm-up.\" The Dinvin is a par-three course that features small, tricky greens and several significant natural hazards. It is maintained to the same high standards as the main track, offering manicured playing surfaces and the same stunning coastal views.\r\n\r\nThe course is particularly popular with families, beginners, and those looking to sharpen their short game. It serves as a vital training ground for the club\'s thriving junior section. Many members use the Dinvin for a quick evening round when time is short, enjoying the peaceful environment and the brisk sea air. It is a perfect example of how a premier club can offer a comprehensive experience for all skill levels, ensuring that the enjoyment of the game remains accessible to everyone in a world-class setting.', ''),
('powfoot', 'Powfoot', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/powfoot#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/powfoot#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.978430, -3.343080, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'powfoot', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000001f4b1fbaa0be0ac070b6b9313d7d4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Powfoot Golf Club is one of the most respected \"hidden\" links in Scotland, situated on the shores of the Solway Firth. Founded in 1903, the course was designed by the esteemed James Braid, who created a unique hybrid layoutpart links and part parkland. The course begins and ends on traditional links land, while the middle section moves inland to more sheltered, tree-lined fairways. This variety ensures that no two holes at Powfoot feel the same.\r\n\r\nThe club has a significant tournament history, frequently serving as an Open Championship Regional Qualifying venue and hosting the Scottish Mid-Amateur Championship. Notable for its deep bunkers and fast-running fairways, Powfoot is a \"pure\" golfer\'s course that rewards strategic thinking. The views across the Solway toward the Lake District mountains provide a magnificent backdrop. It is a friendly, traditional club that prides itself on its impeccable conditioning, offering a challenging and historic round of golf that punches well above its weight on the national stage.', ''),
('prestonfield', 'Prestonfield', 'https://www.prestonfieldgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 54.846608, -5.114807, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.prestonfieldgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000516859f78f7514c01844a4a65d6c4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Prestonfield Golf Club is a magnificent parkland sanctuary located in the shadow of Arthur\'s Seat in Edinburgh. Established in 1920, the course was designed by the legendary James Braid, who utilized the naturally rolling terrain of the historic Prestonfield Estate to create a tactical masterpiece. Despite being located just a mile from the city center, the course feels remarkably secluded, with its fairways lined by mature trees and a diverse range of local wildlife.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced many fine amateur players, including former Scottish internationals. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and its challenging par-threes, Prestonfield is a regular host for the Lothians County Championships. The signature view of the \"Lion\'s Head\" on Arthur\'s Seat from the fairway is one of the most iconic sights in Scottish golf. It is a traditional and welcoming club that offers a refined, historic, and physically engaging round, representing the very best of urban parkland design.', ''),
('prestwick', 'Prestwick', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/prestwick#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/prestwick#/course/1', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.501550, -4.614830, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'prestwick', 1, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000001366dafe957512c087a757ca32c04b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Prestwick Golf Club is a hallowed site and the birthplace of The Open Championship, having hosted the very first tournament in 1860. Originally designed by Old Tom Morris, who also served as the club\'s first keeper of the green, the course is a raw and uncompromising links. It is famous for its eccentricities, including massive dunes, blind shots, and the \"Alps\" hole-the oldest and most famous blind approach in the world. Prestwick hosted The Open 24 times before the tournament grew too large for the site.\r\n\r\nThe club remains one of the most traditional and exclusive in the world, yet it offers a warm welcome to visitors looking to walk in the footsteps of the giants of the game. Notable members have historically included the pioneers of modern golf. To play Prestwick is to experience a time capsule of 19th-century links architecture; it is creative, unpredictable, and spiritually moving. Every hole tells a story, from the \"Cardinal\" bunker to the \"Sea Heugh.\" It is a mandatory pilgrimage for any serious student of the game\'s history.', ''),
('prestwickstcuthbert', 'Prestwick St Cuthbert', 'https://prestwickstcuthbert.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://prestwickstcuthbert.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.490131, -4.595566, 0, 0, '', '', 'prestwickstcuthbert', 1303, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002a70b20ddc6112c0bde0d39cbcbe4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Prestwick St Cuthbert is a premier parkland course that offers a distinct contrast to the famous links neighbors in the town. Established in 1899, the current layout was designed in the 1960s by the respected architect P.M. Ross. The course is characterized by its lush, manicured fairways and its over 1,000 mature trees, creating a parkland oasis in the heart of the \"Ayrshire Golf Coast.\" It is a relatively flat course, making it an easy and enjoyable walk for all ages.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant and competitive membership, frequently hosting the Ayrshire Strokeplay Championship and regional PGA Scotland events. Notable for its impeccably true greens and strategic bunkering, St Cuthbert is a \"fair\" test that rewards accuracy and a sharp short game. The traditional clubhouse is known for its excellent hospitality and views over the 18th green. It is a friendly, professional club that provides a high-quality, polished parkland experience, making it a favorite for those looking for a break from the punishing coastal gorse.', ''),
('prestwickstnicholas', 'Prestwick St Nicholas', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/prestwickstnicholas', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'clubv1', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.493280, -4.620230, 0, 0, '', '', '', 175, 'prestwickstnicholas', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000009feb7921d7b12c0ace28dcc23bf4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Prestwick St Nicholas is a historic and scenic links course located just south of the famous Open venue. Founded in 1851, the club is the 26th oldest in the world, and Old Tom Morris himself was a founding member and a frequent competitor on these fairways. The course is a traditional \"out and back\" links that hugs the shoreline of the Firth of Clyde, offering stunning views across to the Isle of Arran and the Ailsa Craig.\r\n\r\nThe layout is characterized by its firm turf, deep bunkers, and the \"Quarry\" holes that provide a unique and challenging middle section. Notable for its fast greens and its exposure to the sea breezes, St Nicholas is a regular host for the Scottish Ladies\' Championship and national senior events. It is a refined and welcoming club that maintains a strong sense of its 19th-century heritage. For those seeking an authentic links experience with deep historical ties to the founders of the professional game, St Nicholas is an essential and rewarding stop.', ''),
('pumpherston', 'Pumpherston', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pumpherston#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/pumpherston#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.907779, -3.482343, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'pumpherston', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e0a293a5d6db0bc06f7f2e1a32f44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Pumpherston Golf Club in West Lothian is a modern parkland success story. Originally a 9-hole course, it was extended to 18 holes in 2002 with a design that emphasizes ecological sustainability and \"target\" golf. The course is built on reclaimed land and features several significant water hazards and large, undulating greens. It has quickly built a reputation for its year-round conditioning and its commitment to providing a championship-standard test for the local community.\r\n\r\nThe club is a hub for the West Lothian amateur circuit and is known for its friendly, forward-thinking atmosphere. While it lacks the ancient history of its neighbors, Pumpherston offers a polished and technically demanding round that rewards precision over raw power. The signature holes around the central lakes require a steady nerve and careful club selection. It is a popular venue for society outings and corporate days, offering a modern, professional, and visually stunning golfing experience in the heart of the central belt.', ''),
('ralston', 'Ralston', 'https://www.howdidido.com/Directory/OpenCompetitions/686', 'https://www.howdidido.com/Directory/OpenCompetitions/686', 'No', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.841401, -4.382062, 0, 0, 'opens not showing', '', 'ralston', 686, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006b2dcc423b8711c02de92807b3eb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ralston Golf Club, located on the border of Glasgow and Paisley, is a prestigious parkland masterpiece designed by the legendary James Braid. Established in 1913, the course is a model of Braid\'s strategic design, featuring his signature bunkering and greens that require a sharp eye. The layout is characterized by its lush, mature tree-line and its impeccably manicured fairways, offering a sense of total seclusion despite its proximity to the city.\r\n\r\nThe club has a proud history and has produced many fine amateur players who have represented Renfrewshire at the highest levels. Notable for its fast, sloping greens and its challenging par-fours, Ralston is a regular host for regional county championships. The clubhouse is a traditional sanctuary that reflects the club\'s long-standing status as one of the premier inland venues in the West of Scotland. It is a refined, \"gentleman\'s\" club that prioritizes the quality of its turf and the traditions of the game, offering an uncompromising parkland test.', ''),
('ranfurlycastle', 'Ranfurly Castle', 'https://www.ranfurlycastlegolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.854748, -4.586411, 0, 2535, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000020f0c207c5812c02429e96168ed4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ranfurly Castle Golf Club, located in the village of Bridge of Weir, is a premier moorland course that dates back to 1889. The current layout was designed by James Braid and is widely considered one of the finest moorland tracks in the country. Perched on a high ridge, the course offers panoramic views stretching to the mountains of the Southern Highlands. The layout is a hybrid of moorland and heathland, featuring natural hazards like heather, gorse, and rocky outcrops.\r\n\r\nThe club has a significant tournament pedigree, having hosted the Scottish Girls\' Championship and various PGA Scotland events. Notable members have included legends of the local industry, and the club remains one of the most prestigious in Renfrewshire. The greens are famously fast and true, while Braid\'s strategic routing ensures a varied and engaging challenge. The ruins of the 15th-century Ranfurly Castle overlook the course, providing a dramatic historical backdrop. It is a traditional, high-quality club that offers a \"pure\" and scenic golfing experience in a stunningly elevated setting.', ''),
('rathoparkgolfclub', 'Ratho Park', 'https://www.rathoparkgolfclub.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.921878, -3.360074, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.rathoparkgolfclub.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000861e317a6ee10ac071732a1900f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ratho Park Golf Club is a stunning parkland sanctuary located on the outskirts of Edinburgh. Established in 1928, the course was designed by the legendary James Braid and is uniquely situated within the confines of an ancient estate wall. This stone boundary creates an atmosphere of total seclusion, shielding the golfer from the outside world. The layout is characterized by its magnificent mature treesincluding massive oaks and beechesthat frame the fairways and require precise shot-shaping.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious reputation and is a regular host for the Lothians County Championships. Notable for its impeccable conditioning and its remarkably flat terrain, it is an easy walk but a difficult \"score\" as Braid\'s strategic bunkering and small, fast greens demand respect. The Union Canal runs alongside several holes, adding to the tranquil environment. It is a traditional, refined club that prides itself on maintaining the highest standards of etiquette and turf quality, offering a polished and historic parkland experience that remains one of the most popular in the capital.', ''),
('ravelston', 'Ravelston', '', '', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.954616, -3.257703, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1525, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000011a62897c60f0ac0821e6adb30fa4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ravelston Golf Club is a hidden gem tucked away in the heart of Edinburgh\'s affluent West End. Founded in 1912, the course was designed by the esteemed James Braid and is a model of clever routing on a compact site. This 9-hole course (played twice for an 18-hole round) is perched on the slopes of Corstorphine Hill, offering spectacular views over the city toward the Firth of Forth and the mountains of Fife.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its privacy and its incredibly friendly, tight-knit membership. Notable for its lush, wooded environment and significant elevation changes, Ravelston provides a tactical challenge where accuracy is far more important than length. The small, well-protected greens are famously tricky to read. While it may not host international championships, it is a cherished part of the Edinburgh golfing scene, offering a peaceful and scenic escape just minutes from the city center. It is the perfect destination for the \"thinking\" golfer who appreciates historic design and a quiet, aristocratic atmosphere.', ''),
('Reay', 'Reay', 'https://reaygolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.560044, -3.778585, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d13fc1c58a3a0ec017299485af474d40, 'links', 'No', 'Reay Golf Club holds the distinction of being the most northerly 18-hole links course on the British mainland. Located in Caithness, the course was designed by James Braid and offers a raw, unadulterated links experience on the edge of the Atlantic. The layout is a natural masterpiece, winding through dunes and over springy, sandy turf. On a clear day, the views across the Pentland Firth toward the Orkney Isles are simply breathtaking.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its incredibly warm and unpretentious welcome. Despite its remote location, the course is maintained to a high standard, featuring lightning-fast greens and deep, natural bunkers. Notable for its exposure to the fierce northern winds, Reay requires a masterclass in low-ball flight and \"bump and run\" shots. It is an \"honesty box\" facility that represents the very soul of Scottish golfwild, scenic, and deeply connected to the elements. For those traveling the North Coast 500, a round at Reay is an essential and spiritually uplifting experience.', ''),
('renfrew', 'Renfrew', 'https://renfrew.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://renfrew.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'No', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 57.812810, -4.043130, 0, 0, 'opens not live', '', 'renfrew', 181, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000eae74d452a2c10c04eee77280ae84c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Renfrew Golf Club is a premier parkland course that has long been considered one of the finest in the West of Scotland. Established in 1894 and moved to its current site in 1970, the course was designed by the respected Commander John D. Harris. It is an 18-hole championship layout characterized by its wide, lush fairways and towering avenues of trees. It has a high tournament pedigree, having served as an Open Championship Regional Qualifying venue for many years.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted numerous prestigious events, including the Scottish Amateur Championship and several international matches. Notable for its strategic water hazards and its large, undulating greens, Renfrew is a \"fair\" but formidable test that rewards the bold player. The signature finishing hole, requiring a carry over water to a green overlooked by the modern clubhouse, is a highlight of the round. It is a professional and welcoming club that offers a polished, high-gloss parkland experience, making it a favorite for competitive golfers and society outings across the central belt.', ''),
('roodlea', 'Roodlea Golf Center', 'http://www.roodleagolf.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.444070, -4.546508, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006d020ccb9f2f12c03f912749d7b84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Roodlea Golf Centre, located in Ayr, is a modern and highly accessible 9-hole parkland course that caters to the local community and visitors to the Ayrshire coast. Opened in the early 2000s, the facility was designed to provide a relaxed and inclusive environment for golfers of all levels. The course is relatively flat and features wide fairways, making it an ideal venue for beginners and juniors, while well-placed bunkers and water hazards provide enough of a challenge for more experienced players.\r\n\r\nThe centre is particularly renowned for its excellent practice facilities, including a floodlit driving range and a professional coaching academy. While it lacks the ancient history of the nearby Open venues, it has become a vital hub for the \"Golf for All\" movement in Ayrshire. Notable for its friendly atmosphere and year-round playability, Roodlea offers a high-value and stress-free round of golf. It is the perfect place for a quick \"nine\" after work or a family outing, representing the modern, welcoming face of the sport in one of Scotland\'s most famous golfing regions.', ''),
('rosehearty', 'Rosehearty', 'https://www.roseheartygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.695882, -2.108308, 0, 2547, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004e29af95d0dd00c002f04fa912d94c40, 'links', 'No', 'Rosehearty Golf Club is a rugged and charming 9-hole links course located on the Aberdeenshire coast. Established in 1882, it is one of the oldest clubs in the region and offers a traditional, natural links experience. The course is situated right on the water\'s edge, featuring firm, sandy turf and natural hazards like rocky outcrops and thick gorse. The views across the North Sea are spectacular, especially during the long summer evenings when the light seems to linger on the fairways.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility and is maintained with immense pride by a small group of local volunteers. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the routing is a testament to the simplicity of early links design, utilizing the natural contours of the shoreline to create a variety of challenging shots. Notable for its exposure to the North Sea gales, Rosehearty is a place where you must play \"with the wind\" rather than against it. It is a peaceful, unpretentious, and historic gem that offers a pure and affordable connection to the origins of the game.', ''),
('rothes', 'Rothes', 'https://www.rothesgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.rothesgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.523347, -3.221809, 0, 2549, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000efaa07cc43c609c0d8bad408fdc24c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Rothes Golf Club is a scenic 9-hole parkland course situated in the heart of the Spey Valley, famous for its whisky distilleries. Opened in 1990, the course was designed by Euan McIntosh and is built on a hillside overlooking the village and the River Spey. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and its lush, well-manicured fairways. The surrounding woodland and the backdrop of the Ben Aigan hills provide a tranquil and stunning setting for a round of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vital part of the local community and is known for its warm, Speyside hospitality. While it is a relatively young course, it has quickly established a reputation for its conditioning and the trueness of its greens. It is a regular favorite for visitors touring the local distilleries who want to balance their whisky tasting with a high-quality round of golf. Notable for its challenging par-threes and its peaceful, secluded atmosphere, Rothes offers a \"boutique\" golfing experience that captures the natural beauty and the relaxed spirit of the Highlands.', ''),
('Rothesay', 'Rothesay', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 55.832541, -5.049908, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002e3c2f151b3314c021ca17b490ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Rothesay Golf Club, located on the Isle of Bute, is a spectacular 18-hole moorland course designed by the legendary James Braid in 1908. Perched on a high plateau, the course offers some of the most panoramic views in the world of golf, stretching across the Firth of Clyde to the peaks of Arran and the mountains of Argyll. It is a rugged, undulating layout that requires both physical stamina and tactical finesse to navigate.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has produced several notable amateur players. Braid\'s genius is evident in the way he utilized the natural rocky outcrops and heather as organic hazards. Notable for its firm, springy turf and its challenging, fast-running greens, Rothesay is a \"pure\" moorland test. The signature holes along the ridge offer views that are worth the ferry trip alone. It is a friendly and traditional island club that offers a wild, exhilarating, and visually stunning round of golf, representing one of Braid\'s most scenic achievements.', ''),
('roukenglen', 'Rouken Glen', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/roukenglen#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.795876, -4.324529, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'roukenglen', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000126a8654514c11c0edd5c743dfe54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Rouken Glen Golf Course is a historic and popular municipal parkland course located within the award-winning Rouken Glen Park in Giffnock, just south of Glasgow. Established in the early 20th century, the course has long been a favorite for city golfers looking for an accessible and well-maintained round. The layout is characterized by its mature trees, rolling fairways, and several significant elevation changes that provide a varied and engaging challenge.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal facility, Rouken Glen has a reputation for its inclusive and welcoming atmosphere. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, it has served as a vital training ground for generations of Glasgow golfers. The course is famously scenic, with the park\'s historic waterfall and woodland providing a beautiful backdrop. Notable for its year-round playability and its friendly clubhouse, Rouken Glen offers high-quality golf at an affordable price. It is a cherished community asset that represents the \"people\'s game\" in a setting of exceptional natural beauty.', ''),
('routenburn', 'Routenburn', 'https://www.routenburngolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.817662, -4.875184, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000000bee073c308013c04a97fe25a9e84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Routenburn Golf Club is a dramatic and scenic 18-hole moorland course situated on the hills high above Largs. Designed by the legendary James Braid and opened in 1914, the course is famous for its panoramic views over the Firth of Clyde to the islands of Cumbrae and Arran. It is a \"mountain-style\" layout characterized by steep climbs and thrilling downhill shots, requiring a high level of fitness and a creative approach to the various blind shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm and friendly membership and its unpretentious, traditional clubhouse. Braid\'s strategic routing ensures that the wind is a constant and shifting factor, making \"low-ball\" flight essential. Notable for its firm, springy turf and its challenging, sloping greens, Routenburn is a \"pure\" moorland test that punishes the wayward driver. The signature views from the higher holes are among the most photographed in Ayrshire. It is a high-value and exhilarating club that offers a unique and scenic golfing adventure on the edge of the West Coast.', ''),
('rowallancastle', 'Rowallan Castle', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/rowallancastle#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/rowallancastle#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.652320, -4.490710, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'rowallancastle', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d847a7ae7cf611c06c43c5387fd34b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Rowallan Castle Golf Club is a modern masterpiece set within a historic 600-acre Ayrshire estate. Designed by the eight-time European Number One and Ryder Cup Captain Colin Montgomerie, the course opened in 2009 and quickly gained a reputation for its tour-quality conditioning. The layout winds through mature woodland with the spectacular backdrop of two castlesone 13th-century and one Victorian. Montgomerie utilized the natural undulations to create a \"modern classic\" featuring cavernous bunkers and large, fast, undulating greens.\r\n\r\nThe course is a tactical challenge that requires power off the tee but extreme finesse on the greens. Notable for its 19th hole (the \"decider\"), the club offers a relaxed country club atmosphere. While a relatively new addition to the Scottish circuit, it has hosted numerous PGA Scotland events and is a favorite for high-profile pro-ams. Former Celtic star Murdo MacLeod is a well-known fan of the course. Rowallan provides a polished, luxury experience where the history of the estate meets contemporary championship design, making it a standout in the \"Home of Golf.\"', ''),
('roxburghe', 'Roxburghe', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/roxburghe#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/roxburghe#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.558350, -2.470770, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'roxburghe', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000dc80cf0f23c403c05ddc460378c74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Roxburghe Golf Club, located near Kelso, is arguably the finest inland course in the Scottish Borders. Designed by the internationally renowned architect Dave Thomas and opened by Nick Faldo and Colin Montgomerie in 1997, it is a grand championship parkland layout. The course is set on the Duke of Roxburghe\'s estate and is characterized by its scale, featuring deep bunkers, sprawling fairways, and the meandering River Teviot.\r\n\r\nThe club has hosted the Scottish Senior Open and remains a premier venue for professional qualifying events. The signature hole is the par-five 14th, \"The Viaduct\" where the tee shot is played from an elevated position toward a green framed by the historic Roxburgh Viaduct. It is a \"big\" course in every sense, rewarding strong driving and bold approach play. With its luxurious clubhouse and estate setting, The Roxburghe offers a world-class, resort-style experience that brings a touch of Gleneagles-style grandeur to the Borders.', ''),
('royalaberdeen', 'Royal Aberdeen', 'https://www.royalaberdeengolf.com/', '', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'No', 57.186261, -2.077226, 0, 0, '', '', '', 191, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000093543aa289e00c098c28366d7974c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Founded in 1780, Royal Aberdeen is the sixth oldest golf club in the world. The Balgownie Links is a legendary championship venue, originally designed by the Simpson brothers and later refined by James Braid. It is widely regarded as having one of the finest front nines in golf, as the holes weave through massive, ancient dunes that offer total protection from the wind. The back nine moves onto higher ground, providing a more traditional, exposed links challenge with panoramic North Sea views.\r\n\r\nThe club hosted the 2014 Scottish Open (won by Justin Rose) and the 2011 Walker Cup. Notable members have historically included the elite of Aberdeen\'s professional classes. The signature 8th hole, \"Shelter\" is a par-three surrounded by ten bunkers. It is a traditional, prestigious club where the standards of etiquette are as high as the quality of the turf. To play Balgownie is to experience the very essence of traditional Scottish links golf-rugged, historic, and strategically brilliant.', ''),
('royalaberdeensilverburn', 'Royal Aberdeen - Silverburn', 'https://www.royalaberdeengolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'aberdeen', '', 57.178504, -2.083118, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e2ab1dc539aa00c0431a1538d9964c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Silverburn Course is the shorter, charming sibling to the Balgownie Links. Originally laid out as a recreational loop, it was redesigned by James Braid and offers a delightful mix of links and parkland characteristics. While it measures significantly less than the championship track, it features nine par-threes that test a golfer\'s iron play and accuracy to the limit. The course is meticulously maintained by the same world-class greenkeeping team as the main links.\r\n\r\nSilverburn is a favorite for members seeking a more relaxed round or for those looking to sharpen their short game. It offers the same dramatic coastal views as its elder brother but with a less penal routing. It is often used for junior development and senior tournaments within the club. Despite its \"secondary\" status, Silverburn is a high-quality track in its own right, providing a peaceful and scenic alternative to the brutal challenge of the Balgownie dunes. It is the perfect \"warm-up\" for a day at one of the world\'s most historic clubs.', ''),
('royaldornoch', 'Royal Dornoch', 'https://booking.royaldornoch.com/', 'https://booking.royaldornoch.com/', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sun', 'highlands', 'No', 57.887779, -4.013768, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000e1ecd632190e10c0ad8905bea2f14c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Royal Dornoch\'s Championship Course is frequently ranked among the top five golf courses in the world. Golf has been played here since 1616, making it one of the oldest sites in the game. Old Tom Morris extended the course to 18 holes in 1886. It is the spiritual home of the legendary architect Donald Ross, who was born in Dornoch and served as the club\'s professional before moving to America to design Pinehurst No. 2. Many of Ross\'s design hallmarks-most notably the inverted-saucer greens-originated here.\r\n\r\nThe course is a natural masterpiece, winding along the Dornoch Firth with elevated tees and raised greens that require surgical precision. It has hosted the British Amateur and is a site of pilgrimage for legends like Tom Watson, who famously called it the most fun he\'d ever had on a golf course. With its iconic yellow gorse and white-sand beaches, Dornoch offers a pure, \"timeless\" golfing experience. The club recently opened a magnificent new clubhouse in 2025, ensuring that its off-course facilities now match its world-class fairways.', ''),
('royalmusselburgh', 'Royal Musselburgh', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/royalmusselburgh#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/royalmusselburgh#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 55.951044, -2.998849, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'royalmusselburgh', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe610000001010000007023658ba4fd07c04d874ecfbbf94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Royal Musselburgh Golf Club is the fifth oldest club in the world, with roots dating back to 1774. Originally based on the historic Musselburgh Old Links, the club moved to its current site at Prestongrange in 1926. The course was designed by the prolific James Braid and is a quintessential parkland beauty. It is home to the Old Club Cup, the oldest trophy still competitively played for in the world of golf.\r\n\r\nThe layout is characterized by its lush fairways and mature woodland, offering a sheltered and scenic round. The signature hole is the par-three 14th, known as \"The Gully Hole\" which requires a carry over a deep, 30-foot ravine to a small green. The clubhouse is a stunning 16th-century mansion house that adds a sense of immense history to the day. While it is located at the start of East Lothian\'s \"Golf Coast\" it provides a distinct parkland contrast to the seaside links, maintaining an atmosphere of traditional prestige and community warmth.', ''),
('royaltarlair', 'Royal Tarlair', 'https://royaltarlair.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://royaltarlair.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.669313, -2.472557, 0, 2562, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000008cf7e3f6cbc703c0d2e4620cacd54c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Royal Tarlair Golf Club, located in Macduff, is a spectacular cliff-top parkland-links hybrid. Granted its \"Royal\" status in 1926 by Princess Louise, the course offers some of the most dramatic panoramic views in Aberdeenshire. The layout follows the rugged coastline, with several holes perched precariously above the North Sea. It is a place where the wind is a major factor, and the elevation changes provide a physical and mental test.\r\n\r\nThe signature hole is the 13th, \"Clivet\" an enigmatic par-three played from a high tee over a steep valley to a green nestled on a narrow peninsula below. It is widely considered one of the most stunning and nerve-wracking holes in Scotland. The course is adjacent to the village of Pennan, famous as the setting for the film Local Hero. Royal Tarlair is a friendly, unpretentious club that offers a wild and exhilarating round of golf. It is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense, providing world-class views and unique geological challenges for a fraction of the price of the famous links.', ''),
('royaltroon', 'Royal Troon - Old', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/royaltroon/visitor_home.php', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.532870, -4.649940, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'royaltroon', 1, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000ef7211df899912c080828b1535c44b40, 'links', 'No', 'Royal Troon\'s Old Course is one of the pillars of the Open Championship rotation, having hosted the tournament ten times (most recently in 2024). Designed by Willie Fernie in 1878 and refined by James Braid, it is a traditional \"out and back\" links. The front nine runs south along the coast, offering scoring opportunities, while the back nine turns into the prevailing wind and is widely considered the toughest finishing stretch in championship golf.\r\n\r\nThe course is home to two of the most famous holes in the world: the 8th, \"The Postage Stamp\" the shortest hole in Open golf, and the 11th, \"The Railway\" bordered by the Glasgow-Ayr train line. Legendary moments here include the 2016 \"Duel at Troon\" between Henrik Stenson and Phil Mickelson. Notable members have included giants of Scottish industry and sport. To play Troon is to experience a cathedral of the game-a stern, fair, and profoundly historic links that demands the absolute best from every part of your game.', ''),
('royaltroon9', 'Royal Troon - Craigend', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.532870, -4.649940, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'royaltroon', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ef7211df899912c080828b1535c44b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Craigend Course at Royal Troon is the club\'s high-quality 9-hole par-three course. While it is often used as a practice facility for members and juniors, it is maintained with the same meticulous care as the Old and Portland courses. Each hole is designed to test short-iron accuracy and putting touch, featuring small, well-bunkered greens that reflect the challenges found on the championship tracks.\r\n\r\nThe Craigend is a vital part of the club\'s heritage, providing an accessible gateway for the younger generation to learn the game in a world-class environment. It offers a relaxed and quick round of golf for those who don\'t have time for the full links experience. Located near the main clubhouse, it provides a peaceful and scenic environment to hone one\'s skills. While it lacks the international fame of the Old Course, it remains a favorite for members seeking a quiet \"nine\" in the shadow of the game\'s greatest amphitheaters.', ''),
('royaltroonportland', 'Royal Troon - Portland', 'https://www.brsgolf.com/royaltroon/visitor_home.php', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.532870, -4.649940, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'royaltroon', 3, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000ef7211df899912c080828b1535c44b40, 'links', 'No', 'The Portland Course at Royal Troon is a championship-standard links in its own right, originally designed by Willie Fernie and redesigned in 1921 by the legendary Dr. Alister MacKenzie (the architect of Augusta National). Located slightly further inland than the Old Course, it is more sheltered but no less challenging. It features MacKenzie\'s signature undulating greens and strategic bunkering, requiring a thoughtful approach rather than raw power.\r\n\r\nIf the Portland were located anywhere else, it would be a world-famous destination. Because it sits next to its \"Big Sister\" it remains one of the best-value secrets in Ayrshire. It is a favorite for local amateur championships and is often used by members as their \"daily\" course. Notable for its firm turf and fast greens, the Portland provides a classic links experience without the intimidating length and crowds of the Open venue. It is a \"must-play\" for any MacKenzie enthusiast and offers a masterclass in strategic golf design.', ''),
('Saline', 'Saline', 'https://salinegc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.113010, -3.563094, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003197546d37810cc07c0f971c770e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Saline Golf Club is a hidden parkland jewel located on the slopes of the Saline Hills in Fife. This 9-hole course is renowned for its elevation and the staggering panoramic views it offers, stretching across the Forth Valley to the Lothians and the Ochil Hills. Established in 1912, the course provides a peaceful, \"high-altitude\" golfing experience that feels far removed from the busy coastal links of Fife.\r\n\r\nThe layout is physically demanding due to the hilly terrain, but it rewards the golfer with exhilarating downhill shots and unique architectural quirks. The club is a community-run facility known for its friendly, unpretentious atmosphere. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, it is a favorite for local society outings. Notable for its lush fairways and small, tricky greens, Saline is a \"thinking man\'s\" 9-hole track where accuracy is far more important than power. It is an ideal stop for those looking for a quiet, scenic, and high-value round of golf in the heart of rural Fife.', ''),
('Sanday', 'Sanday', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 59.262329, -2.504383, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000056444df4f90804c06de525ff93a14d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Sanday Golf Club is a rugged and elemental 9-hole links located on the beautiful island of Sanday in the Orkney archipelago. Established in 1897, the course is a throwback to the origins of the game, situated on natural machair land along the shore of Backaskaill Bay. It is a \"natural\" course in the truest sense, where the fairways are grazed by sheep and the hazards consist of sand dunes, wildflowers, and the unpredictable Atlantic wind.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility and serves as the social heart of the island\'s golfing community. While it lacks a professional designer, the routing follows the natural contours of the coast, providing a raw and authentic links experience. Playing Sanday is as much about the environment as the sportit is a place of total silence, interrupted only by the sea and the birds. For the adventurous golfer, it offers a rare opportunity to play the game exactly as it was centuries ago, in a setting of haunting northern beauty.', ''),
('sandyhills', 'Sandyhills', '', '', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.845620, -4.149526, 0, 0, '', '', '', 1425, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000569bff571d9910c0f86bb2463dec4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Sandyhills Golf Club is a premier parkland course located on the eastern edge of Glasgow. Founded in 1905, the course was famously described by golf writer Theodore Moon as \"a piece of Old Troon set down four miles from George Square.\" This 18-hole layout is remarkably well-sheltered from the surrounding city, offering a tranquil and mature environment characterized by its lush fairways and the \"Battle Burn\" which meanders through the property.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong competitive history in the Glasgow and Lanarkshire amateur circuits. Notable for its strategic bunkering and its fast, true greens, Sandyhills is a \"fair\" test that rewards accurate iron play. The course has matured beautifully over the last century, with thick avenues of trees framing every hole. It is a welcoming, professional club that provides a high-quality \"urban oasis\" experience, making it one of the most popular and respected inland venues in the West of Scotland.', ''),
('Sanquhar', 'Sanquhar', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'south', '', 55.363378, -3.936325, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e86a2bf6977d0fc0fe0a992b83ae4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Sanquhar Golf Club is a scenic and historic 9-hole parkland-moorland course located in the Nith Valley in Dumfries and Galloway. Established in 1894, the current layout was designed by the legendary Willie Fernie, the 1883 Open Champion. The course is situated on the hills overlooking the town and the ruins of Sanquhar Castle, providing a dramatic and historic backdrop to the round.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, South of Scotland hospitality and its impeccably maintained greens. For much of its history, the course was shared with grazing sheepa tradition that only ended in the 1970sgiving it a rugged, authentic character. Notable for its challenging par-threes and significant elevation changes, Sanquhar offers a spirited test of golf. It is a traditional club that represents the backbone of Scottish village golf: historic, community-focused, and deeply integrated into the local landscape.', ''),
('scoonie', 'Scoonie', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/scoonie#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/scoonie#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.204829, -2.988577, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'scoonie', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000519fe40e9be807c0dd2230d6371a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Scoonie Golf Club is a beautiful 18-hole municipal course located in the seaside town of Leven, Fife. While it sits near the famous Leven Links, Scoonie offers a distinct parkland challenge. The course was significantly redesigned in 1936 by the legendary James Braid, who brought his signature strategic bunkering and multi-tiered green designs to the layout. It is characterized by its rolling terrain and the Scoonie Burn, which acts as a natural hazard on several holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant membership and is a favorite for local golfers who appreciate the high-quality conditioning and the fast-draining turf. Notable for its \"Braid\" influence, the course requires a thoughtful approach to avoid the deep bunkers and tricky slopes. It offers panoramic views over the Firth of Forth and is widely considered one of the best-value municipal courses in the country. Scoonie provides a polished, professional, and accessible parkland experience in one of the world\'s most iconic golfing regions.', ''),
('scotscraiggolfclub', 'Scotscraig', 'https://www.scotscraiggolfclub.com/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.438607, -2.875595, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.scotscraiggolfclub.com', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000037548cf3370107c0f965304624384c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Scotscraig Golf Club is a world-class championship venue and the 13th oldest golf club in the world, founded in 1817 by members of the St Andrews Society of Golfers. The layout is a unique \"links-heathland\" hybrid, featuring the firm turf of a links course but with gorse and heather-lined fairways more typical of an inland track. Designed by the \"Grand Masters\" Old Tom Morris and James Braid, it has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship for decades.\r\n\r\nThe course is legendary for its small, firm greens and its demanding strategic layout. Notable players who have tackled Scotscraig during Open qualifying include Justin Rose, Ernie Els, and Lee Westwood. It is a prestigious, traditional club where the standards of play and maintenance are among the highest in Scotland. To play Scotscraig is to experience a masterclass in golf architecture; it is an unforgiving, historic, and beautifully presented test of the game that remains a mandatory stop for any serious golfer visiting Fife.', ''),
('seafield', 'Seafield', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/gsaayr#/course/3', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.445177, -4.637195, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'gsaayr', 3, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000eab298d87c8c12c038f7578ffbb84b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Seafield Golf Course is the \"little sister\" to the championship Belleisle course in Ayr. Designed by the legendary James Braid and opened in 1927, Seafield is a shorter, more accessible layout that still features the strategic hallmarks of a Braid design. It is a parkland-links hybrid that runs closer to the shoreline than Belleisle, offering a variety of holes that transition from sheltered woodland to exposed coastal terrain.\r\n\r\nDespite its shorter yardage, Seafield is notoriously tricky, with small greens and narrow fairways that punish the over-ambitious driver. It is maintained to the same high standards as its famous neighbor and is a favorite for those looking for a quick but technically demanding round. The club features a state-of-the-art 1.6 million clubhouse shared with Belleisle. Seafield represents the perfect balance of challenge and charm, providing a high-value golfing experience on the famous Ayrshire coast.', ''),
('selkirk', 'Selkirk', 'https://www.selkirkgolf.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.540386, -2.831412, 0, 2589, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ff03ac55bba606c0ae9b525e2bc54b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Selkirk Golf Club is a \"wee gem\" of a course perched on the hills overlooking the historic Borders town. Established in 1883, the current layout was designed in 1924 by the great Willie Park Jr. (architect of Sunningdale Old). It is a 9-hole moorland course that offers some of the most spectacular views in the Southern Uplands, stretching across the Linglie Hills toward the Ettrick and Yarrow valleys.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its \"hill turf\"firm, springy, and remarkably fast-draining. It is an \"honesty box\" facility that maintains a traditional, unpretentious atmosphere. Notable for its thick heather and the \"Long Hole\" (the 8th), which requires two perfect shots to reach a hidden green, Selkirk is a tactical test of the highest order. It is a peaceful, scenic, and spiritually uplifting place to play, offering a pure connection to the game\'s 19th-century moorland roots.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('Shetland', 'Shetland', 'https://www.shetlandgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 60.166483, -1.225693, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000061fa5e43709cf3bf842ba0504f154e40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Shetland Golf Club, located just outside Lerwick, is the most northerly golf course in the UK. Originally based on the Isle of Bressay, the club moved to its current site at Dale in the 1970s. This 18-hole moorland course is an elemental experience, where the lack of trees means the golfer is entirely exposed to the North Atlantic winds. The layout is rugged and undulating, featuring natural water hazards and the constant presence of the surrounding hills and sea.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the Shetland community and is known for its incredibly warm and welcoming atmosphere. Notable for its \"Midnight Sun\" tournaments in June, where golf is played through the night in the northern \"simmer dim\" the course offers an experience unlike any other in the world. It is a place where you must \"play the ground\" utilizing the contours to navigate the wind. For the adventurous traveler, Shetland Golf Club provides a raw, beautiful, and unforgettable golfing frontier.', ''),
('shiskine', 'Shiskine', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/shiskine', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/shiskine#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.507312, -5.348002, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'shiskine', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000037c5e3a25a6415c0266f8099efc04b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Shiskine Golf & Tennis Club on the Isle of Arran is a global icon and arguably the best 12-hole course in the world. Founded in 1896 and designed by Willie Fernie and Willie Park Jr., the course was originally 18 holes, but six were lost to neglect during WWI. Rather than rebuild them, the club kept the 12 best holes, creating a unique and thrilling \"roller-coaster\" of a round. It is set against the dramatic backdrop of the Drumadoon Cliffs and the Kilbrannan Sound.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its quirks, including several blind shots and the iconic \"Crow\'s Nest\" (the 3rd), a par-three played straight up a cliff face. Notable for its \"pure fun\" factor, Shiskine is a site of pilgrimage for golfers from across the globe. It is an unpretentious, friendly club where the joy of the game takes precedence over a formal scorecard. To play Shiskine is to rediscover why we love golfit is creative, breathtakingly scenic, and completely unique.', ''),
('shotts', 'Shotts', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/shotts#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/shotts#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.828643, -3.780132, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'shotts', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002c8194d8b53d0ec098874cf910ea4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Shotts Golf Club is a rugged and challenging moorland course situated on the high plateau of North Lanarkshire. Established in 1923, the course was designed by the legendary James Braid, who expertly utilized the natural peat and heather of the landscape to create a stern test of golf. Sitting 800 feet above sea level, the course offers panoramic views that, on a clear day, stretch across the Forth Valley to the peaks of the Ochil Hills.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its resilient, \"all-weather\" membership and its remarkably fast-draining turf. Notable for its exposure to the winds, Shotts requires a low, stinging ball flight and a creative short game. It has a prestigious history in the Lanarkshire amateur circuit and is praised for its consistent conditioning. The signature 4th hole, \"The Spectacles\" features two cavernous bunkers that demand a precise carry. It is an honest, traditional club that offers a spirited and physically engaging round of golf, capturing the raw essence of Scottish moorland play.', ''),
('Silverknowes', 'Silverknowes', 'https://www.edinburghleisure.co.uk/venues/silverknowes-golf-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.973069, -3.272039, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000071e481c8222d0ac02fe065868dfc4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Silverknowes Golf Course is a premier municipal links-parkland hybrid located on the shores of the Firth of Forth in Edinburgh. Designed by James Braid and opened in the 1930s, the course offers a high-quality, accessible challenge that has long been a favorite for the city\'s residents. The layout is relatively flat and open, but its primary defense is the unpredictable sea breeze that whips across the exposed fairways.\r\n\r\nAs one of the busiest municipal courses in Scotland, Silverknowes has served as a training ground for thousands of golfers. It has hosted various Lothians County amateur events and is highly regarded for the quality of its greens. The course offers stunning views across to the island of Cramond and the mountains of Fife. Notable for its friendly and bustling atmosphere, Silverknowes provides a \"proper\" links-style test at an affordable price, representing the democratic spirit of the game in the heart of the capital.', ''),
('Skeabost', 'Skeabost', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 57.454606, -6.314115, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006fbbd05ca74119c05e48878730ba4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Skeabost Golf Club on the Isle of Skye is a hidden gem in the truest sense, offering a tranquil and atmospheric 9-hole experience. Situated in the grounds of the historic Skeabost House Hotel, the course winds along the banks of the River Snizort. It is a scenic parkland-moorland hybrid characterized by its lush greenery and the dramatic backdrop of the Skye hills. The river acts as a natural hazard on several holes, requiring a steady nerve on the approach shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its relaxed, \"boutique\" atmosphere, making it a favorite for visitors looking to combine a Highland holiday with a peaceful round of golf. While it lacks the length of a championship course, it is technically demanding, with small, well-protected greens. Notable for its salmon-filled river and its diverse wildlife, Skeabost offers a \"slow-golf\" experience where the beauty of the surroundings is the primary attraction. It is a quiet, soulful place to play, representing the intimate and natural side of island golf.', ''),
('skelmorlie', 'Skelmorlie', 'https://skelmorlie.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', '', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.865343, -4.876762, 0, 2595, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009180d1e5cd8113c04969368fc3ee4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Skelmorlie Golf Club is a spectacular 13-hole moorland course perched on the hills high above the Firth of Clyde. Established in 1891, the course is famous for its panoramic views that stretch from the island of Bute to the mountains of Argyll. Because it consists of 13 holes, a \"full\" round involves repeating five holes from different tees to create an 18-hole loop. The layout is a physical test, featuring significant elevation changes and rugged, natural hazards.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its warm, unpretentious welcome. Braid\'s influence (who advised on the layout in the early 20th century) is evident in the strategic positioning of holes along the ridges. Notable for its springy turf and its exposure to the sea gales, Skelmorlie offers an exhilarating and varied challenge. The signature view from the clubhouse balcony over the estuary is worth the visit alone. It is a traditional club that provides high-value golf with one of the most cinematic backdrops in the West of Scotland.', ''),
('southerness', 'Southerness', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/southerness#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/southerness#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.878960, -3.607340, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'southerness', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000cf6bec12d5db0cc0ff3ee3c281704b40, 'links', 'No', 'Southerness Golf Club is a world-class links located on the remote Solway Coast, designed by the esteemed Philip Mackenzie Ross in 1947. It is frequently ranked as one of the top ten courses in Scotland and is a masterpiece of traditional links design. The course is situated on a coastal plain with no trees to speak of, meaning the golfer is entirely at the mercy of the wind. It has hosted the Scottish Amateur Championship and several prestigious international matches.\r\n\r\nThe layout is characterized by its deep, sod-walled bunkers, narrow fairways, and fast-running turf. Notable for its isolation and its stunning views across the Solway Firth to the English Lake District, Southerness offers a \"pure\" links experience that feels entirely secluded from the modern world. The greens are famously firm and fast, requiring a delicate touch. It is a prestigious and welcoming club that prides itself on maintaining a championship-standard course that tests every facet of a player\'s skill. To play Southerness is to experience one of the great, unsung icons of Scottish golf.', ''),
('SouthRonaldsay', 'South Ronaldsay', 'https://southronaldsaygolf.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 58.824441, -2.962605, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000088ba0f406ab307c0a33d5e4887694d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'South Ronaldsay Golf Club is a charming and elemental 9-hole links-moorland hybrid located on the southernmost island of the Orkney archipelago. Established in 1993, the course is a testament to community spirit, having been built and maintained by local volunteers. It is situated on high ground overlooking the Pentland Firth, providing spectacular views toward the Scottish mainland and the distant peaks of Caithness.\r\n\r\nThe club is an \"honesty box\" facility and is known for its incredibly relaxed and friendly atmosphere. While it lacks a professional architect, the routing is clever, utilizing the natural slopes and rocky outcrops to create a variety of challenging shots. The wind is a constant factor here, often turning a short par-four into a daunting test of endurance. Notable for its tranquility and its connection to the local landscape, South Ronaldsay offers a raw and authentic northern golfing experience. It is a hidden treasure for those who enjoy the simple, unadorned pleasure of the game in a wild and beautiful setting.', ''),
('SpeanBridge', 'Spean Bridge', 'https://speangolf.co.uk/#', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 56.889362, -4.922412, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000076c075c58cb013c00f27309dd6714c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Spean Bridge Golf Club is a scenic 9-hole parkland course located in the heart of the Great Glen, just north of Fort William. Established in 1905, the course offers some of the most dramatic mountain views in the country, sitting in the shadow of the mighty Ben Nevis. The layout is relatively flat and winds through mature trees and along the banks of the River Spean, which provides a natural hazard on several holes.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vibrant hub for the local community and is known for its warm, Highland hospitality. While it is a shorter course, it requires a high degree of accuracy to navigate the narrow fairways and avoid the lush vegetation. Notable for its peaceful, secluded atmosphere and its proximity to the Commando Memorial, Spean Bridge is a favorite for tourists and locals alike. The greens are remarkably true for such an exposed site. It is an honest, traditional club that provides a tranquil and high-value round of golf, capturing the rugged, green spirit of the Highlands.', ''),
('speybay', 'Spey Bay', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/speybay#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/speybay#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.668122, -3.064651, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'speybay', 1, 1, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c53a55be678408c07ade8d0585d54c40, 'links', 'No', 'Spey Bay Golf Club is a rugged and traditional links course situated at the mouth of the River Spey on the Moray coast. Designed by the legendary Ben Sayers in 1907, the course is a \"hidden\" links of exceptional quality. It is characterized by its firm, sandy turf, gorse-lined fairways, and the ever-present threat of the North Sea wind. The course recently came under new ownership (the owners of Cabot Saint Lucia) and is undergoing a high-profile renovation to return it to its former glory.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a classic \"out and back\" links that rewards creative shot-making and a low ball flight. Notable for its incredible wildlife, including dolphins and seals often visible from the shore, Spey Bay offers a sense of total immersion in nature. While it hasn\'t hosted the major pro tours, it is a stalwart of the Northern amateur circuit. The signature holes along the pebble beach are both beautiful and treacherous. It is a welcoming, unpretentious club that offers a raw, atmospheric, and spiritually moving round of links golf in a stunningly wild location.', ''),
('speyvalley', 'Spey Valley', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/speyvalley#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/speyvalley#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.206838, -3.802257, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'speyvalley', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe6100000010100000086e5cfb7056b0ec0f7c8e6aa799a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'Yes', 'Spey Valley Golf Club in Aviemore is a modern championship masterpiece located within the Cairngorms National Park. Designed by the renowned Dave Thomas and opened in 2006, it is one of the longest courses in Scotland, measuring over 7,100 yards from the back tees. The layout is a spectacular parkland-heathland hybrid that winds through ancient Scots pine forests and alongside the River Spey. It is a regular host for the European Challenge Tour\'s Scottish Hydro Challenge.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its scale and its dramatic scenery, featuring the longest par-five in Scotland (the 5th hole, \"The Monster\" measuring 635 yards). Notable for its large, undulating greens and strategic water hazards, Spey Valley is a \"big\" course that rewards power and precision in equal measure. The views of the Cairngorm mountains from every fairway are simply breathtaking. It is a professional, high-gloss resort course that offers a world-class, five-star golfing experience, making it a centerpiece of the Highland golf trail.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/px1roVcOv9s?si=WNBSwMZ7OliGDNTW'),
('standrewsbalgove', 'St Andrews - Balgove', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Balgove Course at St Andrews is the only 9-hole course at the \"Home of Golf\" specifically designed to cater to beginners, juniors, and families. While it sits in the shadow of the world-famous Old Course, the Balgove is maintained to the same exacting standards as the rest of the St Andrews Links Trust estate. It features wide fairways and large bunkers, providing a gentle introduction to the unique challenges of links golf.\r\n\r\nThe course is a vital part of the St Andrews community, serving as the primary training ground for the next generation of local golfers. It offers a relaxed and unpretentious environment where the pressure of the championship courses is absent. Notable for its accessibility and its perfectly manicured turf, the Balgove allows players to experience the \"magic\" of St Andrews without the daunting difficulty of the larger tracks. It is the perfect venue for a fun, stress-free \"nine\" in the heart of the world\'s most famous golfing town, proving that golf for all is a core value of the Links Trust.', ''),
('standrewscastle', 'St Andrews - Castle', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Castle Course is the newest addition to the St Andrews Links Trust, opened in 2008 and designed by David McLay Kidd (the architect of Bandon Dunes). Perched on a rugged cliff-top overlooking the town, it offers a starkly different experience from the traditional links below. It is famous for its massive, rolling undulations and some of the most complex greens in the country. The layout is a visual masterpiece, with the North Sea visible from every hole and the skyline of St Andrews providing a dramatic backdrop.\r\n\r\nThe course has hosted the European Tour\'s St Andrews Bay Championship and is a favorite for those seeking a \"modern-traditional\" challenge. Notable for its 17th hole, a par-three requiring a heroic carry over a yawning chasm of sea and rock, it is a course that demands imagination and a steady nerve. While controversial when it first opened due to its difficulty, it has matured into a prestigious and exhilarating round that provides a thrilling, elevated contrast to the classic seaside tracks of the Auld Grey Toon.', ''),
('standrewsCraigtoun', 'St Andrews - Craigtoun', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Craigtoun Course, located on the high ground overlooking St Andrews, is the only parkland layout in the town. Originally designed by Peter Thomson (five-time Open winner) and later significantly revised by Tim Liddy in 2006, the course offers a \"resort-style\" experience of the highest caliber. It is characterized by its wide-open spaces, rugged bunkering, and a \"heathland\" feel that provides a beautiful alternative to the coastal links.\r\n\r\nOwned by the Old Course Hotel, The Craigtoun has hosted the European Amateur Championship and is a regular venue for elite international events. Notable for its expansive views of the town and the sea, it is a \"big\" course that rewards powerful driving and strategic approach play. The greens are large and fast, and the gorse-lined fairways provide a colorful Highland-edge atmosphere. It is a polished, professional, and tranquil sanctuary that offers a world-class inland round in the world\'s most famous golfing destination.', ''),
('standrewseden', 'St Andrews - Eden', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Eden Course was opened in 1914 to ease the pressure on the Old and New courses, designed by the legendary Harry Colt. Colt brought his signature strategic bunkering to the links, creating a layout that is shorter than its neighbors but arguably more technical. It is characterized by its small, well-guarded greens and several significant water hazards, including the Eden Estuary which comes into play on the early holes.\r\n\r\nThe club has a vibrant social scene and is a favorite for local medals and visiting societies. Notable for its \"traditional links\" feel without the intimidating length of a championship track, the Eden requires a high degree of accuracy off the tee. It has hosted various Scottish regional tournaments and remains a vital part of the St Andrews Links Trust estate. It is the perfect course for the \"thinking\" golfer who appreciates the subtleties of Colt\'s design and wants to experience the magic of St Andrews in a slightly more relaxed environment.', ''),
('standrewsjubilee', 'St Andrews - Jubilee', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The Jubilee Course is often cited by locals as the most difficult of all the St Andrews links. Originally opened in 1897 to commemorate Queen Victoria\'s Diamond Jubilee, it was a 12-hole course before being extended and eventually redesigned in 1988 by Donald Steel into a championship-standard links. It is situated on the narrowest strip of land between the New Course and the sea, featuring deep dunes and narrow fairways.\r\n\r\nThe course has hosted numerous amateur championships and is a regular test for the St Andrews Links Trophy. Notable for its relentless demand for accuracy, especially when the wind whips off the West Sands, the Jubilee provides a \"pure\" links experience that many believe is a truer test of skill than its more famous neighbors. The elevated tees offer stunning views of the estuary and the town. It is a rugged, uncompromising, and beautifully maintained track that represents the very best of modern links architecture in a historic setting.', ''),
('standrewsnew', 'St Andrews - New', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'No', 'The New Course at St Andrews is only \"new\" in name-it was actually opened in 1895. Designed by the \"Grand Old Man of Golf\" Old Tom Morris, it was built to accommodate the increasing demand for golf in the town. It is a classic \"out and back\" links, running parallel to the Old Course, and many purists consider it a more consistent and \"fairer\" test than its more famous sibling. It features traditional gorse-lined fairways, deep bunkers, and fast-running turf.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and shares many of the same views and conditions as the Old Course. Notable for its shared fairways and challenging finishing holes, the New Course is a regular venue for national amateur events. It is a favorite for local members who appreciate the logical flow of Old Tom\'s design. To play the New is to experience the absolute peak of late 19th-century links architecture-it is honest, challenging, and steeped in the traditions of the St Andrews Links Trust.', ''),
('standrewsold', 'St Andrews - Old', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Old Course is the undisputed home of golf, the place where the game was born and where every great champion has walked. Its history stretches back over 600 years. Originally a natural progression across the links land, it was refined by Old Tom Morris and Alister MacKenzie. It is home to the most iconic landmarks in the sport: the Swilcan Bridge, the Road Hole (17th), and the massive double greens that span half an acre.\r\n\r\nMuirfield may be the most \"perfect\" design, but the Old Course is the most \"magical.\" It has hosted The Open Championship 30 times, with winners including Tiger Woods, Jack Nicklaus, and Bobby Jones. Notable members include the entire history of the R&A. To play here is a spiritual experience; the sense of history is palpable as you stand on the 1st tee. It is a public course that belongs to the world, offering a unique, strategic, and profoundly moving round of golf that every player dreams of completing once in their lifetime.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/rrFpmSEUyHw?si=vpca-pUpebzkgo7p'),
('standrewsStrathtyrum', 'St Andrews - Strathtyrum', 'https://standrews.com/homepage', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'fife', '', 56.343684, -2.802423, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003677f4bf5c6b06c049145ad6fd2b4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Strathtyrum Course was opened in 1993 to provide a more accessible and enjoyable links experience for players of all levels. While it is the shortest of the 18-hole courses at St Andrews, it is maintained to the same high standards as the championship tracks. Designed by Donald Steel, the layout features wider fairways and fewer bunkers, making it an ideal choice for a relaxed round or for those looking to build their confidence on links turf.\r\n\r\nThe course is particularly popular with families, seniors, and visitors who want to enjoy the St Andrews atmosphere without the brutal challenge of the Jubilee or the Old. Notable for its large, undulating greens that still require a sharp putting stroke, the Strathtyrum offers a scenic and tranquil environment. It provides a vital balance to the Links Trust\'s portfolio, ensuring that the \"Home of Golf\" remains a destination for everyone. It is a high-quality, friendly, and beautifully presented course that captures the joy of the game in its purest form.', ''),
('stboswells', 'St Boswells', 'https://www.stboswellsgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.stboswellsgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.578031, -2.639543, 0, 2607, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f9156bb8c81d05c07f8978ebfcc94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'St Boswells Golf Club is a charming and historic 9-hole parkland course situated on the banks of the River Tweed in the Scottish Borders. Established in 1899, the course is famous for its idyllic setting and its remarkably well-conditioned greens. The layout winds along the riverbank, with the water providing a beautiful but treacherous hazard on several holes. The mature trees and lush vegetation create a peaceful and sheltered environment.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm Borders hospitality and its vibrant community spirit. While it is a shorter course, the sloping fairways and small greens require a high degree of accuracy and a delicate touch. It has a prestigious history in the Borders Golfers\' Association and is a favorite for local society outings. Notable for its \"village green\" atmosphere and its stunning river views, St Boswells offers a tranquil and high-value round of golf. It is a quintessential Scottish village clubunpretentious, scenic, and deeply traditionaloffering a peaceful escape in one of the country\'s most beautiful regions.', ''),
('stfillans', 'St Fillans', 'https://www.st-fillans-golf.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.390609, -4.106466, 0, 2608, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000338b506c056d10c0fa42c879ff314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'St Fillans Golf Club is a spectacular 9-hole Highland gem located at the eastern end of Loch Earn. Established in 1903 and significantly redesigned in the 1920s by the legendary James Braid, the course is frequently described as one of the most beautiful in Scotland. It is situated in a natural amphitheater of mountains, with the \"Bolfracks\" hills providing a dramatic backdrop. The course is a parkland-moorland hybrid characterized by its lush greenery and the River Earn, which meanders through the property.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious connection to the professional game, being the home course of the legendary Sandy Lyle\'s father, Alex Lyle, who was the professional here for many years. Notable for its peace and seclusion, St Fillans offers a varied and engaging challenge where accuracy is far more important than length. The greens are notoriously true and well-protected. It is a friendly, traditional club that offers a world-class view and a high-quality Braid layout, making it a \"must-play\" for anyone exploring the heart of Perthshire.', ''),
('stirling', 'Stirling', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stirling#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stirling#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.118240, -3.948360, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'stirling', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002ead86c43d960fc01e8a027d220f4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Stirling Golf Club is a prestigious parkland course situated in the historic Kings Park, directly below the magnificent Stirling Castle. Established in 1869, the course was redesigned in the 1920s by the prolific James Braid, who created a layout that rewards both power and precision. The course offers panoramic views of the castle, the Wallace Monument, and the distant peaks of the Trossachs. It is a tactical course characterized by its mature trees and strategic bunkering.\r\n\r\nThe club has a rich history and has hosted many prestigious amateur and professional events, including the Scottish Youths\' Championship. Notable members have included local dignitaries and leaders of the central Scotland professional community. The greens at Stirling are famously consistent and fast, requiring a sharp eye for a read. The signature view of the castle from the 1st tee is one of the most iconic sights in Scottish golf. It is a traditional, professional, and welcoming club that offers a polished and historic parkland experience in the \"Gateway to the Highlands.\"', ''),
('stmedan', 'St Medan', 'https://www.stmedangolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.stmedangolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.724962, -4.539182, 0, 2610, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000145e82531f2812c0df6b088ecb5c4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'St Medan Golf Club is a unique and incredibly scenic 9-hole course located on the shores of Luce Bay in Wigtownshire. Established in 1905, it is famous for its \"18 tees to 9 greens\" layout, which provides a completely different perspective and challenge on the second loop. The course is situated on a peninsula and is a natural links-style track, where the sea is visible from every hole and the wind is a constant factor.\r\n\r\nThe club has a special connection to the author Gavin Maxwell (Ring of Bright Water), who grew up in the area; the club even adopted the otter as its logo in his honor. Notable for its family-friendly atmosphere, St Medan celebrated its centenary in 2005. The signature holes require precise shots over rocky inlets and gorse, with the bronze sculpture of Maxwell\'s otter overlooking the bay from a nearby hill. It is an unpretentious, \"slow-golf\" gem that offers some of the most tranquil and atmospheric coastal play in the South West.', ''),
('stmichaels', 'St Michaels', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stmichaels#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stmichaels#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.387931, -2.902387, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'stmichaels', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000036afeaac163807c0630d17b9a7314c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'St Michaels Golf Club, located just outside St Andrews in Fife, is a high-quality parkland-heathland hybrid with a prestigious architectural pedigree. Originally laid out in 1903 by the legendary Old Tom Morris and Hugh Hamilton, the course was extended to 18 holes in 1996, fulfilling the founders\' original vision. It is situated on the \"Gallow Hill\" and its small, firm greens and narrow fairways are often said to be just as testing as those of its famous neighbors in the Auld Grey Toon.\r\n\r\nThe club is a regular host for Fife County amateur events and is praised for its year-round playability due to its free-draining soil. Notable for its \"St Andrews spires\" views and its proximity to the River Eden, the course features several standout par-threes. It offers a refined, historic, and more affordable alternative to the Links Trust courses, maintaining a traditional atmosphere where the quality of the conditioning is paramount. St Michaels is a \"thinking man\'s\" course that rewards strategy and precision over raw power.', ''),
('stonehaven', 'Stonehaven', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stonehaven#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stonehaven#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 56.980296, -2.187554, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'stonehaven', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000033dfc14f1c8001c02733de567a7d4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Stonehaven Golf Club is one of the most dramatic clifftop courses in Scotland, perched on the \"Braes of Cowie\" overlooking the North Sea. Founded in 1888, the course is unique because it sits directly on the Highland Fault Line, which separates the Highlands from the Lowlands. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and thrilling short holes played over deep, rocky gullies where a mishit ball is lost to the ocean below.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vibrant part of the Aberdeenshire community and was recently ranked in the Top 100 Scottish Courses by Golf World, described as \"brilliant fun.\" Notable for its views of the historic Dunnottar Castle to the south, the course is relatively short (par 66) but notoriously tricky when the sea breeze picks up. It is a traditional, friendly club that provides an exhilarating and visually stunning round of golf, where the dramatic scenery often compensates for a bruised scorecard.', ''),
('Stornoway', 'Stornoway', 'https://stornowaygolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 58.215534, -6.388339, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000009e0b23bda88d19c089963c9e961b4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Stornoway Golf Club, located in the grounds of Lews Castle on the Isle of Lewis, is the premier 18-hole course in the Outer Hebrides. While the club was instituted in 1890legend suggests it may have been laid out by Old Tom Morris during a \"missionary journey\" to the islandsthe current layout was constructed in 1947 by John R. Stutt. It is a lush, wooded parkland course that provides a stark and beautiful contrast to the rugged moorland and machair links typically found in the Western Isles.\r\n\r\nThe club is the heart of the Hebridean golfing scene and is known for its incredibly warm island hospitality. Notable for its shelter provided by the castle\'s mature woodland, it offers a more tranquil playing experience than the wind-blasted coastal tracks. The course has hosted the Western Isles Open and is a regular venue for regional championships. With its panoramic views of Stornoway Harbour and the Minch, it offers a sophisticated and scenic round of golf that highlights the diverse landscape of the Outer Hebrides.', ''),
('stranraer', 'Stranraer', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stranraer#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/stranraer#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.925110, -5.068350, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'stranraer', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f5b9da8afd4514c0ed9925016a764b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Stranraer Golf Club holds a significant place in history as the final course designed by the legendary James Braid before his death in 1950. Situated on the shores of Loch Ryan, the course is a championship-standard parkland layout that offers spectacular views over the water to Ailsa Craig and the Isle of Arran. Braid utilized the undulating terrain to create a strategic masterpiece that rewards thoughtful positioning off the tee.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious tournament pedigree, frequently hosting national amateur events and regional PGA Scotland pro-ams. Notable for its lush conditioning and the \"Creachmore Burn\" that meanders through the property, Stranraer is a \"fair\" but stern test of golf. The signature 5th hole is often cited as one of the best par-fours in the country. It is a professional and welcoming club that offers a \"Tour-standard\" experience in a setting of exceptional natural beauty, representing Braid\'s enduring architectural legacy.', ''),
('strathaven', 'Strathaven', 'https://www.strathavengc.com/', 'competition2', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'intelligent', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.686910, -4.068040, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.strathavengc.com', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000084471b47ac4510c0cea5b8aaecd74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathaven Golf Club is a premier parkland course in Lanarkshire, originally laid out as a 9-hole track by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie. It was extended to a full 18 holes in 1965 with design work by John R. Stutt. The course has matured into one of the best parkland venues in the West of Scotland, characterized by its tight, tree-lined fairways and exceptionally well-manicured greens.\r\n\r\nThe club has a long history of hosting top-tier tournaments, including the 2021 Scottish Girls\' Amateur Championship. Notable for its challenging \"tunnel\" fairways and strategic bunkering, Strathaven is a course that demands accuracy from start to finish. The 16th hole, a 462-yard par-four through mature woodland, is widely considered one of the toughest tests in the region. It is a vibrant, friendly club that offers a polished and high-quality golfing experience just a short drive from Glasgow.', ''),
('StrathclydePark', 'Strathclyde Park', 'https://www.slleisureandculture.co.uk/info/244/strathclyde_park_golf_course', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.782431, -4.034189, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000002288f370022310c03430f2b226e44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathclyde Park Golf Course is a popular 9-hole municipal facility located within the Strathclyde Country Park in Hamilton. The course occupies a unique position, bordered by the Hamilton Racecourse on one side and a nature reserve on the other. It is a classic parkland layout featuring mature woodland and open fairways, providing a gentle but engaging challenge for golfers of all skill levels.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal facility operated by South Lanarkshire Leisure, it is a vital entry point for the game in the local community. Notable for its proximity to the Strathclyde Park Family Golf Centre, which features a 24-bay floodlit driving range, it offers a comprehensive environment for practice and play. While it doesn\'t boast a celebrity architect, the course is well-regarded for its condition and its tranquil, green setting. It is the perfect venue for a quick, affordable \"nine\" in a scenic urban park environment.', ''),
('strathendrick', 'Strathendrick', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/strathendrick#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/strathendrick#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.055338, -4.445225, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'strathendrick', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004772f90fe9c711c0ef1cca5015074c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathendrick Golf Club is a beautiful and historic 9-hole parkland course situated on the banks of the River Endrick near Killearn. Designed in 1901 by the legendary Willie Fernie, the course is perched on an elevated site that offers breathtaking panoramic views of Ben Lomond, the Luss Hills, and the Campsies. The layout is undulating and features many natural hazards, requiring the use of every club in the bag.\n\nThe club is famous for its quaint, \'C\' Listed pavilion clubhouse which dates back to the club\'s founding. Notable for its high-quality fairways and its friendly, welcoming atmosphere, Strathendrick is a favorite for visitors looking for a traditional \"village\" golfing experience. While it is a shorter course, the varying layout and the presence of the river ensure that it remains a stern test for even expert players. It is a peaceful and scenic gem that captures the lush, green essence of the Stirlingshire countryside.', ''),
('strathlenegolfclub', 'Strathlene', 'https://www.strathlenegolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'clubv1', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.690954, -2.923126, 0, 2629, '', '', '', 1214, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c8b260e28f6207c02b85402e71d84c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathlene Buckie Golf Club is a historic clifftop links course that dates back to 1877, making it one of the oldest clubs in Scotland. Located on the Moray Firth coast, the course is a unique hybrid that combines ancient links features with modern design elements (it was extended to 18 holes in 1936). The layout is routed around a central dune ridge and features tumultuous terrain, elevated greens, and spectacular sea views.', ''),
('strathmore', 'Strathmore', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/strathmore#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/strathmore#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'perthshire', 'Yes', 56.600784, -3.219977, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'strathmore', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000040fa264d83c209c0e3fa777de64c4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathmore Golf Centre, located in the heart of the Strathmore Valley near Alyth, is a premier 27-hole facility that opened in 1996. The main Rannaleroch Course was designed by John Salvesen (a former R&A Captain) and is a championship-standard parkland-heathland hybrid. Known as \"The Friendly Place to Play Golf\" the centre has won numerous awards, including Scotland\'s Best Golf Course (Under 75) at the 2022 Scottish Golf Tourism Awards.\r\n\r\nThe Rannaleroch layout is minimalist in style, working with the natural rolling farmland to create a variety of challenges, including a notable water carry on the par-five 5th hole. The facility also features the 9-hole Leitfie Links, which is ideal for juniors and beginners. Notable for its world-class conditioning and its modern, inclusive atmosphere, Strathmore has quickly become a cornerstone of the Perthshire golf scene. It offers a professional, high-value, and welcoming experience that caters to every level of the game.', ''),
('StrathpefferSpa', 'Strathpeffer Spa', 'https://strathpefferspagolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.591633, -4.543377, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000299831056b2c12c0001e51a1bacb4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathpeffer Spa Golf Club is frequently hailed as the \"hidden gem of the Highlands.\" Established in 1888, the course was designed by two of the most significant figures in golf history: Willie Park Jr. (the 1887 and 1889 Open Champion) laid out the first nine, and Old Tom Morris completed the 18-hole extension a decade later. Perched on a high ridge overlooking the Victorian spa village, the course offers breathtaking panoramic views over the Cromarty Firth and the peaks of Ben Wyvis.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its extreme elevation changes, providing a physical and tactical challenge. Notable for its natural, rugged conditioning, the layout feels like a step back into the late 19th century. Legendary commentator Peter Alliss famously praised its scenic beauty. While the course is relatively short, its defense lies in the undulating terrain and small, tricky greens. It is a traditional and welcoming club that offers a \"venerable\" golfing experience where you can walk the same fairways as the founders of the professional game.', ''),
('strathtay', 'Strathtay', 'https://www.strathtaygolfclub.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'perthshire', '', 56.661461, -3.774089, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f88bd99255310ec02c4a09c1aa544c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Strathtay Golf Club is a picturesque and tranquil 9-hole parkland course set in the heart of Highland Perthshire. Originally laid out in 1909 by Captain Steuart of Ballechin, the course remained largely unchanged for a century until nine additional tees were added in 2008 to celebrate its centenary. This \"9 holes, 18 tees\" layout provides a varied experience, with the elevated tees offering stunning vistas of the Tay Valley and the surrounding peaks.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its peaceful environment and the exceptional condition of its greens. Each tee marker provides a small snippet of the club\'s history, making a round here a delightful journey through time. Notable for its lush fairways and mature woodland, Strathendrick offers a classic \"village\" golf experience. It is a friendly, community-focused club that prides itself on its inclusive atmosphere, making it a favorite for both locals and visitors looking for a high-quality, stress-free round in a world-class landscape.', ''),
('stromness', 'Stromness', 'https://www.stromnessgc.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 58.952160, -3.302209, 0, 2633, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000075745c8dec6a0ac09947fe60e0794d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Stromness Golf Club, founded in 1890, is a unique and imaginative seaside parkland course located at the southern entrance to the historic Orkney harbor town. The course offers spectacular views across to the islands of Hoy and Graemsay, as well as the world-famous Scapa Flow. One of its most distinctive features is that the routing actually takes players over and around WWII gun emplacements and underground bunkers, serving as a living memorial to the region\'s strategic military history.\r\n\r\nWhile relatively short (just over 4,800 yards), the tight and tricky layout provides a stern test of accuracy. Notable for its \"turn up and play\" policy, the club is known for its incredibly relaxed and friendly atmosphere. The course is a focal point for the local community and is particularly scenic during the \"simmer dim\" (the long Northern summer twilight). It is a \"must-play\" for those visiting Orkney, offering a blend of sport, history, and stunning maritime scenery that is truly one-of-a-kind.', ''),
('swanston', 'Swanston', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/swanston#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/swanston#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.892256, -3.222655, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'swanston', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b9533a58ffc709c074d4d17135f24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Swanston Golf Club, located at the foot of the Pentland Hills in Edinburgh, has a fascinating historyit was founded in 1927 as a ladies-only course. Due to high demand from the members\' husbands, it was soon opened to men and expanded to 18 holes. The course underwent a major modernization in 2006 and further improved in 2016 by incorporating two spectacular holes from the defunct Lothianburn course. The result is a challenging, hilly parkland-moorland hybrid with panoramic views over the city of Edinburgh and the Firth of Forth.\r\n\r\nThe club has a professional and forward-thinking atmosphere, featuring a world-class academy and a modern, family-friendly clubhouse. Notable for its high-quality conditioning and its commitment to junior development, Swanston is a regular host for regional amateur championships. It is a favorite for those seeking a physically engaging round with a \"countryside\" feel just minutes from the city center. It is a traditional club with a modern outlook, providing a polished and scenic golfing experience in the shadow of the Pentlands.', ''),
('swanstontemplar', 'Swanston Templar', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/swanstontemplar#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/swanstontemplar#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.893710, -3.216980, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'swanstontemplar', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b1169f0260bc09c0d80ddb1665f24b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Templar Course at Swanston is a dedicated 9-hole par-three course that serves as the \"nursery\" for the club\'s thriving academy. Named after the Knights Templar (who had strong historical ties to the nearby area), the course was built to provide a high-quality environment for beginners, juniors, and those looking to refine their short game. Despite its shorter yardage, the course features tour-standard greens and strategic bunkering that reflect the challenges found on the main 18-hole track.\r\n\r\nThe Templar is maintained with the same meticulous care as the championship course, ensuring a high-quality experience for all users. It is a vital asset for the Swanston Golf Academy, which is one of the premier teaching facilities in the Lothians. Notable for its inclusive atmosphere and its role in growing the game, the course offers a quick and enjoyable \"nine\" that is perfect for a post-work round. It represents the club\'s dedication to accessibility, making golf at the foot of the Pentlands an option for players of all skill levels.', ''),
('tain', 'Tain', 'https://tain.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://tain.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'highlands', 'Yes', 57.812810, -4.043130, 0, 0, '', '', 'tain', 753, '', 0, 1, 'c', 0xe61000000101000000eae74d452a2c10c04eee77280ae84c40, 'links', 'No', 'Tain Golf Club is a \"Northern Jewel\" designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris in 1890. Situated on the shores of the Dornoch Firth, it is an 18-hole links course that offers a subtle and challenging masterpiece of early architecture. It is famously the neighbor of Royal Dornoch, and many golfers consider the two courses to be the perfect \"Highland double.\" Tain is characterized by its firm, sandy turf, gorse-lined fairways, and the \"Alps\" hole (the 11th), where a blind approach is played over a massive ridge.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious history and has hosted the Scottish Women\'s Championship and the Columbo Cup (since 1897). Notable for its proximity to the Glenmorangie Distillery, the course offers a sensory experience of sea air and malt whisky. The 17th hole, \"Black Bridge\" features a meandering river that adds a dramatic water hazard to the final stretch. Tain is a refined, historic, and incredibly welcoming club that offers world-class links golf with a fraction of the crowds found on the more famous Open tracks.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('tarbert', 'Tarbert', 'https://tarbertgolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.860296, -5.435679, 0, 2638, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004837c2a222be15c09770e82d1eee4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tarbert Golf Club is a delightful and friendly 9-hole course located in the picturesque village of Tarbert, Argyll. Established in 1898, the course has occupied several sites before settling into its current hilltop location in the 1930s. Originally laid out by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, the course is a moorland-parkland hybrid that offers stunning views of the surrounding hills and the sea.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its unpretentious \"honesty box\" atmosphere and its incredibly warm welcome for visitors. While the course is short, its defense lies in the narrow fairways and the significant elevation changes that require precise club selection. Notable for its peaceful, secluded setting, Tarbert is a quintessential \"Argyll gem\" where the focus is on the simple enjoyment of the game. It is the perfect venue for those looking to experience the rugged beauty of the West Coast in a relaxed and traditional setting.', ''),
('tarland', 'Tarland', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/tarland#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/tarland#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.128994, -2.845875, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'tarland', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000003108ac1c5ac406c0abb019e082904c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tarland Golf Club is an enchanting 9-hole parkland masterpiece located in the heart of Royal Deeside. Founded in 1908 and designed by the legendary Old Tom Morris, the course is often described as a \"centennial jewel.\" It is meticulously maintained and features a layout that rewards accuracy over length. The signature view from the 8th fairway offers a panoramic vista across the Dee Valley to the majestic Lochnagar mountain.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its traditional Scottish hospitality. While a 9-hole track, the use of multiple tees for a \"medal\" 18-hole round provides a varied and challenging test. Notable for its lush, wooded environment and its serene atmosphere, Tarland has won numerous awards for its conditioning and value. It is a \"must-visit\" for anyone touring the Aberdeenshire Highlands, offering a pure connection to the architectural legacy of Tom Morris in a setting of exceptional natural beauty.', ''),
('taynuilt', 'Taynuilt', 'https://www.taynuiltgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 56.432193, -5.240248, 0, 2641, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b7b75b9203f614c0b247a81952374c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Taynuilt Golf Club is a spectacular 9-hole parkland course situated on the shores of Loch Etive, dominated by the towering peak of Ben Cruachan. Established in 1987 and officially opened in 1991 by the legendary Sir Michael Bonallack, the course has quickly gained a reputation as one of the best 9-hole tracks in the country. The layout is undulating and winds along the banks of the River Nant, which frames the final hole.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its friendly, \"volunteer-run\" spirit and its remarkably well-conditioned turf. Notable for its picture-postcard views, Taynuilt offers a challenging round where the small greens and natural water hazards keep players on their toes. It is a regular host for the Argyll and Bute regional championships. For those traveling through the West Highlands, Taynuilt provides a peaceful and visually stunning golfing sanctuary that captures the green, rugged spirit of the landscape.', ''),
('TheRenaissanceClub', 'Renaissance', 'https://trcaa.com/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'eastlothian', '', 56.051427, -2.811122, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'b', 0xe610000001010000006687f8872d7d06c0d190f12895064c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'The Renaissance Club in East Lothian is one of the most prestigious modern additions to the \"Home of Golf.\" Established in 2008 and designed by the acclaimed Tom Doak, it is a world-class links that blends contemporary luxury with traditional architectural values. Since 2019, the club has been the permanent home of the Scottish Open, hosting the world\'s best players, including Rory McIlroy and Xander Schauffele.\r\n\r\nThe course is a tactical masterpiece, featuring Doak\'s signature large, undulating greens and strategic bunkering that utilizes the natural landscape. The \"cliff-edge\" stretch (holes 9 through 11) offers breathtaking views of the Firth of Forth. Notable for its exclusive atmosphere and its \"Tour-standard\" conditioning, The Renaissance Club represents the pinnacle of modern Scottish golf. While it is a private club, it offers limited visitor access, providing a rare opportunity to play a course that has become a cornerstone of the professional international circuit.', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/Ud3ilD08u0w?si=05SFz8ZZa9EIASAA'),
('thornhill', 'Thornhill', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/thornhill#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/thornhill#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'south', 'Yes', 55.245850, -3.748760, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'thornhill', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000766c04e275fd0dc05ddc4603789f4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'While the coastal links often steal the spotlight, Thornhill Golf Club in Dumfriesshire offers a masterclass in the \"hidden gem\" category. Established in 1893, the course is a captivating hybrid of parkland and heathland, set against the dramatic, panoramic backdrop of the Southern Uplands. The original nine-hole layout was designed by the 1883 Open Champion Willie Fernie, a man whose architectural influence touched the likes of Royal Troon and Turnberry. It wasn\'t until 1979 that the course was expanded to its current 18-hole championship status, a project led by a dedicated club committee that seamlessly integrated Fernie\'s historic holes with modern terrain.\r\n\r\nThornhill\'s most famous son is undoubtedly Andrew Coltart, the former Ryder Cup player and multiple European Tour winner. Coltart honed his game on these very fairways as a junior, and his success brought a sense of international prestige to this quiet corner of Scotland. The club also boasts a rich history of professional talent, including Marshall Douglas, a Nigerian Open winner and longtime club professional who was eventually made an honorary life member for his 50-year association with the club.\r\n\r\nThe course itself is celebrated for its playability and conditioning. Unlike many hilly inland courses, Thornhill sits on relatively level ground, making it an \"easy walk\" without sacrificing tactical depth. The signature challenge lies in its narrow, tree-lined fairways and the subtle undulations of its greens. It frequently hosts prestigious regional events like the Southwest of Scotland Championship, consistently proving that a course doesn\'t need to be on the coast to provide a world-class Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('thornton', 'Thornton', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/thornton#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/thornton#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'fife', 'Yes', 56.167239, -3.125897, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'thornton', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ec504d49d60109c0d1ce691668154c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Thornton Golf Club is a beautiful parkland gem located in the heart of Fife, established in 1921. The course is situated on the banks of the River Ore, which acts as a natural and often treacherous hazard on several holes. The layout is characterized by its mature woodland and remarkably flat terrain, making it an easy and enjoyable walk for golfers of all ages. Despite its lack of elevation, Thornton is notoriously tricky, with narrow fairways and well-protected greens.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its warm, Fife hospitality. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, it has a reputation for being one of the best-maintained inland tracks in the county. Notable for its peaceful, secluded atmosphere and its diverse wildlife, Thornton offers a \"hidden\" golfing experience away from the busy coastal links. The 18th hole, playing back toward the traditional clubhouse, provides a classic finish. It is a friendly, unpretentious club that offers a high-value and technically demanding round of golf in a tranquil setting.', ''),
('thurso', 'Thurso', 'https://thursogolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.579673, -3.560454, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000904c874ecf7b0cc0e6af90b9324a4d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Thurso Golf Club holds the distinction of being the most northerly golf course on the British mainland. Established in 1893, the course offers a rugged and atmospheric moorland-links hybrid experience. The layout is perched on high ground overlooking the town and the Pentland Firth, providing spectacular views toward the Orkney Isles and the towering cliffs of Dunnet Head.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vital part of the Caithness community and is known for its incredibly warm and unpretentious welcome. While it lacks a \"celebrity\" architect, the natural routing is a masterclass in utilizing the wind-swept landscape to create a variety of challenging shots. Notable for its firm, springy turf and its exposure to the fierce Atlantic gales, Thurso requires a creative array of \"low-ball\" shots. It is an \"honesty box\" facility that represents the very soul of northern golfwild, scenic, and deeply connected to the elements. For those traveling the North Coast 500, Thurso is an essential and spiritually moving stop.', ''),
('tillicoultry', 'Tillicoultry', 'https://tillicoultry.hub.clubv1.com/visitors/TeeSheet', '', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.154741, -3.750359, 0, 0, '', '', 'tillicoultry', 1690, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f9122a38bc000ec0d82c978dce134c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tillicoultry Golf Club is a spectacular and historic 9-hole moorland course situated on the slopes of the Ochil Hills. Established in 1899, the course offers panoramic views across the Forth Valley to the peaks of the Southern Uplands. It is a \"mountain-style\" layout characterized by steep climbs and thrilling downhill shots, requiring a good level of fitness and a creative approach to the various blind shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its friendly, community-focused atmosphere and its traditional clubhouse. While it is a shorter course, the natural hazards of heather and gorse, combined with the significant elevation changes, ensure that it remains a stern test for even expert players. Notable for its peaceful, elevated setting, Tillicoultry provides a spirited and challenging round of golf that captures the rugged beauty of the Stirlingshire countryside. It is an honest, traditional club that offers high-value golf with a view that is truly breathtaking.', ''),
('tobermory', 'Tobermory', 'https://www.tobermorygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.tobermorygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.627817, -6.065796, 0, 2653, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000099d4d006604318c0b96fb54e5c504c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tobermory Golf Club on the Isle of Mull is frequently described as one of the most scenic 9-hole courses in the world. Established in 1896, the course is perched on the cliffs high above the iconic colorful harbor of Tobermory. The layout is a rugged moorland hybrid that offers breathtaking views across the Sound of Mull to the mountains of Ardnamurchan. It is a physical test, featuring significant elevation changes and natural hazards like rocky outcrops and thick heather.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its incredibly relaxed, \"island-style\" hospitality and its \"honesty box\" policy. While it lacks the length of a championship course, it is technically demanding, with small greens nestled into the hillside. Notable for its peace and seclusion, Tobermory offers a \"slow-golf\" experience where the beauty of the surroundings is the primary attraction. It is a quiet, soulful place to play, representing the intimate and natural side of Hebridean golf. To play here is to experience the game as it was over a century agosimple, beautiful, and completely unique.', ''),
('torphins', 'Torphins', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/torphins#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/torphins#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.112240, -2.630797, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'torphins', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000bd512b4cdf0b05c0caa65ce15d8e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Torphins Golf Club is a charming and historic 9-hole parkland-moorland hybrid located in the heart of Royal Deeside. Established in 1896, the course is perched on a hillside overlooking the village and the surrounding Aberdeenshire hills. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and its lush, well-manicured fairways. The surrounding woodland and the backdrop of the Grampian mountains provide a tranquil and stunning setting for a round of golf.\r\n\r\nThe club is a vital part of the local community and is known for its warm, Deeside hospitality. While it is a shorter course, it requires a high degree of accuracy to navigate the sloping fairways and small, tricky greens. Notable for its peaceful, secluded atmosphere and its commitment to traditional values, Torphins offers a \"boutique\" golfing experience that captures the natural beauty of the region. It is the perfect venue for those looking for a quick, scenic, and high-value round of golf in one of Scotland\'s most beautiful and historic valleys.', ''),
('TorranceHouse', 'Torrance House', 'https://torrancehousegc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.748559, -4.144589, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000047289230f9410c0301004c8d0df4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Torrance House Golf Club is a premier 18-hole municipal parkland course located in East Kilbride, Lanarkshire. Developed in the 1960s around the historic 17th-century Torrance House, the course has matured into a scenic and testing facility. The layout winds through mature woodland and features several significant elevation changes, providing a varied and engaging challenge. It has a strong competitive history and frequently hosts Lanarkshire County amateur events.\r\n\r\nAs a municipal facility, Torrance House is known for its inclusive and friendly atmosphere. While it is a relatively long course, it is an easy walk and offers wide fairways that encourage bold driving. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and its strategic bunkering, it is widely considered one of the best-value public courses in the country. The signature view of the historic house from the 18th fairway provides a dramatic finish to the round. It is a cherished community asset that represents the \"people\'s game\" in a setting of exceptional natural beauty.', ''),
('torwoodlee', 'Torwoodlee', 'https://torwoodlee.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://torwoodlee.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.636706, -2.836634, 0, 0, '', '', '', 2894, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f8c5a52a6db106c05f950b957fd14b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located just north of Galashiels, Torwoodlee Golf Club offers a golfing experience that is uniquely intertwined with the history of the Scottish Borders. Established in 1895, the course is a majestic rolling parkland paradise set within a valley flanked by the River Gala. Its most distinctive modern feature is the Borders Railway line, which bisects the course. Golfers transition between the lower riverside holes and the higher, hillier terrain via a refurbished footbridge, watching the trains glide past as they navigate the 5,935-yard layout.\r\n\r\nThe architectural lineage of Torwoodlee is a prestigious tapestry. The original nine-hole layout was the work of two-time Open Champion Willie Park Jr., whose influence remains visible in the flatter holes near the river. In 1925, the legendary James Braid was brought in to suggest vital improvements, and later, the course was expanded to a full 18 holes by architect John Garner in time for the club\'s centenary in 1995. This blend of styles created a course of two halves: the technical, tree-lined challenges of the original grounds and the more expansive, dramatic vistas of the newer section.\r\n\r\nTorwoodlee is frequently cited as one of the friendliest clubs in Scotland, often winning \"Freedom of the Fairway\" awards for its hospitality. While it maintains a peaceful atmosphere, it is a serious test of golf, regularly hosting the Border Golfers\' Association championships and prestigious regional Opens. The signature 6th hole, \"Bowland View,\" offers a spectacular tee shot that plunges from the course\'s highest point, providing a view of the Borders countryside that is worth the green fee alone.', ''),
('traigh', 'Traigh', 'https://www.traighgolf.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 56.939960, -5.853270, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000b6a1629cbf6917c02ac6f99b50784c40, 'links', 'No', 'Traigh Golf Club is often cited as the most beautiful 9-hole course in Scotland. Located on the \"Road to the Isles\" near Arisaig, the course is situated on a series of sandy dunes overlooking the white beaches of Traigh and the islands of Rum, Eigg, and Muck. Established in 1900 and redesigned in the 1990s by John Salvesen, the layout is a natural links masterpiece that flows seamlessly with the rugged coastline.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its incredibly relaxed atmosphere and its stunning sunsets. While it is a shorter course, the wind off the Atlantic and the natural hazards of the dunes ensure that it remains a stern test of skill. Notable for its isolation and its cinematic views, Traigh offers a raw, elemental connection to the origins of the game. To play here is to rediscover why we love golfit is creative, breathtakingly scenic, and spiritually moving. It is a \"must-visit\" for any adventurous golfer traveling through the West Highlands.', ''),
('troondarley', 'Troon Darley', 'https://www.troonlinksgolf.com/#main-content', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.542543, -4.652507, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f0a485cb2a9c12c03dd68c0c72c54b40, 'links', 'No', 'While its neighborsRoyal Troon and Old Prestwickboast global fame and Open Championship history, Troon Darley is whispered about by locals as the most brutal test in the region. Situated on the same stretch of prime links land as its illustrious sisters, Darley is a municipal masterpiece managed by Golf South Ayrshire. It is a traditional links course that trades the sprawling scale of a championship venue for a tight, claustrophobic challenge. At roughly 6,300 yards, it isn\'t the longest course in the area, but its fairways are notoriously narrow, hemmed in by a relentless \"army\" of gorse, heather, and deep bunkers that swallow anything less than a perfect strike.\r\n\r\nThe course was officially established in 1911 as the third public course in Troon, originally known as Troon Municipal No. 1. While the specific architect is often attributed to the collective efforts of early club professionalsincluding the influence of Willie Fernie, who designed so much of the Troon landscaperecent years have seen a revitalization. In 2024, the club announced a major masterplan involving Pangaea Golf Architecture and 1999 Open Champion Paul Lawrie to enhance the layout while preserving its \"tough as nails\" reputation.\r\n\r\nHistorically, Darley has served as a proving ground for future legends. It was one of the courses used for Final Open Qualifying in 1962, the year a young Jack Nicklaus qualified for his first-ever Open Championship. Today, it remains a venue for prestigious amateur events like the Cunningham Rosebowl and the Victory Cup. For many golfers, a par at Darley is more satisfying than a birdie elsewhere, as it demands a level of strategic discipline that would make even the most seasoned pro sweat.', ''),
('troonfullartor', 'Troon Fullarton', 'https://www.troonlinksgolf.com/#main-content', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.542543, -4.652507, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f0a485cb2a9c12c03dd68c0c72c54b40, 'links', 'No', 'Troon Fullarton: The Short and Shrewd \"Inland Links\"\r\nWhile its neighbors are often described as grueling tests of endurance, Troon Fullarton offers a refreshing change of pace that emphasizes finesse over raw power. Managed by Golf South Ayrshire, this par-64 layout is frequently referred to as an \"inland links.\" Though it sits slightly further back from the Firth of Clyde than the championship courses, it retains the firm, sandy turf and undulating fairways characteristic of the region. The course architect, much like the other municipal links in Troon, is rooted in the early 20th-century work of Willie Fernie, the 1883 Open Champion who helped shape the golfing identity of the entire town.\r\n\r\nFullarton is the shortest of the three Troon municipal courses, but its defense lies in its small, tricky greens and strategically placed bunkers. It is the perfect venue for \"honing the short game,\" a sentiment echoed by many professionals who grew up in the area. While it hasn\'t hosted the Open Championship, it serves as an essential entry point for the \"Troon Links\" experience, often used by visitors as a warm-up before tackling the more intimidating Darley or Lochgreen. Its brisk pace of play and welcoming atmosphere make it a favorite for local juniors and seniors alike, maintaining a community-focused charm that contrasts with the high-pressure environment of the nearby private clubs.', ''),
('troonlochgreen', 'Troon Lochgreen', 'https://www.troonlinksgolf.com/#main-content', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'ayrshire', '', 55.542543, -4.652507, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000f0a485cb2a9c12c03dd68c0c72c54b40, 'links', 'No', 'Troon Lochgreen stands as the undisputed \"Big Brother\" of the Troon municipal courses. Extending to over 6,800 yards, it is a formidable par-74 that offers a fascinating hybrid of traditional links and lush parkland holes. The course\'s history is legendary; it was primarily designed by Willie Fernie, though its reputation as a championship-quality venue was cemented when it was utilized as a Final Open Qualifying site. The most famous moment in its history occurred in 1962, when a 22-year-old Jack Nicklaus successfully navigated the Lochgreen fairways to qualify for his very first Open Championship, launching one of the greatest careers in the history of the sport.\r\n\r\nThe course is unique for its \"two-faced\" personality. The opening and closing sections feel like a classic coastal linksexposed to the wind and requiring low, stinging shotswhile the middle section ducks behind the dunes into a more sheltered, tree-lined parkland setting. This variety has made it a perennial favorite for prestigious amateur tournaments, including the Scottish Amateur Championship. Lochgreen is often cited as the \"best value\" round in Scotland, providing a professional-grade challenge on the same hallowed turf shared by Royal Troon, but with the accessible, egalitarian spirit of a public course.', ''),
('trumpnew', 'Trump International - New', 'https://www.trumpgolfscotland.com/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'trumpAberdeen', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.277429, -2.020530, 19063, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000eeb1f4a10b2a00c022fb20cb82a34c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Opened in 2025, the MacLeod Course is the much-anticipated second 18-hole layout at the Trump International estate in Aberdeenshire. Designed to complement the world-renowned \"Old Course\" this new masterpiece was brought to life by Eric Trump and a specialist team of architects at Golflink Evolve, including Esie O\'Mahoney and Jamie O\'Reilly. Named after the President\'s mother, Mary Anne MacLeod, the course is woven through the same colossal, \"cathedral-like\" dunes of Balmedie. It is a modern links that pushes the boundaries of traditional design, featuring the largest natural sand bunker in the world and sweeping wetlands that provide a dramatic, rugged aesthetic.\r\n\r\nThe course\'s debut was nothing short of historic, with the opening ceremony attended by Donald J. Trump and major figures from the golf world, including Ryder Cup captain Paul McGinley and PGA Champion Rich Beem. While the Old Course is a relentless championship test, the MacLeod Course is designed to be more \"playable\" for the everyday golfer while still maintaining its fearsome links pedigree. Together, they form what the club calls \"The Greatest 36 Holes in Golf\" solidifying Aberdeenshire\'s status as a global powerhouse for luxury links golf.', ''),
('trumpold', 'Trump International - Old', 'https://www.trumpgolfscotland.com/', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'trumpAberdeen', '', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.277429, -2.020530, 14851, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe61000000101000000eeb1f4a10b2a00c022fb20cb82a34c40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Located at Balmedie in Aberdeenshire, Trump International is one of the most talked-about modern courses in the world. Designed by Dr. Martin Hawtree and opened in 2012, it is a massive, spectacular links built amidst some of the tallest sand dunes in Europe. The course is a \"modern-traditional\" masterpiece where every hole is secluded from the others by towering ridges of marram grass. It has quickly become a mainstay for elite events and is often cited for its \"Tour-standard\" conditioning.\r\n\r\nThe course is notorious for its difficulty, especially when the North Sea wind channels through the valleys. Notable for its 14th hole, which offers a panoramic view of the coastline, and its \"Great Dunes\" it is a visual and physical test of the highest order. The club features a luxurious, five-star clubhouse and a world-class practice facility. While it is a relatively new addition to the Scottish landscape, it has already established itself as a world-ranking titan that demands every shot in a golfer\'s bag.', ''),
('tulliallan', 'Tulliallan', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/tulliallan#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/tulliallan#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'central', 'Yes', 56.083576, -3.716165, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'tulliallan', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000098512cb7b4ba0dc0815d4d9eb20a4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Situated near the historic village of Kincardine, Tulliallan Golf Club is a masterful example of a woodland parkland course that rewards strategy over brute strength. Originally established in 1902, the course has evolved significantly from its nine-hole roots. It was largely shaped by the legendary James Braid, whose design philosophy of risk-and-reward is evident across the undulating fairways. The layout is famously framed by a dense canopy of ancient oaks and beech trees, which provide a natural amphitheater that shelters the course from the winds common to the nearby Firth of Forth.\r\n\r\nThe club is renowned for its high-profile membership and local prestige, counting several notable Scottish sporting figures and business leaders among its ranks over the decades. It has gained a reputation as a fierce competitive venue, frequently hosting the Scottish Youths\' Championship and various PGA regional events. The signature test at Tulliallan is undoubtedly its greens; often described as \"glass-like\" by visiting professionals, they require a delicate touch and a sharp eye. With views stretching toward the Ochil Hills, it offers a tranquil yet testing escape that feels far more remote than its central location suggests.', ''),
('turnhouse', 'Turnhouse', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/turnhouse#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/turnhouse#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.952320, -3.332282, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'turnhouse', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000005265187783a80ac0d2a92b9fe5f94b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Turnhouse Golf Club is a premier parkland course located on the western outskirts of Edinburgh, near the airport. Established in 1897, the course was significantly redesigned by the legendary James Braid in the 1920s. It is characterized by its rolling terrain, which offers panoramic views of the Fife hills and the Pentland Hills. The layout is famously \"breezy\" due to its elevated position, making the wind a constant and shifting factor.\r\n\r\nThe club has a strong competitive history and has produced several Scottish international players. Notable for its impeccably fast greens and its challenging \"short\" holes, Turnhouse is a regular host for the Lothians County Championships. The course features a variety of tree-lined and open fairways, requiring a versatile approach to shot-making. It is a friendly, professional club that offers a high-quality \"city-fringe\" golfing experience, making it one of the most popular and respected parkland venues in the capital.', ''),
('turriff', 'Turriff', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/turriff#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/turriff#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'No', 56.488275, -3.004707, 0, 0, 'no data', '', '', 0, 'turriff', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000887fd8d2a30908c02a3a92cb7f3e4c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Deep in the heart of \"Castle Country,\" Turriff Golf Club offers a beautifully manicured parkland experience that serves as a lush contrast to the rugged coastlines of the North East. Established in 1896, the course moved to its current location on the banks of the River Deveron in the mid-20th century. The layout was refined by the prolific Archie Simpsona member of the famous Simpson golfing dynasty from Earlsferrywhose architectural touch ensured the course made the most of its gentle slopes and natural water hazards.\r\n\r\nTurriff is a club that punches well above its weight in terms of community and competitive spirit. It is particularly famous for hosting the Turriff Open, an event that draws top-tier amateurs from across Scotland. The course is characterized by its wide, inviting fairways, but the real challenge lies in the closing stretch where the River Deveron looms large, ready to punish any wayward shots. It is a favorite among local professionals for its pristine conditioning, and the club prides itself on a welcoming atmosphere that reflects the traditional hospitality of rural Aberdeenshire.', ''),
('ullapool', 'Ullapool', 'https://www.ullapoolgolfclub.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 57.905839, -5.165650, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000061545227a0a914c07e384888f2f34c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Ullapool Golf Club is a spectacular and scenic 9-hole parkland-links hybrid located on the shores of Loch Broom in the Highlands. Established in 1998 and officially opened by the legendary Prince Andrew, the course offers some of the most dramatic mountain and sea views in the country. The layout is relatively flat and winds along the shoreline, featuring springy turf and several challenging water hazards provided by the loch.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, Highland hospitality and its impeccably maintained greens. Notable for its \"Midnight Sun\" tournaments in June, where golf is played in the long northern twilight, the course offers a unique and memorable experience. It is a favorite for those traveling the North Coast 500 who want a quick, high-quality round in a world-class setting. Ullapool represents the best of modern Highland golfaccessible, scenic, and deeply integrated into the local landscape.', ''),
('uphall', 'Uphall', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/uphall#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/uphall#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.924991, -3.517410, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'uphall', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a4fca4daa7230cc0130ce71a66f64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Uphall Golf Club is a premier parkland course located in West Lothian, established in 1895. The course is situated on the banks of the Broxburn, which acts as a natural and often treacherous hazard on several holes. The layout is characterized by its mature woodland and remarkably well-manicured fairways, offering a sense of total seclusion despite its central location. It has a strong competitive history and frequently hosts West Lothian County amateur events.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its friendly, professional atmosphere and its commitment to high-quality conditioning. Notable for its \"thinking man\'s\" layout, Uphall requires a high degree of accuracy to navigate the narrow, tree-lined corridors and avoid the water hazards. The signature 13th hole, \"The Canal\" requires a steady nerve on the approach. It is a popular venue for society outings and corporate days, offering a polished and engaging parkland experience that remains a cornerstone of the regional golfing scene.', ''),
('valeofleven', 'Vale of Leven', '', '', 'No', 'Yes', '', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.986904, -4.565730, 0, 0, '', '', 'valeofleven', 1784, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000de76a1b94e4312c05325cade52fe4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Vale of Leven Golf Club is a spectacular and historic parkland-moorland hybrid perched on the hills overlooking Loch Lomond. Established in 1907, the course offers panoramic views that stretch from the loch to the peaks of the Southern Highlands. The layout is characterized by its significant elevation changes and its exposure to the breezes, which act as a constant defender of par. It is a tactical course where local knowledge is key to navigating the various blind shots.\r\n\r\nThe club is a focal point of the local community and is known for its unpretentious and welcoming membership. Notable for its fast, true greens and its challenging par-threes, Vale of Leven is a regular host for regional amateur championships. The signature view from the clubhouse over the Leven Valley is one of the most photographed in the region. It is a traditional, well-maintained club that provides a spirited and physically engaging round of golf, capturing the rugged, green spirit of the West Highlands.', ''),
('vaul', 'Vaul', 'https://www.vaulgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.vaulgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 56.528685, -6.792963, 0, 2675, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000090c01f7efe2b1bc0617138f3ab434c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'For those seeking the soul of Scottish golf, Vaul Golf Club on the Isle of Tiree is a pilgrimage worth making. This is golf in its most elemental form, played over the \"machair\"a rare, fertile coastal plain carpeted in wildflowers. While golf was played here by marines as early as 1886, the course was formally laid out in 1911 by professional James Hobbins and later refined with the help of Gordon Lockhart. It is a traditional 9-hole links that captures the \"hassle-free\" spirit of the Hebrides, where sheep often act as the primary greenkeepers.\r\n\r\nThe club lacks the corporate polish of mainland venues, but it compensates with a rich, eccentric history. Its most famous benefactor was Charles McNeil, a wealthy industrialist from Govan who gifted the club its first clubhouse. Today, the course is a favorite of those who appreciate the \"old-fashioned\" game. There are no tee times and few bunkers; instead, the defense is provided by the Atlantic gales and the natural undulations of the dunes. It is a place where you are more likely to encounter a local crofter than a tour pro, offering a raw, beautiful experience that feels like stepping back 100 years in time.', ''),
('wandbgc', 'Wigtown and Bladnoch', 'https://www.wandbgc.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://www.wandbgc.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.864783, -4.450436, 0, 2696, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a4c343183fcd11c082919735b16e4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Wigtown & Bladnoch Golf Club is a scenic and historic 9-hole parkland course situated on the shores of the Solway Firth. Established in 1905, the course offers panoramic views across the Wigtown Bay nature reserve. The layout is characterized by its lush greenery and its proximity to the Bladnoch Distillery, adding a sensory layer of malt whisky to the sea air.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its warm, South West hospitality and its unpretentious atmosphere. While it is a shorter course, the sloping fairways and small greens require a high degree of accuracy. Notable for its peaceful, secluded setting and its commitment to traditional values, it is a favorite for visitors exploring the \"Book Town\" of Wigtown. It is a quintessential Scottish village club that provides a tranquil and high-value round of golf in a setting of exceptional natural beauty.', ''),
('WeeBraids', 'Wee Braids', 'https://www.edinburghleisure.co.uk/venues/wee-braids-golf-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'edinburgh', '', 55.913546, -3.179761, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000022c50089267009c020b24813eff44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Perched atop the Braid Hills with stunning views over the Edinburgh skyline and the Firth of Forth, the Wee Braids is the charming, shorter sibling to the famed No. 1 course. While the No. 1 course is a long, arduous hike, the Wee Braids offers a brisk 9-hole (traditionally 18-hole) par-3 and par-4 experience that captures the same wild, gorse-heavy character. Though the architect of the original No. 1 was Peter McEwan, the evolution of the Braids estate has seen the hands of many great Scots. The Wee Braids is the quintessential \"Edinburgh nursery\" where generations of city golfersincluding potentially the young Tommy Armourfirst learned the game.\r\n\r\nThe course is famous for its natural, unmanicured beauty; there are no artificial bunkers, as the thick gorse and rocky outcrops provide all the hazards one could need. It is a democratic sanctuary of golf, where the lack of a formal \"famous member\" list is replaced by its status as a breeding ground for the city\'s amateur legends. Despite its shorter length, the elevation changes and swirling winds make it a surprisingly technical test, proving that you don\'t need 7,000 yards to have a memorable Scottish golfing experience.', ''),
('westerngailes', 'Western Gailes', 'https://westerngailes.com/book-a-tee-time/', 'https://westerngailes.com/book-a-tee-time/', 'No', 'No', '', '', 'mon,tue,wed,thu,fri,sat,sun', 'ayrshire', '', 55.581694, -4.663210, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 1, 'a', 0xe610000001010000004985b18520a712c0c423f1f274ca4b40, 'links', 'Yes', 'Western Gailes is widely regarded as one of the finest and most authentic links courses in the world. Founded in 1897 by a group of Glasgow golfers seeking a winter escape from the city fog, the course is sandwiched between the railway line and the sea. Its architectural pedigree is elite, having been refined by Willie Park Jr. in 1912. Unlike many courses that run \"nine out and nine back,\" Western Gailes features a clubhouse positioned centrally, with the holes looping out in both directions along a narrow strip of classic Ayrshire dunes.\r\n\r\nThe club\'s history is a roll call of golfing royalty. It has hosted nearly every major amateur and professional event in the country, including the Curtis Cup, the Scottish Amateur, and it served as a Final Open Qualifying venue for decades. Legends like Harry Vardon, Gene Sarazen, and Tom Watson have all praised its layout. Famous members and honorary figures include Ryder Cup hero Bernard Gallacher. The course is a relentless test of ball-striking, especially when the \"Ayrshire Breeze\" blows off the Firth of Clyde, making every par feel like a significant achievement.', ''),
('Westerwood', 'Westerwood', 'https://www.thewesterwoodhotel.co.uk/golf/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.968165, -3.978878, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000ec3026fdbdd40fc0e010aad4ecfb4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Westerwood Golf & Spa Resort in Cumbernauld features a modern championship course designed by the legendary Seve Ballesteros and Dave Thomas. Opened in 1989, the layout is a spectacular parkland-moorland hybrid that winds through silver birch and pine forests. It is famous for its \"Signature\" 15th hole, a par-three played over a deep, heather-filled ravine to a green carved into the hillside.\r\n\r\nThe course is notorious for its challenging bunkering and its large, undulating greens that reflect Seve\'s creative flair. Notable for its world-class resort facilities, Westerwood is a favorite for corporate golf days and national amateur qualifiers. It offers a \"Tour-standard\" experience where the wind off the surrounding hills adds an extra layer of difficulty. It is a polished, high-gloss destination that provides a visually stunning and technically demanding round in the heart of the central belt.', ''),
('westhill', 'Westhill', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westhill#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westhill#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'aberdeen', 'Yes', 57.159796, -2.291706, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'westhill', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000356090f4695502c00c04013274944c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Established in 1977, Westhill Golf Club is a vibrant, community-focused parkland course located just a few miles west of Aberdeen. Unlike the ancient links of the coast, Westhill is a product of modern Scottish golf, designed to provide a challenging yet accessible layout for the growing local population. The course was a collaborative effort, with the original design being refined over the years to include strategic bunkering and the introduction of water hazards, most notably the pond at the par-5 5th hole. Its location offers breathtaking panoramic views across the valley toward the peaks of Royal Deeside.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its friendly, inclusive atmosphere rather than a roster of aristocratic members. However, it has become a respected venue for regional Aberdeenshire tournaments and is a staple for the North East District circuit. The layout is characterized by its hilly terrain, which requires thoughtful club selection and a fair bit of stamina. The signature hole is the \"Hole O\' the Hill\" where the elevation change offers a exhilarating tee shot. It stands as a testament to the success of Scotland\'s 20th-century \"golf for all\" movement.', ''),
('westkilbride', 'West Kilbride', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westkilbride#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westkilbride#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'ayrshire', 'Yes', 55.692369, -4.877920, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'westkilbride', 1, 1, 'c', 0xe610000001010000006c04e275fd8213c0d2e1218c9fd84b40, 'links', 'No', 'West Kilbride Golf Club is a hallowed links masterpiece located on the Ayrshire coast. Founded in 1893 and significantly redesigned by the legendary James Braid, the course is a traditional \"out and back\" links that hugs the shoreline of the Firth of Clyde. It offers spectacular, uninterrupted views across to the Isle of Arran and the Ailsa Craig. The layout is characterized by its firm, sandy turf, deep bunkers, and the ever-present sea breeze.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious tournament history, frequently hosting the Scottish Girls\' Championship and serving as a qualifying venue for the Open. Notable for its fast, true greens and its challenging middle stretch through the dunes, West Kilbride is a \"pure\" links experience of the highest order. It is a refined and welcoming club that maintains a strong sense of its 19th-century heritage. For those seeking an authentic, championship-standard links round with a world-class backdrop, West Kilbride is an essential and rewarding stop.', ''),
('westlinton', 'West Linton', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westlinton#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/westlinton#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.718011, -3.341692, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'westlinton', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004c70ea03c9bb0ac08995d1c8e7db4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'High on the slopes of Slipperfield Hill, West Linton Golf Club is a stunning moorland course that feels like the roof of the world. Founded in 1890 by local schoolmaster Robert Millar, the course saw significant refinement in 1926 from the legendary James Braid. Braid\'s influence is felt in the way the holes interact with the natural undulations of the heather-clad landscape. It remained a 9-hole course until 1972 when it was expanded to a full 18-hole championship layout. The air here is thin and crisp, and the views of the Pentland Hills provide one of the most serene backdrops in the Lothians.\r\n\r\nThe club boasts a proud list of honorary members, including Ryder Cup legend Bernard Gallacher and 1988 Masters Champion Sandy Lyle, who officially opened the current clubhouse. It is also the home club of Simon Mackenzie, a former Scottish Amateur Champion. West Linton is a member of the James Braid Golf Trail and is a regular host for national amateur qualifying events. The course is a fair but stern test, where the wind and the thick heather act as the primary defenders of par, demanding accuracy over distance.', ''),
('westlothian', 'West Lothian', 'https://westlothian.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'https://westlothian.hub.clubv1.com/Visitors/TeeSheet', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.997955, -3.599993, 0, 0, '', '', 'westlothian', 1623, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a5a14621c9cc0cc099f04bfdbcff4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'West Lothian Golf Club is a premier hillside parkland course located near Bo\'ness. Established in 1892, the course offers some of the most expansive views in the central belt, stretching across the Firth of Forth to the Ochil Hills and the mountains of the Southern Highlands. The layout is a tactical masterpiece characterized by significant elevation changes and mature woodland.\r\n\r\nThe club has a prestigious tournament history, frequently hosting the Scottish Mid-Amateur Championship and regional PGA Scotland events. Notable for its impeccably fast, sloping greens and its \"thinking man\'s\" routing, it requires a creative approach to avoid the deep bunkers. The signature 14th hole, \"The Airngath\" offers a dramatic tee shot with a backdrop that is among the most photographed in the region. It is a professional and welcoming club that provides a polished and physically engaging round of golf.', ''),
('westray', 'Westray', '', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 59.321640, -2.998913, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000dc645419c6fd07c0f08ae07f2ba94d40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'For the true adventurer, Westray Golf Club on the Orkney Islands represents the edge of the golfing world. Formally established in 1899, it claims the unique title of being the most north-westerly golf course in Great Britain. This 9-hole links course is pure, raw golf. It was originally laid out by local enthusiasts and the Pierowall Hotel owner, George Mackay, over the \"machair\" land of the North Links. There is no famous architect here; instead, the course was shaped by the Atlantic Ocean and the grazing of local livestock, which still keep the fairways short today.\r\n\r\nThe club is a \"hidden gem\" in the truest sense. While it doesn\'t host professional tours, its annual Westray Open is a highlight of the island social calendar, drawing players from across the Orkneys. The course is famously challenging due to its exposure to the North Sea galesplaying here requires a \"low ball\" and a high degree of patience. With the sound of crashing waves and the sight of puffins nearby, Westray offers a spiritual connection to the game\'s origins that few mainland courses can replicate.', ''),
('whalsay', 'Whalsay', 'https://www.whalsaygolfclub.co.uk/website/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'islands', '', 60.379384, -0.924985, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000444c89247a99edbf1650a8a78f304e40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Whalsay Golf Club holds the title of the most northerly 18-hole golf course in the British Isles. Located on the \"Bonnie Isle\" of Whalsay in Shetland, the course is an elemental experience perched on the edge of the Atlantic. The layout is a rugged moorland links where there are no trees to block the wind; instead, you are surrounded by dramatic sea cliffs, peat bogs, and the constant sound of the ocean.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its incredibly warm Shetland welcome and its \"Midnight Sun\" tournaments. Notable for its isolation and its cinematic views of the northern isles, Whalsay requires a masterclass in low-ball flight and imagination. The turf is remarkably springy and fast-draining despite the harsh climate. For the adventurous golfer, Whalsay offers a raw, beautiful, and unforgettable golfing frontier that marks the literal edge of the sport in the UK.', '');
INSERT INTO `clubs` (`id`, `name`, `bookingLink`, `openBookingLink`, `onlineBooking`, `openBooking`, `bookingSystem`, `openBookingSystem`, `availabilityDays`, `region`, `working`, `lat`, `lon`, `courseId`, `clubId`, `reason`, `baseUrl`, `clubv1hub`, `clubv1opencourseid`, `brsDomain`, `brsCourseId`, `top100`, `category`, `location`, `coursetype`, `image`, `description`, `youtube`) VALUES
('Whitecraigs', 'Whitecraigs', 'https://www.whitecraigsgolfclub.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.787468, -4.310286, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006aa0f99cbb3d11c0c1525dc0cbe44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Located in the affluent southern suburbs of Glasgow, Whitecraigs Golf Club is a prestigious parkland course with an incredible historical resume. Established in 1905, the original design was the work of Willie Fernie, the 1883 Open Champion. In the 1930s, the \"King of Architects\" James Braid, was brought in to remodel several holes, creating the sophisticated layout that exists today. The course is characterized by its rolling fairways, mature woodlands, and impeccably conditioned greens that have earned it a reputation as one of the finest inland courses in Scotland.\r\n\r\nWhitecraigs\' place in history was cemented when it hosted the US Ryder Cup teams in 1929 and 1933, featuring legends like Walter Hagen and Gene Sarazen, who practiced here before their matches. In 1983, the \"Golden Bear\" Jack Nicklaus visited the club, further adding to its storied legacy. Today, the club continues to host high-level events, including the World Professional Senior\'s Golf Championship. It remains a bastion of traditional Scottish club life, blending a rich, competitive history with a lush, serene environment that feels miles away from the city center.', ''),
('Whitecraigswee', 'Whitecraigs - Wee', 'https://www.whitecraigsgolfclub.net/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'glasgow', '', 55.787468, -4.310286, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000006aa0f99cbb3d11c0c1525dc0cbe44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Tucked away within the grand estate of the main club, the Whitecraigs Wee Course is a 9-hole par-3 layout that is often described as one of the most enchanting walks in Glasgow. While the \"Big Course\" takes the headlines, the Wee Course is meticulously maintained to the same exacting standards, featuring a recently installed professional irrigation system. It serves as the perfect \"nursery\" for the club\'s thriving junior section and a tranquil alternative for members looking for a quick round in a beautiful garden-like setting.\r\n\r\nThe Wee Course lacks the intimidating length of its sibling but compensates with tricky, small greens that require a precise wedge game. It is a vital part of the Whitecraigs ecosystem, ensuring that the game remains accessible to all ages and skill levels. Many of the club\'s champions began their journey on these nine holes. It is a place of quiet beauty, framed by colorful rhododendrons and ancient trees, offering a peaceful sanctuary where the focus is purely on the joy of the short game.', ''),
('whitehillhouse', 'Whitehill House', 'https://whitehillhouse.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://whitehillhouse.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'edinburgh', 'Yes', 55.846347, -3.125164, 0, 2692, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000a417b5fb550009c0ab08371955ec4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Set within the grounds of a magnificent A-listed Tudor-Jacobean mansion in Midlothian, Whitehill House Golf Course is a unique 20-hole par-70 layout. Designed by the acclaimed John Chilver Stainer, the course is famously difficult, often described as a \"formidable test\" even for low-handicappers. Stainer\'s design philosophy here was to use the natural steep-sided valleys and deep gorges of the estate to create high-drama golf. The signature hole, \"Ramsay\'s Revenge\" requires a heart-stopping carry over a deep ravine to an elevated green.\r\n\r\nWhile the house itself dates back to the 1840s (designed by David Bryce), the golf course is a more modern addition that has quickly gained a \"cult\" reputation for its difficulty. It doesn\'t host standard tour events, but it is a favorite for corporate days and serious amateurs looking to test their mettle. The experience at Whitehill House is as much about the architecture of the building as it is the course; finishing a round under the shadow of the towering stone chimneys provides a sense of Victorian grandeur that is rare in modern golf.', ''),
('whitingbay', 'Whiting Bay', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/whitingbay#/course/1', '', 'Yes', 'No', 'brs', '', '', 'islands', 'Yes', 55.490171, -5.100359, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'whitingbay', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000e36f7b82c46614c04b395fecbdbe4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Overlooking the Firth of Clyde on the Isle of Arran, Whiting Bay Golf Club is a spectacular hill-top course that offers some of the most breathtaking views in Scottish golf. Established in 1895, the club is a member of the exclusive \"1895 Club\" association. The course was originally a 9-hole layout before being expanded. While no single \"superstar\" architect is credited with its entire modern form, it was developed by local enthusiasts who understood the unique topography of the island. It is a hybrid of moorland and parkland, with fairways that climb and dive through the rugged Arran landscape.\r\n\r\nThe club is the heartbeat of the local community and is famous for its warm \"Arran welcome.\" While it may not have the Open Championship history of the mainland, it has produced numerous local champions who have excelled in the Arran Golf Championship. The course is notorious for its \"blind shots\" and sloping lies, requiring a creative approach and a steady putter. It is a course that doesn\'t just test your swing, but your legs as well, rewarding those who reach the highest points with a view of the Holy Isle that is simply unforgettable.', ''),
('wick', 'Wick', 'https://www.wickgolfclub.org.uk/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 58.483025, -3.127601, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000c37e4fac530509c0401361c3d33d4d40, 'links', 'No', 'Perched on the edge of the Sinclair\'s Bay, Wick Golf Club holds the distinction of being the oldest established club in the Highlands, dating back to 1870. The current 18-hole layout on the Reiss Links was designed by the legendary John Sutherland, the long-time secretary of Royal Dornoch and a towering figure in Scottish golf history. Sutherland utilized the natural \"run of the land\" to create a traditional out-and-back links that is often cited as the most northerly championship-quality course on the British mainland.\r\n\r\nWick\'s history is defined by its rugged resilience. One of its most famous early members and presidents was Sheriff Thoms, a key figure in spreading the game across the North of Scotland. The course is famous for its \"Midnight Tournament,\" traditionally held on the longest day of the year, where golfers tee off in the eerie twilight of the Highland summer. Having hosted the Scottish North District Championships many times, it is a course that demands respect, particularly at the par-3 holes which are often played directly into the biting North Sea wind. It is a true \"hidden gem\" for anyone navigating the North Coast 500.', ''),
('wigtownshirecountygolfclub', 'Wigtownshire County', 'https://wigtownshirecountygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://wigtownshirecountygolfclub.com/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'south', 'Yes', 54.865213, -4.829894, 0, 2697, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000259694bbcf5113c07a89b14cbf6e4b40, 'links', 'No', 'Wigtownshire County Golf Club, located at Glenluce, is a premier 18-hole links course situated on the shores of Luce Bay. Established in 1894, the course is a traditional links characterized by its firm turf, sandy dunes, and the constant presence of the sea breeze. It has a prestigious history and has served as a Final Qualifying venue for the Open Championship in the past.\r\n\r\nThe layout is a classic \"out and back\" links that rewards creative shot-making and a low ball flight. Notable for its incredibly fast greens and its challenging middle stretch through the gorse, the \"County\" is widely regarded as one of the best-value links in Scotland. The ruins of Glenluce Abbey provide a dramatic backdrop to several holes. It is a refined and welcoming club that offers a \"pure\" and historic links experience, making it a centerpiece of the South West golf trail.', ''),
('williamwood', 'Williamwood', 'https://www.williamwoodgc.co.uk/', '', 'No', 'Yes', 'clubv1', 'clubv1', '', 'glasgow', 'No', 55.797723, -4.274297, 0, 0, '', '', 'williamwood', 874, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004b901150e11811c02d228ac91be64b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Founded in 1906, Williamwood Golf Club is a classic James Braid-designed parkland course located on the south side of Glasgow. Braid\'s signature stylestrategic bunkering and the clever use of natural landformsis evident throughout the 18 holes. In recent years, the course has been further enhanced by architect Graeme Webster, ensuring that it remains a modern championship test while preserving Braid\'s original vision. The layout is remarkably lush and \"green\" offering a quiet, parkland escape in a densely populated suburban area.\r\n\r\nWilliamwood has long been a hub for elite amateur golf in the West of Scotland. It is a regular host for Glasgow County events and has a reputation for producing exceptionally talented young players. The course is defined by its par-4s, many of which require a shaped shot off the tee to navigate the mature treelines. The club is also famous for its high-tech practice facilities, including an indoor simulator, bridging the gap between its early 20th-century heritage and the modern game. It is a course that rewards the \"thinking golfer\" who can navigate its subtle doglegs and tiered greens.', ''),
('windyhill', 'Windyhill', 'https://windyhillgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://windyhillgolfclub.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.934926, -4.366266, 0, 2699, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000058c2e6f0e7711c00d17b9a7abf74b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Sitting 500 feet above sea level on the slopes of the Kilpatrick Hills, Windyhill Golf Club lives up to its name. Established in 1908, the course was designed by the prolific James Braid, who made excellent use of the rugged, undulating terrain. The elevation provides staggering viewson a clear day, you can see the peaks of Ben Lomond to the north and the city of Glasgow to the south. Because of its height and exposure, the wind is a constant factor, turning a relatively modest 6,000-yard layout into a grueling test of flight control.\r\n\r\nWindyhill\'s most famous member is undoubtedly the legendary Janice Moodie, a two-time Solheim Cup winner and LPGA star who grew up playing these hills. The course has hosted the Scottish Ladies\' Championship and numerous professional Pro-Ams, consistently challenging the best in the business with its heavy gorse and tricky, sloping fairways. It is a \"working man\'s\" championship course, known for its grit and its incredibly friendly, down-to-earth membership. To play well at Windyhill, you must embrace the elements and master the art of the \"knockdown\" shot.', ''),
('winterfield', 'Winterfield', 'https://winterfield.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'https://winterfield.cw.sct.dotgolf.co.uk/Teebooking/SearchSlots.aspx', 'Yes', 'No', 'dotgolf', 'dotgolf', '', 'eastlothian', 'Yes', 56.003332, -2.536632, 0, 2700, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe6100000010100000086e5cfb7054b04c0e083d72e6d004c40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Winterfield Golf Club in Dunbar is a spectacular 18-hole links-parkland hybrid that offers some of the most dramatic coastal views in East Lothian. Established in 1935, the course is situated on a headland overlooking the Firth of Forth and the Bass Rock. It is a \"natural\" course characterized by its significant elevation changes and its exposure to the fierce North Sea gales.\r\n\r\nThe club is known for its friendly, community-focused atmosphere and its proximity to the historic town center. Notable for its signature 1st holea par-three played straight toward the oceanWinterfield provides a spirited and exhilarating test. While shorter than its championship neighbors, its defense lies in the wind and the tricky, sloping greens. It is an honest, traditional club that offers a wild and visually stunning round of golf, representing the \"fun\" side of the East Lothian links experience.', ''),
('wishaw', 'Wishaw', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/wishaw#/course/1', 'https://visitors.brsgolf.com/wishaw#/course/1', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'brs', 'brs', '', 'glasgow', 'Yes', 55.782340, -3.933240, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, 'wishaw', 1, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000658d7a8846770fc0232d95b723e44b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Wishaw Golf Club is a historic parkland course in North Lanarkshire with roots dating back to 1894. The current layout was designed in 1935 by the legendary James Braid after the club moved to its present site at Foggielea. It is a quintessential Braid design, making expert use of the natural undulations to create a strategic and fair test of golf. The course is characterized by its mature tree-lined fairways and exceptionally true, undulating greens.\r\n\r\nThe club has a long-standing reputation for its high-quality conditioning and its welcoming, family-oriented atmosphere. Notable for its \"humps and hollows\"a classic Braid featureit requires a sharp short game to navigate the tricky surrounds. While it sits within a busy part of the central belt, the course feels remarkably secluded and offers lovely views of the surrounding countryside. It is a traditional club that takes great pride in its heritage, offering a polished and engaging parkland round that remains a favorite in the Lanarkshire golfing circuit.', ''),
('woll', 'Woll', 'https://www.wollgolf.co.uk/visitorbooking/', 'competition2', 'Yes', 'Yes', 'intelligent', 'intelligent', '', 'borders', 'Yes', 55.483322, -2.847816, 0, 0, '', 'https://www.wollgolf.co.uk', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe610000001010000004c3448c153c806c0fab7cb7eddbd4b40, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'The Woll Golf Course, located at the New Woll Estate in Ashkirk near Selkirk, is one of the most popular and modern golfing destinations in the Scottish Borders. Originally opened as a 9-hole course in 1993, it was expanded to a full 18-hole championship layout by 2004. It is a beautiful parkland course that follows the contours of the Ale Valley, featuring water hazards on several holes, including a spectacular 17th hole where the green is almost entirely surrounded by water.\r\n\r\nThe club is famous for its \"Play, Stay, and Eat\" concept, featuring luxury self-catering cottages and an award-winning restaurant. Notable for being voted into the Top 100 Golf Course Society Venues in the UK, it offers a high-gloss, resort-style experience. The greens are built to USGA specifications, ensuring excellent year-round playability. The Woll is known as \"The Friendliest Course in the Borders\" providing a high-value, professional, and scenic round of golf that is a mandatory stop for anyone touring the south of Scotland.', ''),
('Woodlands', 'Woodlands', 'https://www.woodlands.scot/golf-course/', '', 'No', 'No', '', '', '', 'highlands', '', 51.544600, -2.540788, 0, 0, '', '', '', 0, '', 0, 0, 'd', 0xe61000000101000000d28db0a8885304c068b3ea73b5c54940, 'nonlinks', 'No', 'Woodlands Golf Course, often referred to as The Dragon\'s Tooth, is a world-renowned 9-hole masterpiece located at the foot of Glencoe. Situated on the shores of Loch Linnhe, the course is shadowed by the majestic peaks of Sgorr Dhearg and Sgorr Dhonuill. It has been ranked by Golf Magazine as one of the Top 50 9-hole courses in the world and is widely considered the best 9-hole track in Scotland.\r\n\r\nThe layout features USGA-specification greens and a design that is both visually stunning and technically demanding. Notable for its dramatic elevation changes and the \"Dragon\'s Tooth\" mountain backdrop, it offers a \"boutique\" golfing experience of the highest order. The club operates on a relaxed \"turn up and play\" basis and features a charming clubhouse with an honesty bar. For any golfer traveling through the Highlands, Woodlands provides a raw, beautiful, and spiritually moving round of golf that captures the very essence of the Scottish landscape.', '');
